agnijaara|अग्निजार
Tatpur. m. (-रः) A medicinal plant. See अग्निज. E. अग्नि and जार. 

agnijaala|अग्निजाल
Tatpur. m. (-लः) A medicinal plant. See अग्निज. E. अग्नि and जाल.

agnijihvaa|अग्निजिह्वा
Tatpur. f. (-ह्वा)<BR> ^1 A tongue of Agni, a flame of fire. (There are seven tongues of Agni. See हिरण्या, कनका, रक्ता, कृष्णा, वसुप्रभा, अतिरक्ता, बहुरूपा).<BR> ^2 A medicinal plant. See लाङ्गली and लाङ्गलिकी. E. अग्नि and जिह्वा.

agnijvaalaa|अग्निज्वाला
Tatpur. f. (-ला)<BR> ^1 A flame of fire.<BR> ^2 A plant bearing red blossoms used by dyers (Grislea tomentosa, Rox.).<BR> ^3 Another plant, commonly Jalapippalí. E. अग्नि and ज्वाला, from the fiery colour of its blossoms.

agnitejas|अग्नितेजस्
Bahuvr. I. m. f. n. (-जाः-जाः-जः) Having the power of Agni or fire. <BR>II. m. (-जाः) Name of a son of Pulaha, one of the seven Ŕishis during the reign of the 11th (a future) Manu. E. अग्नि and तेजस्.

agnitraya|अग्नित्रय
Tatpur. n. (-यम्) The aggregate of the three fires &c. See अग्नित्रेता. E. अग्नि and त्रय.

agnitretaa|अग्नित्रेता
Tatpur. f. (-ता) The aggregate of the three fires maintained by the Brahman householder, viz. the Gárhapatya, Áhavaníya and Dakshińa, qq. vv. E. अग्नि and त्रेता.

agnida|अग्निद
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-दः-दा-दम्)<BR> ^1 Setting on fire, incendiary.<BR> ^2 Supplying with fire.<BR> ^3 Stomachic, tonic, digestive. E. अग्नि and द.

agnidagdha|अग्निदग्ध
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-ग्धः-ग्धा-ग्धम्) Burnt with fire. <BR>II. m. pl. (-ग्धाः) The name of a particular class of Pitŕis or Manes, of such who when alive, kept up the household flame and presented oblations with fire. E. अग्नि and दग्ध. In the latter sense it would seem that the word has been taken as a Bahuvríhi.

agnidatta|अग्निदत्त
Tatpur. m. (-त्तः) The name of a prince. E. अग्नि and दत्त.

agnidamanii|अग्निदमनी
Tatpur. f. (-नी) A medicinal plant of narcotic properties (Solanum jacquini). See कण्ठकारिका. E. अग्नि (bile) and दमनी (what tames).

agnidish|अग्निदिश्
Tatpur. f. (-दिक्) The south-east quarter, of which Agni is the regent. E. अग्नि and दिश्.

agnidiipana|अग्निदीपन
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-नः-नी-नम्) Producing appetite, stomachic. E. अग्नि and दीपन.

agnidiipta|अग्निदीप्त
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-प्तः-प्ता-प्तम्)<BR> ^1 Blazing, on fire.<BR> ^2 Digestive. <BR>II. f. (-प्ता) The name of a plant. See महाज्योतिष्मती. E. अग्नि and दीप्त.

agnideva|अग्निदेव
I. Karmadh. m. (-वः) Agni, the god of fire. <BR>II. Bahuvr. 1. m. (-वः) A worshipper of fire. 2. f. (-वा) A name of the third lunar mansion, identified with the Pleiades: Agni being the ruling deity of the constellation. Also अग्निदेवता. E. अग्नि and देव.

agnidevatya|अग्निदेवत्य
m. f. n. (-त्यः-त्या-त्यम्) Belonging or referring to the divinity of Agni or fire. (This word occurs also, but less correctly, in the form of अग्निदैवत्य). E. अग्निदेवता, taddh. aff. यत्.

agnidaivata|अग्निदैवत
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Belonging to Agni as divinity, referring to the divinity of Agni. E. अग्नि and दैवत.

agnidaivatya|अग्निदैवत्य
m. f. n. (-त्यः-त्या-त्यम्) See अग्निदेवत्य.

agninaxatra|अग्निनक्षत्र
Tatpur. n. (-त्रम्) The third lunar mansion. E. अग्नि and नक्षत्र. 

agninayana|अग्निनयन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) See अग्निप्रणयन. E. अग्नि and नयन.

agniniryaasa|अग्निनिर्यास
Tatpur. m. (-सः) The name of a plant, also अग्निजार. E. अग्नि and निर्यास.

agnipakva|अग्निपक्व
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-क्वः-क्वा-क्वम्) Cooked or dressed with fire. E. अग्नि and पक्व.

agnipada|अग्निपद
Tatpur. n. (-दम्) The name of a plant. (?) E. अग्नि and पद.

agniparichChada|अग्निपरिच्छद
Tatpur. m. (-दः) The implements and apparatus used in oblations to fire. E. अग्नि and परिच्छद.

agniparidhaana|अग्निपरिधान
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Surrounding the sacrificial fire with the paridhis (see परिधि) or wooden frames covered with skin. E. अग्नि and परिधान.

agnipariixaa|अग्निपरीक्षा
Tatpur. f. (-क्षा) Ordeal by fire, as formerly practised by walking through it, or as subsequently practised, by dipping the hand into boiling oil, holding a heated iron &c. E. अग्नि and परीक्षा.

agniparvata|अग्निपर्वत
Tatpur. m. (-तः) A volcano. E. अग्नि and पर्वत.

agnipraNayana|अग्निप्रणयन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Carrying forth the sacrificial fire, a ceremony occurring in several sacrifices, as in the Jyotisht́oma, the Darśapúrńamása, the Cháturmásya. It consists in taking the fire from the Práchínavanśa (q. v.) Mand́apa, a building erected in the centre of the Dárśikí Vedi (q. v.) and carrying it to the Ágnídhra (q. v.) Mand́apa, which stands in the Saumikí Vedi (q. v.). E. अग्नि and प्रणयन.

agnipravesha|अग्निप्रवेश
Tatpur. m. (-शः) Entering the fire, esp. self immolation by a widow upon the pyre of her deceased husband. E. अग्नि and प्रवेश. Also अग्निप्रवेशन n. (-नम्).

agniprastara|अग्निप्रस्तर
Tatpur. m. (-रः) Fire-stone, flint, or any stone producing fire. E. अग्नि and प्रस्तर.

agnibaahu|अग्निबाहु
Tatpur. m. (-हुः) See अग्निवाहु.

agnibha|अग्निभ
Bahuvr. n. (-भम्) Gold. E. अग्नि and भा (having the lustre of fire, brilliant as fire).

agnibhu|अग्निभु
Tatpur. n. (-भु) See the following.

agnibhuu|अग्निभू
Tatpur. I. m. (-भूः)<BR> ^1 A name of Skanda, the Hindu deity of war. See कार्त्तिकेय, स्कन्द, अग्निजन्मन्. (Śiva having cast his seed into flame, for the purpose of generating a warrior, able to subdue Táraka, a demon, Skanda was produced.)<BR> ^2 (In arithmetic sometimes used to denote) the numeral six (Skanda having six faces). <BR>II. n. (-भु) Water (rain being generated, according to the Hindu belief from the clouds which are produced by the smoke of fire). E. अग्नि and भू (generating from).

agnibhuuti|अग्निभूति
Bahuvr. m. (-तिः) A proper name, viz. one of the pupils of the last Tírthakara, belonging to the family of Gotama and being one of the eleven chiefs of the gańas or companies of the Jaina Ŕishis. E. अग्नि and भूति (superhuman power): equal to Agni.

agnimaNi|अग्निमणि
Tatpur. m. (-णिः) The sun-stone. E. अग्नि and मणिः brilliant as fire. See अग्निगर्भ and सूर्यकान्त.

agnimat|अग्निमत्
m. f. n. (-मान्-मती-मत्)<BR> ^1 Having fire in general.<BR> ^2 Having and maintaining a consecrated fire.<BR> ^3 Having a good digestion. E. अग्नि taddh. aff. मतुप्.

agnimantha|अग्निमन्थ
Tatpur. m. (-न्थः) A small tree (Premna integrifolia). See मणिकारिका. E. अग्नि and मन्थ (churning), because fire is produced by friction of two pieces of its wood. 

agnimanthana|अग्निमन्थन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Producing fire by friction of two pieces of wood. See the preceding. E. अग्नि and मन्थन.

agnimanthaniiya|अग्निमन्थनीय
m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Referring to अग्निमन्थन q. v. E. The preceding, taddh. aff. छ.

agnimaaThara|अग्निमाठर
Tatpur. m. (-रः) The name of an expounder of the Rigveda. E. अग्नि and माठर.

agnimaandya|अग्निमान्द्य
Tatpur. n. (-न्द्यम्) Languor of the digestive organs, the want of appetite or digestion. E. अग्नि and मान्द्य.

agnimaaruti|अग्निमारुति
Karmadh. m. (-तिः) A name of the saint Agastya. E. अग्नि fire, i. e. the fire of the stomach, the digestive faculty, and मारुति a name of Hanumat; because the saint could digest as well as the monkey: the epithet alludes to a story of his devouring and digesting Vátápi, a demon, who had assumed the form of a sheep.

agnimitra|अग्निमित्र
Tatpur. m. (-त्रः) The name of a prince of the Sunga dynasty. E. अग्नि and मित्र.

agnimindha|अग्निमिन्ध
Tatpur. m. (-न्धः) The priest who kindles or attends the fire. See अग्नीध्. E. अग्नि and इन्ध, with ágama मुम् (or better अग्नि in the acc. and इन्ध).

agnimukha|अग्निमुख
Bahuvr. I. m. (-खः)<BR> ^1 A deity.<BR> ^2 A Bráhmańa.<BR> ^3 A plant (Plumbago zeylanica).<BR> ^4 Marking nut (Semecarpus anacardium).<BR> ^5 A particular medicinal preparation promotive of digestion and appetite. <BR>II. f. (-खी)<BR> ^1 Marking nut (Semecarpus anacardium).<BR> ^2 Another plant, see लाङ्गलिकी. E. अग्नि and मुख.

agniyuta|अग्नियुत
Tatpur. m. (-तः) Name of a Ŕishi or sage, author of a hymn of the Rigveda. E. अग्नि and युत.

agniyojana|अग्नियोजन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) A sacrificial act, viz. making the fire to join or to light up with a powerful blaze, by throwing ájya or clarified butter into it. E. अग्नि and योजन.

agniraxaNa|अग्निरक्षण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) Maintenance of a sacred fire; preserving a fire in a family for perpetuity, which supplies that lighted on occasions of worship. E. अग्नि and रक्षण.

agnirajas|अग्निरजस्
Bahuvr. m. (-जाः) An insect of a scarlet colour. E. अग्नि and रजस्. Also अग्निरज m. (-जः).

agniruhaa|अग्निरुहा
Tatpur. f. (-हा) The name of a plant, called Mánsarohińí. E. अग्नि and रुह, fem. aff. टाप्.

agnirohiNii|अग्निरोहिणी
Tatpur. f. (-णी) Hard, inflammatory swelling in the axilla, one of the minor diseases or क्षुद्ररोग q. v. E. अग्नि and रोहिन्, fem. aff. ङीप्.

agniloka|अग्निलोक
Tatpur. m. (-कः) The world of Agni. E. अग्नि and लोक.

agnivat|अग्निवत्
I. m. f. n. (-वान्-वती-वत्). See अग्निमत्. E. अग्नि, taddh. aff. मतुप्. <BR>II. ind. Like Agni or fire. E. अग्नि, taddh. aff. वति.

agnivarchas|अग्निवर्चस्
Bahuvr. m. (-र्चाः) The name of a pupil of Súta, a teacher of the Puráńas. E. अग्नि and वर्चस्.

agnivarNa|अग्निवर्ण
Bahuvr. I. m. f. n. (-र्णः-र्णा-र्णम्)<BR> ^1 Having the colour of fire.<BR> ^2 Having the property of fire, hot, scalding, scorching. <BR>II. m. (-र्णः) The name of a prince, the son of Sudarśana. <BR>III. f. (-र्णा) A kind of strong liquor. E. अग्नि and वर्ण.

agnivardhaka|अग्निवर्धक
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-कः-का or -की-कम्)<BR> ^1 Tonic, stomachic.<BR> ^2 Feeding or exciting fire. E. अग्नि and वर्धक.

agnivardhana|अग्निवर्धन
Tatpur. I. n. (-नम्)<BR> ^1 Exciting fire.<BR> ^2 Improving the appetite. II. m. (-नः) A stomachic or any thing improving the appetite. E. अग्नि and वर्धन. 

agnivallabha|अग्निवल्लभ
Tatpur. m. (-भः)<BR> ^1 A plant (Shorea robusta).<BR> ^2 Resin, pitch, the resinous and fragrant exudation of the Shorea robusta. E. अग्नि and वल्लभ, from its exciting or befriending fire.

agnivaaNa|अग्निवाण
Tatpur. m. (-णः) A fiery arrow, a rocket. E. अग्नि and वाण.

agnivaaha|अग्निवाह
Tatpur. m. (-हः) Smoke. E. अग्नि and वाह.

agnivaahu|अग्निवाहु
I. Tatpur. m. (-हुः) Smoke. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. (-हुः) A proper name of<BR> ^1 the son of Priyavrata by Kámyá, and<BR> ^2 one of the ten sons of Sváyambhuva or the first Manu. E. अग्नि and वाहु. Also अग्निबाहु.

agnivimochana|अग्निविमोचन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) A sacrificial act, viz. withdrawing the fuel so as to diminish the fire after its having been made to rise in a large blaze. See अग्नियोजन. E. अग्नि and विमोचन.

agnivisarpa|अग्निविसर्प
Tatpur. m. (-र्पः) Pain occasioned by the inflammation of a tumour. E. अग्नि and विसर्प.

agniviharaNa|अग्निविहरण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) Removing the sacrificial fire, a ceremony in the Jyotisht́oma sacrifice which consists in taking the fire from the Ágnídhra Mand́apa (q. v.) and placing it in the Sadas (q. v.), another Mand́apa in the Saumikí Vedi (q. v.). E. अग्नि and विहरण.

agniviija|अग्निवीज
Tatpur. n. (-जम्) Gold. E. अग्नि and वीज.

agniviirya|अग्निवीर्य
Tatpur. n. (-र्यम्) Gold. E. अग्नि and वीर्य.

agnivRddhi|अग्निवृद्धि
Tatpur. f. (-द्धिः)<BR> ^1 Improved digestion or appetite.<BR> ^2 Increase of fire. E. अग्नि and वृद्धि.

agnivesha|अग्निवेश
Bahuvr. m. (-शः) Name of one of the oldest medical authorities in India. He is called also Hutáśaveśa and Bhadrakápya. E. अग्नि and वेश.

agnisharaNa|अग्निशरण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) The house or place where the sacred fire is kept. E. अग्नि and शरण.

agnishaala|अग्निशाल
Tatpur. f. n. (-ला-लम्) The house where the sacred fire is kept. E. अग्नि and शाला, the latter part of the compound remaining fem. or becoming neuter.

agnishikha|अग्निशिख
I. Bahuvr. 1. m. f. n. (-खः-खा-खम्) Having the splendour or the heat of fire. BREAḲ. m. (-खः)<BR> ^1 A lamp.<BR> ^2 An arrow.<BR> ^3 A fiery arrow, a rocket.<BR> ^4 The safflower plant (Carthamus tinctorius).<BR> ^5 The name of the father of Vararuchi. <BR>3. m. n. (-खः-खम्) Saffron, the plant and die. BREAḰ. n. (-खम्) Gold. <BR>II. Tatpur. f. (-खा)<BR> ^1 Flame.<BR> ^2 A plant (Gloriosa superba).<BR> ^3 A medicinal plant (Menispermum cordifolium). E. अग्नि and शिखा.

agnishekhara|अग्निशेखर
Bahuvr. n. (-रम्) Saffron. E. अग्नि and शेखर.

agniShTut|अग्निष्टुत्
Tatpur. m. (-ष्टुत्)<BR> ^1 The name of the first day of the Agnisht́oma sacrifice (q. v.).<BR> ^2 The name of a day of the Sattra Panchadaśarátra. E. अग्नि and स्तुत्.

agniShTubh|अग्निष्टुभ्
Tatpur. m. (-ष्टुप्) A proper name, the son of the sixth Manu, Chákshusha, by Nad́valá, also called Agnisht́oma. E. अग्नि and स्तुभ्.

agniShToma|अग्निष्टोम
Tatpur. m. (-मः)<BR> ^1 The name of a sacrifice or rather a series of offerings to fire for five days, to be celebrated in the spring. It is the first and principal part of the Jyotisht́oma, one of the great sacrifices in which especially the juice of the Soma plant is offered for the purpose of ob taining Swarga or heaven. It is nitya or obligatory for the complete performance of the Jyotisht́oma and so far considered sometimes identical with it, while the other six parts or Somasansthás of this sacrifice are considered as kámya and anitya, voluntary and supererogatory. (See अत्यग्निष्टोम, उक्थ्य, षोडशिन्, अतिरात्र, अप्तोर्याम and वाजपेय.) The Agnisht́oma consists of three distinct parts or savanas, the prátah́savana with five, the mádhyandinasavana with five and the tŕitíya-savana with two stotras.<BR> ^2 The name of the Sáman or Sámaveda verse called Yajnáyajníya (which begins with the words यज्ञायज्ञा वो अग्नये &c. see Sámaveda I. 1. 4. 1.), because it closes the ceremonies of the Agnisht́oma in the tŕitíya-savana.<BR> ^3 The name of the first day in the Sattra Panchadaśarátra.<BR> ^5 A proper name, the son of the sixth Manu, Chákshusha, by Nad́valá, also Agnisht́ubh.<BR> ^6 A species of the Soma plant. E. अग्नि and स्तोम.

agniShTomayaajin|अग्निष्टोमयाजिन्
Tatpur. m. (-जी) One who has performed the Agnisht́oma sacrifice. E. अग्निष्टोम and याजिन्.

agniShTha|अग्निष्ठ
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-ष्ठः-ष्ठा-ष्ठम्) Placed in, on or by the fire. <BR>II. m. (-ष्ठः)<BR> ^1 An iron frying pan.<BR> ^2 The eleventh yúpa or sacrificial post of the 21 posts in the Aśwamedha sacrifice, that post to which the seventeen animals are tied. <BR>III. f. (-ष्ठा) That corner of the eight corners of the yúpa or sacrificial post which is near the fire. E. अग्नि and स्थ.

agniShvaatta|अग्निष्वात्त
Tatpur. m. pl. (-त्ताः) Demigods or manes to whom funeral oblations are presented; a sort of manes who when alive did not maintain their domestic fires nor offer burnt sacrifices. According to some they live in the Somaloka and are sons of Maríchi and progenitors especially of the gods; according to others they are residents of the Virájaloka, sons of Pulastya, the manes of the demigods and demons, and parents of Pívarí. Also written अग्निस्वात्त. E. अग्निस्व (अग्नि and स्व) and आत्त (who are obtained by what belongs or is given to Agni) or अग्निषु (in or by oblations to fire) and आत्त (obtained viz. invoked).

agnisaMskaara|अग्निसंस्कार
Tatpur. m. (-रः)<BR> ^1 Consecration of fire, making the three fires (see अग्नि) fit for sacrificial purposes by the Agnyádhána, the Pavamánesht́i (q. v.) and other preparatory rites which, themselves, are performed with non-consecrated fire.<BR> ^2 The completion of any essential rite by worship with fire, especially the burning of the dead body as an essential rite of the Hindu religion. E. अग्नि and संस्कार.

agnisancaya|अग्निसञ्चय
Tatpur. m. (-यः) The same as अग्निचयन q. v. E. अग्नि and सञ्चय.

agnisakha|अग्निसख
Tatpur. m. (-खः) The wind. E. अग्नि and सखि, samásta aff. टच्.

agnisambhava|अग्निसम्भव
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-वः-वा-वम्) Originating from fire. <BR>II. m. (-वः)<BR> ^1 Wild safflower.<BR> ^2 The juice or essence of the body, lymph. E. अग्नि and सम्भव.

agnisahaaya|अग्निसहाय
m. (-यः)<BR> ^1 The wind.<BR> ^2 A wild pigeon. E. अग्नि and सहाय.

agnisaaxikamaryaada|अग्निसाक्षिकमर्याद
Bahuvr. m. (-दः) One who binde himself  with a vow in taking fire as a witness, esp. one who takes the vow of conjugal fidelity. E. अग्निसाक्षिक and मर्यादा.

agnisaat|अग्निसात्
ind. Completely to fire. Only in composition with अस्, भू or कृ, i. e. to be reduced or to reduce ‘(completely to fire). E. अग्नि, taddh. aff. साति.

agnisaara|अग्निसार
n. (-रम्) A medicinal application to the eyes, a collyrium from the calx of brass. E. अग्नि and सार.

agnisaavarNi|अग्निसावर्णि
Tatpur. m. (-र्णिः) A proper name, one of the fourteen Manus who preside successively over the fourteen Manvantaras of the Kalpa. E. अग्नि and सावर्णि.

agnisiMha|अग्निसिंह
Karmadh. m. (-हः) A proper name, the father of the seventh black Vásudeva (q. v.). E. अग्नि and सिंह.

agnisiMhanandana|अग्निसिंहनन्दन
Tatpur. m. (-नः) A proper name, the son of Agnisinha and the seventh black Vásudeva (q. v.). E. अग्निसिंह and नन्दन.

agnistoka|अग्निस्तोक
Tatpur. m. (-कः) A spark. E. अग्नि and स्तोक.

agnisvaatta|अग्निस्वात्त
See अग्निष्वात्त.

agnihotR|अग्निहोतृ
Tatpur. m. (-ता). See अग्निहोत्रिन्. E. अग्नि and होतृ.

agnihotra|अग्निहोत्र
I. Bahuvr. n. (-त्रम्)<BR> ^1 A sacrificial ceremony which consists in making oblations to fire, of milk (payas), curds (dadhi), sour gruel (yavágú), clarified butter (ghŕita), boiled rice (odana), grain (tand́ula), the juice of the Soma plant, flesh, sesamum oil (taila) and kidney beans (másha), or as is practised at present, merely of milk, sesamum oil and sour gruel. There are two kinds, 1. the nitya, perpetual, ‘during the whole life’ or that Agnihotra which is addressed to Agni every evening at sunset and to Súrya every morning at sunrise; and 2. the kámya, voluntary or the Agnihotra which occurs only occasionally and which is performed for the attainment of some specific object, as the Mŕitágnihotra or the Máságnihotra in the beginning of the Sattra Kund́apáyinámayana.<BR> ^2 The same as अग्न्याधान q. v. E. अग्नि and होत्र, sc. कर्मन् ‘an act in which oblations are made to Agni’. <BR>II. Tatpur. m. (-त्रः)<BR> ^1 Fire.<BR> ^2 Havis or clarified butter. E. अग्नि and होत्र.

agnihotrahavaNii|अग्निहोत्रहवणी
Tatpur. f. (-णी) A wooden vessel used in sacrifices for making libations with clarified butter. E. अग्निहोत्र (clarified butter) and हवनी.

agnihotrin|अग्निहोत्रिन्
m. (-त्री)<BR> ^1 One who has performed the Agnihotra q. v.<BR> ^2 The same as अग्न्याहित.<BR> ^3 The same as अग्निचित्.<BR> ^4 One who possesses or keeps a sacrificial fire. Sometimes read अग्निहोतृ. E. अग्निहोत्र, taddh. aff. इनि.

agniidh|अग्नीध्
Tatpur. m. (-ग्नीत्) The priest who kindles the fire; he is one of the three priests who are subordinate to the Brahman or the Ŕitvij performing the ceremonial of the Ŕig-, Yajurand Sámaveda, (see ब्रह्मन्, ब्राह्मणाच्छंसिन् and पोतृ) and one of the four priests who receive the third division of the Dakshińá. (See नेष्टृ, प्रतिहर्तृ and अच्छावाक.) E. अग्नि and इध् (instead of इन्ध्).

agniidhra|अग्नीध्र
Tatpur. I. m. (-ध्रः)<BR> ^1 A proper name: the son of Priyavrata and Kámyá, a king of Jambudvípa; one of the ten sons of the first Manu, Sváyambhuva.<BR> ^2 The same as अग्नीध् q. v. In this meaning the word seems to be a misspelling of आग्नीध्र. <BR>II. f. (-ध्री) Kindling or exciting the sacrificial fire by  throwing clarified butter &c. into it. See आग्नीध्री which seems to be the more correct form of this word. E. अग्नि and इध्र (from इन्ध्, uń. aff. क्रन्).

agniindhana|अग्नीन्धन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Kindling or exciting a sacrificial fire. E. अग्नि and इन्धन. See अग्निकारिका.

agniiya|अग्नीय
m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Fiery, relating to Agni (in the different meanings of this word). E. अग्नि, taddh. aff. छ.

agniiShoma|अग्नीषोम
Dvandva. m. du. (-मौ) Agni and Soma. E. अग्नि and सोम.

agniiShomapraNayana|अग्नीषोमप्रणयन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Carrying forth the fire and the Soma; a ceremony in the Jyotisht́oma sacrifice which takes place after the Vaisarjana homa (q. v.) and consists in taking the fire from the Práchínavańśa (q. v.) Mand́apa and carrying it to the Ágnídhra (q. v.) Mand́apa, and in the same time taking the Soma from the Práchínavańśa and carrying it to the Havirdhána Mand́apa, a building erected in the Saumikí Vedi (q. v.). See also अग्निप्रणयन. E. अग्नीषोम and प्रणयन.

agniiShomiiya|अग्नीषोमीय
m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Belonging or sacred to Agni and Soma. E. अग्नीषोम, taddh. aff. छ.

agniiShomiiyanirvaapa|अग्नीषोमीयनिर्वाप
Tatpur. m. (-पः) A ceremony in the Darśapúrńamása sacrifice which is performed on the day of the full moon and consists in making libations with the Purod́áśa (q. v.) or cake sacred to Agni and Soma and previously fried in eleven kapálas or bowls. See अग्नीषोमीयैकादशकपाल. E. अग्नीषोमीय and निर्वाप.

agniiShomiiyapashu|अग्नीषोमीयपशु
Karmadh. m. (-शुः) One of the three principal paśus or sacrificial animals in the Jyotisht́oma sacrifice. (See also सवनीयपशु and अनुबन्ध्यपशु.) It is a goat or according to one school, a sheep, sacred to Agni and Soma, the procedings with which take place on the day called Aupavasathya or the fourth of the Agnisht́oma (q. v.). E. अग्नीषोमीय and पशु.

agniiShomiiyapashvanuShThaana|अग्नीषोमीयपश्वनुष्ठान
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) The procedings with the Agníshomíyapaśu. See अग्नीषोमीयपशु. E. अग्नीषोमीयपशु and अनुष्ठान.

agniiShomiiyapuroDaasha|अग्नीषोमीयपुरोडाश
Karmadh. m. (-शः) The Purod́áśa (q. v.) with which libations are made during the Agníshomíyayága (q. v.) after having been baked in eleven kapálas or bowls. E. अग्नीषोमीय and पुरोडाश.

agniiShomiiyayaaga|अग्नीषोमीययाग
Karmadh. m. (-गः) One of the three yágas or sacrificial acts of which consists the Púrńamása or the latter part of the Darśapúrńamása sacrifice. (See also आग्नेययाग and उपांशुयाजयाग.)

agniiShomiiyaikaadashakapaala|अग्नीषोमीयैकादशकपाल
Karmadh. m. (-लः) The Purod́áśa (q. v.) or cake which is offered to Agni and Soma in the Darśapúrńamása sacrifice after having been baked in eleven kapálas or bowls. See also अग्नीषोमीयपुरोडाश. E. अग्नीषोमीय and एकादशकपाल.

agniiShomya|अग्नीषोम्य
m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्). The same as अग्नीषोमीय. E. अग्नीषोम, taddh. aff. यत्.

agnyabhaava|अग्न्यभाव
Tatpur. m. (-वः)<BR> ^1 Loss or extinction of the sacred fire.<BR> ^2 Loss of appetite. E. अग्नि and अभाव.

agnyastra|अग्न्यस्त्र
Tatpur. n. (-स्त्रम्) Fire-arms; in poetry, it is usually applied to a superhuman power over the element of fire, but occasionally indicates, apparently, a rocket. E. अग्नि and अस्त्र. 

agnyaagaara|अग्न्यागार
Tatpur. m. (-रः) A fire-temple; a chamber or building where the sacred fire is kept. E. अग्नि and आगार.

agnyaadhaana|अग्न्याधान
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) The placing of the fire on the ground previously prepared for it (see अग्निचयन); a ceremony which is necessary to make the Áhavaníya and the other sacred fires (see अग्नि) fit for sacrificial use and is followed by the Pavamáneshtis (q. v.). See अग्निसंस्कार. The act takes place in the spring, if the person belongs to the cast of the Bráhmańas, in the hot season or gríshma if he is a Kshatriya, in the autumn or śarad if he is a Vaiśya and is performed once for all, to serve all future purposes. E. अग्नि and आधान.

agnyaadheya|अग्न्याधेय
Tatpur. n. (-यम्) The same as अग्न्याधान q. v. E. अग्नि and आधेय.

agnyaalaya|अग्न्यालय
Tatpur. m. (-यः)<BR> ^1 A place in which consecrated fire is kept.<BR> ^2 A hole, with compartments of prescribed dimensions and shape, for the several sacred fires. E. अग्नि and आलय.

agnyaahita|अग्न्याहित
Bahuvr. m. (-तः) A householder who has performed the ceremony of the अग्न्याधान q. v. Also आहिताग्नि. E. अग्नि and आहित.

agnyaahiti|अग्न्याहिति
Tatpur. f. (-तिः) The same as अग्न्याधान q. v. E. अग्नि and आहिति.

agnyutpaata|अग्न्युत्पात
Tatpur. m. (-तः) A fiery meteor, a falling star, a comet. E. अग्नि and उत्पात.

agnyuddharaNa|अग्न्युद्धरण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) A sacrificial ceremony; taking the sacred fire out of the place where it is kept, for the purpose of performing a sacrifice, as the Agnihotra, the Darśapúrńamása &c. E. अग्नि and उद्धरण.

agman|अग्मन्
n. (ग्म) Battle. E. अज्, kŕit aff. मनिन्. See अज्मन्.

agra|अग्र
I. m. f. n. (-ग्रः-ग्रा-ग्रम्)<BR> ^1 Chief, principal.<BR> ^2 Prior, first.<BR> ^3 Excessive, more, much. <BR>II. n. (-ग्रम्)<BR> ^1 Top, summit, point, upper part.<BR> ^2 Front, fore part.<BR> ^3 The beginning, first part.<BR> ^4 The best, excellent.<BR> ^5 Goal, resting place.<BR> ^6 Assemblage, multitude.<BR> ^7 A weight equal to one Pala.<BR> ^8 A kind of alms give to Brahmans, four mouthfuls or according to others, food given in alms, 48 times the quantity of the alms called भिक्षा.<BR> ^9 (In astronomy) the sun's amplitude. E. अङ्ग्, uń. aff. रन्, the nasal of the radical being dropped.

agrakara|अग्रकर
Tatpur. m. (-रः)<BR> ^1 The tip of the extended hand.<BR> ^2 (Karmadh.) The right or better hand.<BR> ^3 The extremity of a ray of light; the focal point. E. अग्र and कर.

agrakaaya|अग्रकाय
Tatpur. m. (-यः) The fore part of the body. E. अग्र and काय.

agraga|अग्रग
Tatpur. m. (-गः) A leader. E. अग्र and ग.

agragaNya|अग्रगण्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ण्यः-ण्या-ण्यम्) To be reckoned or considered as first or best. E. अग्र and गण्य.

agragaamin|अग्रगामिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-मी-मिनी-मि) Preceding, going before. E. अग्र and गामिन्.

agraja|अग्रज
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-जः-जा-जम्) First-born or produced. <BR>II. m. (-जः)<BR> ^1 An elder brother; the first-born.<BR> ^2 A Brahman. <BR>III. f. (-जा) An elder sister. E. अग्र and ज.

agrajaNGghaa|अग्रजङ्घा
Tatpur. f. (-ङ्घा) The fore part of the thigh. E. अग्र and जङ्घा.

agrajanman|अग्रजन्मन्
Bahuvr. m. (-न्मा)<BR> ^1 An elder brother or first-born. <BR> ^2 A priest or Brahman; a man of the sacerdotal tribe.<BR> ^3 Brahmá, the first-born of the gods. E. अग्र and जन्मन्.

agrajaataka|अग्रजातक
Tatpur. m. (-कः) A Brahman; a man of the first class. E. अग्र and जातक.

agrajaati|अग्रजाति
Bahuvr. m. (-तिः) A Brahman; a man of the first class. E. अग्र and जाति.

agrajihva|अग्रजिह्व
Tatpur. n. (-ह्वम्) The tip of the tongue. E. अग्र and जिह्वा.

agrajyaa|अग्रज्या
Tatpur. f. (-ज्या) (In astronomy.) Sine of the amplitude. E. अग्र and ज्या.

agraNii|अग्रणी
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-णीः-णीः-णि) First, principal. E. अग्र and नी.

agrataHsara|अग्रतःसर
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-रः-रा or -री-रम्) Going before, preceding. <BR>II. m. (-रः) A leader. E. अग्रतस् and सर.

agratas|अग्रतस्
ind.<BR> ^1 Before, in front of.<BR> ^2 Before in rank, first &c. E. अग्र, taddh. aff. तसिल्.

agradaanin|अग्रदानिन्
m. (-नी) A degraded Brahman, one who receives presents from Śúdras or things first offered to the deceased. E. अग्रदान (a present first given viz. to Śúdras or to deceased), taddh. aff. इनि.

agranakha|अग्रनख
Tatpur. m. (-खः) The tip of the nail. E. अग्र and नख.

agranaasikaa|अग्रनासिका
Tatpur. f. (-का) The tip of the nose. E. अग्र and नासिका.

agraniruupaNa|अग्रनिरूपण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) Determining beforehand, prophecy, predestination. E. अग्र and निरूपण.

agraparNii|अग्रपर्णी
Bahuvr. f. (-र्णी) A plant, Cowhage (Carpopogon pruriens). E. अग्र and पर्ण.

agrapaaNi|अग्रपाणि
Tatpur. m. (-णिः)<BR> ^1 The tip of the hand.<BR> ^2 (Karmadh.) The right hand. E. अग्र and पाणि.

agrabhaaga|अग्रभाग
Tatpur. m. (-गः)<BR> ^1 Part of the top or end.<BR> ^2 (Karmadh.) Fore or top part.<BR> ^3 (In astronomy.) Degree of amplitude, also अग्रांश. E. अग्र and भाग.

agrabhuumi|अग्रभूमि
Tatpur. m. f. (-मिः) A goal, an object, the place or thing to be attained. E. अग्र and भूमि.

agramaaMsa|अग्रमांस
Tatpur. n. (-सम्)<BR> ^1 The heart.<BR> ^2 A disease of the liver, viz. and enlargement of one of the lobes causing it to occupy the forepart of the stomach. E. अग्र and मांस.

agrayaana|अग्रयान
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Advancing before an army, for the purpose of defiance. E. अग्र and यान.

agrayaayin|अग्रयायिन्
Tatpur. m. (-यी) Going in front, a leader. E. अग्र and यायिन्.

agrayodhin|अग्रयोधिन्
Tatpur. m. (-धी) The leader of a combat. E. अग्र and योधिन्.

agralohitaa|अग्रलोहिता
Tatpur. f. (-ता) A kind of potherb, see चिल्ली. E. अग्र and लोहित.

agraviija|अग्रवीज
Bahuvr. m. (-जः) A viviparous plant, as the Gomphroena globosa, &c. E. अग्र and वीज.

agrasandhaanii|अग्रसन्धानी
Tatpur. f. (-नी) The register of human actions, kept by Yama, the judge of the dead. E. अग्र and सन्धानी; recording all actions from the original birth.

agrasandhyaa|अग्रसन्ध्या
Karmadh. f. (-न्ध्या) The first twilight, dawn. E. अग्र and सन्ध्या.

agrasaanu|अग्रसानु
Tatpur. m. (-नुः) The front part of a table land. E. अग्र and सानु. 

agrasara|अग्रसर
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-रः-रा or -री-रम्) Preceding, going before, a leader. E. अग्र and सर.

agrasena|अग्रसेन
Bahuvr. m. (-नः) A proper name, the son of Janamejaya. E. अग्र and सेना.

agraha|अग्रह
Bahuvr. m. (-हः) An anchorite or Vánaprastha, a Brahman of the third order, one who has retired from the world. E. अ priv. and ग्रह a house, ‘being no longer a householder’. Also written अगृह.

agrahasta|अग्रहस्त
Tatpur. m. (-स्तः)<BR> ^1 The tip of the extended hand.<BR> ^2 The tip of an elephant's trunk.<BR> ^3 (Karmadh.) The right or better hand. E. अग्र and हस्त.

agrahaayaNa|अग्रहायण
Tatpur. m. (-णः) A name given to the solar month Márgaśiras or Márgaśirsha (q. v.) when the latter was made to commence the year; the eighth month of the lunar year of the Hindus, when the moon is full near the head of Orion, or about November-December. Also written आग्रहायण. (The fem. अग्रहायणी is a false reading for आग्रहायणी q. v.) E. अग्र and हायण.

agrahaara|अग्रहार
Tatpur. m. (-रः)<BR> ^1 An endowment of land or villages conferred upon Brahmans.<BR> ^2 A village, or a part of one, occupied by Brahmans and held either rent-free under special grants or at a reduced rate of assessment. The precise nature of the tenure is usually denoted by a term prefixed, as Sarvágrahára, free from all (sarva) tax &c. E. अग्र (alms) and हार.

agraaMsha|अग्रांश
Tatpur. m. (-शः) See अग्रभाग. E. अग्र and अंश.

agraaMshu|अग्रांशु
Tatpur. m. (-शुः) The extreme ray or point of a ray of light, the focal point. E. अग्र and अंशु.

agraaxi|अग्राक्षि
Tatpur. n. (-क्षि) The fore part of the eye, fullness of the sight. E. अग्र and अक्षि.

agraanguli|अग्राङ्गुलि
Tatpur. m. (-लिः) The tip of the finger. E. अग्र and अङ्गुलि.

agraaniika|अग्रानीक
Tatpur. m. n. (-कः-कम्) The front of an army. E. अग्र and अनीक.

agraayaNiiya|अग्रायणीय
n. (-यम्) Name of the second of the fourteen oldest books of the Jainas. E. अग्रायण, taddh. aff. छ.

agraahya|अग्राह्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ह्यः-ह्या-ह्यम्)<BR> ^1 Not fit or proper to be accepted.<BR> ^2 Not to be attained.<BR> ^3 Not to be trusted or consented to. E. अ neg. and ग्राह्य.

agrima|अग्रिम
I. m. f. n. (-मः-मा-मम्)<BR> ^1 Chief, principal, best.<BR> ^2 Prior, precedent.<BR> ^3 Elder, elder born. <BR>II. f. (-मा) The name of a fruit (Annona reticulata). See लवणी. E. अग्र, taddh. aff. डिमच्.

agriya|अग्रिय
I. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Chief, principal, best. <BR>II. m. (-यः) The first-born, an elder brother. See also अग्रीय and अग्र्य. E. अग्र, taddh. aff. घ.

agriiya|अग्रीय
I. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) and II. m. (-यः) See अग्रिय. E. अग्र, taddh. aff. छ.

agru|अग्रु
I. m. (-ग्रुः) Not married. <BR>II. f. (-ग्रू)<BR> ^1 A finger.<BR> ^2 A river. E. अग्, uń. aff. क्रुन्.

agrega|अग्रेग
Tatpur. m. (-गः) A leader, a preceder. E. अग्र (loc.) and ग.

agregaa|अग्रेगा
Tatpur. m. (-गाः) A leader, a preceder. E. अग्र (loc.) and गा.

agreguu|अग्रेगू
Tatpur. m. (-गूः) A leader. E. अग्र (loc.) and गू.

agreNii|अग्रेणी
Tatpur. m. (-णीः) A leader. E. अग्र (loc.) and नी. 

agredidhiShu|अग्रेदिधिषु
Tatpur. I. m. (-षुः) A man of either of the three first classes, whose wife has before been married, and has born him children. <BR>II. f. (-षुः) A younger sister married before her elder; also अग्रेदिधिषू. E. अग्र (loc.) and दिधिषु or दिधिषू.

agrepaa|अग्रेपा
Tatpur. m. f. (-पाः-पाः) Drinking first. E. अग्र (loc.) and पा.

agrepuu|अग्रेपू
Tatpur. m. f. (-पूः-पूः) Drinking first. E. अग्र (loc.) and पू.

agrebhruu|अग्रेभ्रू
Tatpur. m. (-भ्रूः) Roaming or wandering first. E. अग्र (loc.) and भ्रू (from भ्रम् q. v.).

agrevaNa|अग्रेवण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) The skirts of a wood. E. अग्र (loc.) and वन.

agrevadha|अग्रेवध
Tatpur. m. (-धः) Killing what is before any one, before any one's sight. E. अग्र (loc.) and वध.

agresara|अग्रेसर
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-रः-रा or -री-रम्) Preceding, going before. <BR>II. m. (-रः) A leader. E. अग्र (loc.) and सर.

agresarika|अग्रेसरिक
Tatpur. m. (-कः) A leader. E. अग्र (loc.) and सरिक.

agrya|अग्र्य
I. m. f. n. (-ग्र्यः-ग्र्या-ग्र्यम्)<BR> ^1 Being on the top or summit.<BR> ^2 Chief, principal, best.<BR> ^3 Intent, studying attentively or eagerly. <BR>II. m. (-ग्र्यः) A first-born, an elder brother. See also अग्रिय and अग्रीय. E. अग्र, taddh. aff. यत्.

agh|अघ्
r. 10th cl. par. (अघयति) To sin, to commit sin. (Probably a denominative derived from अघ. See also अघाय्.)

agha|अघ
I. n. (-घम्)<BR> ^1 Sin.<BR> ^2 Pain, suffering.<BR> ^3 Passion, as love, hatred.<BR> ^4 Impurity (see अशौच). E. हन् with आ, krit aff. ड, the preposition being made short (or better अंह् or अङ्घ्, kŕit aff. अच्.) See अंहस्, अङ्घस् and अङ्घ. <BR>II. 1. m. f. n. (-घः-घा-घम्) One afflicted with sin, pain, passion, impurity (see the preceding). BREAḲ. m. (-घः) Name of a demon, the general of Kansa. <BR>3. f. (-घा)<BR> ^1 The goddess of Sin.<BR> ^2 pl. f. (-घाः) The constellation, more usually known under the name of मघाः q. v. E. अघ (sin &c.), taddh. aff. अच्.

aghana|अघन
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-नः-ना-नम्) Not solid, liquid. E. अ and घन.

aghanaashaka|अघनाशक
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-कः-का-कम्) Purifying, freeing from sin. E. अघ and नाशक.

aghanaashana|अघनाशन
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-नः-नी-नम्) Purifying, freeing from sin. <BR>II. m. (-नः)<BR> ^1 An expiator.<BR> ^2 A name of Vishńu. E. अघ and नाशन.

aghamaya|अघमय
m. f. n. (-यः-यी-यम्) Sinful, identical with or fruitful in sin. E. अघ, taddh. aff. मयट्.

aghamarShaNa|अघमर्षण
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-णः-णी-णम्) An expiatory prayer: reciting mentally a particular passage from the Vedas, while a little water, in the palm of the right hand, is held to the nose; this forms a part of the daily ceremonies of the Brahmans. <BR>II. m. (-णः) The son of Madhuchhandas and author of the passage recited upon the above occasion. E. अघ and मर्षण.

agharma|अघर्म
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-र्मः-र्मा-र्मम्) Cool, not warm. E. अ neg. and घर्म.

agharmadhaaman|अघर्मधामन्
Bahuvr. m. (-मा) The moon (as the source of coolness). E. अघर्म and धामन्. 

aghavat|अघवत्
m. f. n. (-वान्-वती-वत्) Wicked, vicious, sinful. E. अघ, taddh. aff. मतुप्.

aghashaMsa|अघशंस
Tatpur. m. (-सः) A wicked man. E. अघ and शंस.

aghashaMsahan|अघशंसहन्
Tatpur. m. (-हा) Killing or destroying the wicked. E. अघशंस and हन्.

aghaharaNa|अघहरण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) Removing sin or impurity. E. अघ and हरण.

aghaatin|अघातिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ती-तिनी-ति) Harmless, not mischievous (as a work or deed &c.). E. अ and घातिन्.

aghaay|अघाय्
denom. par. (अघायति) To sin, to commit sin. See also अघ्. E. अघ, denom. aff. क्यच्.

aghaayu|अघायु
m. (-युः) A sinner, a wicked man. E. अघाय्, kŕit aff. उ.

aghaaha|अघाह
Tatpur. m. (-हः) Time or day of impurity, consequent on the death of a relative &c. E. अघ and अहन्, samásta aff. टच्.

aghRNa|अघृण
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-णः-णा-णम्) Unkind, cruel. E. अ priv. and घृणा.

aghora|अघोर
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Not formidable, not terrible. <BR>II. m. (-रः)<BR> ^1 A name of Śiva.<BR> ^2 A worshipper of Śiva and Durgá in their terrific forms. <BR>III. f. (-रा) The fourteenth day of the dark half of the month Bhádra (August-September), upon which Śiva is worshipped. E. अ neg. and घोर. (The name of Śiva taken in a euphemistic sense.)

aghoraghoraruupa|अघोरघोररूप
Bahuvr. m. (-पः) A name of Śiva. E. अघोरघोर (not frightful and frightful in the same time) and रूप.

aghorapathin|अघोरपथिन्
Bahuvr. m. (-पन्था) A worshipper of the terrific forms of Śiva and Durgá. E. अघोर and पथिन्.

aghoramaarga|अघोरमार्ग
Bahuvr. m. (-र्गः) The same as the preceding. E. अघोर and मार्ग.

aghoSha|अघोष
I. Tatpur. m. (-षः) (In grammar.) The absence of soft articulation, hard articulation; such as characterises the pronunciation of the letters क ख च छ ट ठ त थ प फ श ष स and of Visarga. See वाह्यप्रयत्न. E. अ neg. and घोष. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-षः-षा-षम्)<BR> ^1 Without a soft sounding, sounding hard (as a letter).<BR> ^2 Without a cowherd (as a country). E. अ priv. and घोष.

aghos|अघोस्
ind. A vocative particle. E. Irregular vocative of अघवत् (erroneously derived from अ neg. and हन्, aff. ओस्).

aghnya|अघ्न्य
Tatpur. I. m. (-घ्न्यः) A name of Brahmá. <BR>II. f. (-घ्न्या) A cow. E. अ and हन्, uń. aff. यक् (अघ्न्य literally: not to be slain, inviolable).

ank|अङ्क्
I. (अकि-भ्वादि-उदात्त-अनुदात्तेत्) r. 1st cl. átm. (अङ्कतेआनङ्के-अङ्किता. p. p. अङ्कित. Des. अञ्चिकिषते)<BR> ^1 To mark.<BR> ^2 To go. <BR>II. (अङ्क-चुरादि-परस्मैपदिन्) r. 10th cl. par. (अङ्कयति. p. p. अङ्कित)<BR> ^1 To mark.<BR> ^2 To go crookedly or tortuously. See अङ्ग्. (Probably a denominative from अङ्क.)

anka|अङ्क
m. (-ङ्कः) I.<BR> ^1 Winding tortuously.<BR> ^2 The flank or part above the hips where women place young children in carrying them.<BR> ^3 The body.<BR> ^4 Proximity.<BR> ^5 Place, ground.<BR> ^6 A hooked instrument. E. अञ्च्, kŕit or uń. aff. अच्. See अङ्कस्. <BR>II.<BR> ^1 A mark or spot.<BR> ^2 (In arithmetic.) A cypher, an arithmetical sign, a number or coefficient.<BR> ^3 (Used sometimes to denote) the numeral 9.<BR> ^4 A line, a stroke.<BR> ^5 Fault, offence.<BR> ^6 Ornament, decoration.<BR> ^7 The act of a play.<BR> ^8 A  species of dramatic entertainment.<BR> ^9 Mimic war or conflict. E. अञ्च्, kŕit or uń. aff. अच् or अङ्क्, kŕit aff. अच्.

