aNvii|अण्वी
f. (-ण्वी) (ved.) A finger. See अणु.

at|अत्
r. 1st cl. par. (अततिआत-अतिता-अतिष्यति-आतीत्.--p. p. अतित and आत्त.)<BR> ^1 To go, to move.<BR> ^2 To move continually.<BR> ^3 To obtain. With अभि-<BR> ^1 To approach.<BR> ^2 To obtain.--अव- To go down.-सम्- To approach, to hasten to.

at|अत्
ind. A particle which is said to imply surprise or astonishment. It occurs only in अद्भुत according to the native etymology, and perhaps also in अद्धा. It belongs to those indeclinables which in conjunction with radicals are called गति q. v.

ataTa|अतट
Bahuvr. I. m. f. n. (-टः-टा-टम्) Having no shores or banks, steep. <BR>II. m. (-टः) A precipice. E. अ priv. and तट.

atathaa|अतथा
Tatpur. m. (-थाः) Different, not so as before. (ved.) E. अ neg. and तथा.

atathochita|अतथोचित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Not deserving such or so like, worthy of something better. E. अ neg. and तथोचित.

atathya|अतथ्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-थ्यः-थ्या-थ्यम्) Untrue, false, unreal. E. अ neg. and तथ्य.

atadguNa|अतद्गुण
Bahuvr. m. (-णः) (In rhetoric.) A figure of speech, not employing predicates or comparisons which correspond with the nature of the object itself. E. अ priv. and तद्गुण.

atana|अतन
(ved.) I. n. (-नम्) Going, moving continually. <BR>II. m. (-नः) One who goes, who moves continually. E. अत्, kŕit aff. ल्युट्.

atantra|अतन्त्र
I. Tatpur. n. (-न्त्रम्) Not the object of a rule or of the rule in question. E. अ neg. and तन्त्र. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-न्त्रः-न्त्री-न्त्रम्)<BR> ^1 Having no string or rope &c.<BR> ^2 Unrestrained. See तन्त्र. E. अ priv. and तन्त्र.

atandra|अतन्द्र
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-न्द्रः-न्द्रा-न्द्रम्) Unwearied, active, alert. E. अ priv. and तन्द्रा.

atandrita|अतन्द्रित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Unwearied, active, energetic. E. अ neg. and तन्द्रित. 

atandrin|अतन्द्रिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-न्द्री-न्द्रिणी-न्द्रि) Unwearied, active, alert. E. अ neg. and तन्द्रिन्.

atapa|अतप
Bahuvr. I. m. f. n. (-पः-पा-पम्)<BR> ^1 Cool.<BR> ^2 Unanxious.<BR> ^3 Unemployed.<BR> ^4 Unostentatious. <BR>II. m. pl. (-पाः) The name of a particular class of gods of the Buddhists. E. अ priv. and तप.

atapas|अतपस्
Bahuvr. m. (-पाः) One who does not practise austerities, impious. E. अ priv. and तपस्.

atapaska|अतपस्क
Bahuvr. m. (-कः). The same as the preceding. E. अ priv. and तपस्, samásánta aff. कप्.

atapta|अतप्त
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-प्तः-प्ता-प्तम्) Cool, not heated. E. अ neg. and तप्त.

atameru|अतमेरु
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-रुः-रुः-रु) Not wearied, not fatigued, not languid or exhausted. (ved.) E. अ neg. and तमेरु.

atarka|अतर्क
m. (-र्कः) I. Tatpur. Absence of reasoning, want of consideration. E. अ neg. and तर्क. <BR>II. Bahuvr. One who employs groundless arguments, who reasons illogically. E. अ priv. and तर्क.

atarkita|अतर्कित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्)<BR> ^1 Unconsidered.<BR> ^2 Unexpected, unweighed. अतर्कितम् used as adv., unexpectedly, suddenly. E. अ neg. and तर्कित.

atarkya|अतर्क्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-र्क्यः-र्क्या-र्क्यम्) Unsearchable, incomprehensible, inscrutable. E. अ neg. and तर्क्य.

atala|अतल
Bahuvr. n. (-लम्) A particular hell or division of the infernal regions, the portion immediately below the earth. E. अ priv. and तल; ‘bottomless’.

atalasparsha|अतलस्पर्श
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-र्शः-र्शा-र्शम्) Bottomless, very deep. E. अ priv. and तल-स्पर्श; ‘the bottom of which cannot be touched’.

atalaspRsh|अतलस्पृश्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-स्पृक्). See the preceding. E. अ neg. and तल-स्पृश्.

atavyas|अतव्यस्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-व्यान्-व्यसी-व्यः) Not stronger, not very strong. (ved.) E. अ neg. and तव्यस्.

atas|अतस्
ind.<BR> ^1 Hence, from this place.<BR> ^2 From that time.<BR> ^3 Therefore, from that cause.<BR> ^4 Used also in the same sense as the ablative or fifth case of एतद्; f. i. अत ऊर्ध्वम् or अतः परम्, after that, afterwards, from now; अतोऽन्यथा different from that; अतोऽर्थात् from that reason, therefore. E. अश् (i. e. अ considered as a substitute of एतद्), taddh. aff. तसिल्.

atasa|अतस
I. m. (-सः)<BR> ^1 Wind, air.<BR> ^2 The soul.<BR> ^3 A weapon.<BR> ^4 Cloth made from bark.<BR> ^5 (In the Vedas.) A tree, a large tree. <BR>II. f. (-सी)<BR> ^1 Common flax (Linum usitatissimum).<BR> ^2 Sańa, Bengal sun, a kind of flax (Crotolaria juncea). E. अत्, uń. aff. असच्, when fem. with ङीष् added.

ati|अति
ind. (see निपात, उपसर्ग, गति, कर्मप्रवचनीय)<BR> ^1 Over, beyond.<BR> ^2 Exceedingly, very much. This word is used either as a separable preposition with a word following in the accusative, or as an inseparable prefix in composition with verbal and nominal themes. If अति, in composition with a nominal theme, constitutes a Tatpur. compound, it must either express a higher degree (f. i. in अतिराजन्, a superior or excellent king) or the sense of the word क्रान्त must be supplied after it and the latter part of the compound understood in the sense of the accu sative (f. i. in अतिखट्वः which is explained as meaning अतिक्रान्तः खट्वाम्). E. अत्, kŕit aff. इन्(?).

atikatha|अतिकथ
Tatpur. I. f. (-था) Idle or unmeaning speech. <BR>II. m. f. n. (-थः-था-थम्)<BR> ^1 Incredible, unworthy of belief or trust.<BR> ^2 Erring, deviating from the duties of a profession or cast. E. अति and कथा. Some works substitute for this word the reading इतिकथ q. v., which seems to be the more correct form.

atikandaka|अतिकन्दक
Bahuvr. m. (-कः) The name of a tree. See हस्तिकन्द. E. अति and कन्द, samásánta aff. कप्.

atikalyam|अतिकल्यम्
Avyayíbh. Too early in the morning, at dawning. E. अति and कल्य.

atikasha|अतिकश
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-शः-शा-शम्) Past whipping, unmanageable, restive (as a horse). E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and कशा (in the sense of the accusative).

atikaaya|अतिकाय
Bahuvr. I. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Gigantic. <BR>II. m. (-यः) The name of a Rákshasa. E. अति and काय.

atikutsita|अतिकुत्सित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Very low, much despised. E. अति and कुत्सित.

atikulva|अतिकुल्व
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-ल्वः-ल्वा-ल्वम्) Having very few hairs. (ved.) E. अति and कुल्व. Also read अतिकूल्व.

atikRchChra|अतिकृच्छ्र
Tatpur. m. (-च्छ्रः)<BR> ^1 Extreme pain or suffering.<BR> ^2 A kind of penance, eating a handful of food a day for nine days, and fasting three. E. अति and कृच्छ्र.

atikRti|अतिकृति
Tatpur. f. (-तिः) A class of metres regulated by number and quantity. See अतिच्छन्दस्. It comprises two species (see क्रौञ्चपदा and शम्भु) and consists of a stanza of four lines, with twenty-five syllables in each line. Also called अभिकृति. E. अति (sc. क्रान्ता) and कृति (another class of metres; in the sense of the accusative).

atikRsha|अतिकृश
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-शः-शा-शम्) Very thin, emaciated. E. अति and कृश.

atikRShNa|अतिकृष्ण
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ष्णः-ष्णा-ष्णम्) Very dark, too dark or dark blue. E. अति and कृष्ण.

atikeshara|अतिकेशर
Bahuvr. m. (-रः) The name of an aquatic plant (Trapa bispinosa). See कुब्जक. E. अति and केशर.

atikrama|अतिक्रम
m. (-मः)<BR> ^1 Going over or beyond, lit. or fig.<BR> ^2 Surpassing, excelling, overcoming.<BR> ^3 Transgressing.<BR> ^4 Neglect, disregard, impropriety.<BR> ^5 Contrariety, opposition.<BR> ^6 A groundless demand, an imposition.<BR> ^7 A gallant attack, advance of an army in front of an enemy. (See अभिक्रम.) E. क्रम् with अति, kŕit aff. अच्.

atikramaNa|अतिक्रमण
n. (-णम्)<BR> ^1 Going over or beyond.<BR> ^2 Transgressing.<BR> ^3 Going away, passing.<BR> ^4 Passing away (as time), idling. E. क्रम् with अति, kŕit aff. ल्युट्.

atikramin|अतिक्रमिन्
m. f. n. (-मी-मिणी-मि)<BR> ^1 Transgressing.<BR> ^2 Exceeding, surpassing. E. अतिक्रम, taddh. aff. इनि, or क्रम् with अति, kŕit aff. इनि.

atikraanta|अतिक्रान्त
m. f. n. (-न्तः-न्ता-न्तम्)<BR> ^1 Transgressed, exceeded, passed in time, excelled, surpassed, or<BR> ^2 having transgressed, exceeded &c. See क्रम् with अति. E. क्रम् with अति, kŕit aff. क्त.

atikraantaniShedha|अतिक्रान्तनिषेध
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-धः-धा-धम्) Having transgressed a prohibition, having done what is prohibited by law. E. अतिक्रान्त and निषेध.

atikraamaka|अतिक्रामक
m. f. n. (-कः-का-कम्) Exceeding, one who oversteps due bounds. E. क्रम् with अति, kŕit aff. ण्वुल्. 

atikraamat|अतिक्रामत्
m. f. n. (-मन्-मन्ती-मत्) Transgressing, exceeding, surpassing &c. See क्रम् with अति. E. क्रम् with अति, kŕit aff. शतृ.

atixipta|अतिक्षिप्त
I. m. f. n. (-प्तः-प्ता-प्तम्) Thrown beyond, thrown outside &c. <BR>II. n. (-प्तम्) (In medicine.) A dislocation (see भग्न and सन्धिमुक्त), described as ‘when the two bones of a joint are forced out and cause much pain’. E. क्षिप् with अति, kŕit aff. क्त.

atiga|अतिग
m. f. n. (-गः-गा-गम्)<BR> ^1 Exceeding, going beyond.<BR> ^2 Surpassing, excelling. E. गम् with अति, kŕit aff. ड.

atigaNDa|अतिगण्ड
Bahuvr. I. m. f. n. (-ण्डः-ण्डा-ण्डम्) Having large cheeks or temples. <BR>II. m. (-ण्डः) The Yoga star of the sixth lunar mansion (see आर्द्रा), that star which serves as the index of the mansion. It is perhaps the 133d of Taurus. E. अति and गण्ड.

atigandha|अतिगन्ध
Bahuvr. I. m. f. n. (-न्धः-न्धा-न्धम्) Of strong or exceeding odour. <BR>II. m. (-न्धः)<BR> ^1 A fragrant grass, lemon-grass (Andropogon schœnanthus).<BR> ^2 Champac (Michelia champaca).<BR> ^3 A kind of Jasmin. See मुद्गर.<BR> ^4 Sulphur. E. अति and गन्ध.

atigandhaalu|अतिगन्धालु
Tatpur. m. (-लुः) The name of a creeper. See पुत्रदात्री. E. अति and गन्धालु.

atigarbita|अतिगर्बित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Very arrogant, very proud. E. अति and गर्बित.

atigava|अतिगव
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-वः-वा-वम्) Having gone beyond a cow, having surpassed a cow &c. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and गो (in the sense of the accusative), samásánta aff. टच्.

atigahana|अतिगहन
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-नः-ना-नम्) Very impervious or inaccessible. E. अति and गहन.

atigupta|अतिगुप्त
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-प्तः-प्ता-प्तम्) Very secret, closely hidden or concealed. E. अति and गुप्त.

atiguhaa|अतिगुहा
Tatpur. f. (-हा) A plant (Hemionites cordifolia, Rox.). See पृश्निपर्णी. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and गुहा (in the sense of the accusative); ‘rising above the ground’.

atigo|अतिगो
Tatpur. f. (-गौः) An excellent cow. E. अति and गो.

atigraha|अतिग्रह
m. (-हः) I. Overtaking, surpassing. E. ग्रह् with अति, kŕit aff. अच्. <BR>II. Tatpur. (In the philosophical terminology of the Upanishads) that which goes beyond the grahas or the eight instruments of apprehension i. e. the objects or functions of apprehension themselves: thus with the graha प्राण (meaning there ‘the nose’) corresponds the atigraha अपान (meaning there ‘fragrant substance’), with the graha वाच्, the atigraha नामन् and likewise, with the other six grahas जिह्वा, चक्षुस्, श्रोत्र, मनस्, हस्त, त्वच्, the atigrahas रस, रूप, शब्द, काम, कर्मन् and स्पर्श.--Also called अतिग्राह. E. अति and ग्रह (in the sense of the accusative).

atigraaha|अतिग्राह
Tatpur. m. (-हः) The same as अतिग्रह in its philosophical meaning. E. अति and ग्राह (in the sense of the accus.).

atigraahya|अतिग्राह्य
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-ह्यः-ह्या-ह्यम्) Very acceptable or agreeable. <BR>II. m. (-ह्यः) The name of three particular grahas or sacrificial vessels (see ग्रह), with which libations were made in the Jyotisht́oma sacrifice to Agni, Indra and Súrya. E. अति and ग्राह्य.

atigha|अतिघ
Tatpur. m. (-घः)<BR> ^1 A bludgeon, a weapon.<BR> ^2 Anger, wrath. E. अति and घ. 

atighnii|अतिघ्नी
Tatpur. f. (-घ्नी) The state of happiness, the state of profound sleep. (In the terminology of the Upanishads.) E. अति and घ्न, with ङीप् aff., ‘destroying thoroughly all unpleasant feelings’; sc. अवस्था.

atichara|अतिचर
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Going very much. <BR>II. f. (-रा) The name of a plant which grows in Bengal (Hibiscus mutabilis). See also पद्मचारिणी, अव्यथा, पद्मा and चारटी. E. अति (very much) and चर, or अति (sc. क्रान्त) and चर (going i. e. a living being, in the sense of the accusative); the plant being called so, because ‘it grows in impervious places and, therefore, goes beyond the reach of living beings’.

atichaara|अतिचार
m. (-रः) I.<BR> ^1 Going over or beyond.<BR> ^2 Surpassing, excelling. E. चर् with अति, kŕit aff. घञ्. <BR>II. Tatpur.<BR> ^1 Going quickly.<BR> ^2 The passage of a planet from one zodiacal sign to another, in a shorter than ordinary period. E. अति (exceedingly) and चार.

atichaarin|अतिचारिन्
m. f. n. (-री-रिणी-रि) Transgressing, surpassing. E. चर् with अति, kŕit aff. घिनुण्, the affix implying here habit or nature.

atichChatra|अतिच्छत्र
Tatpur. I. m. (-त्रः) A species of mushroom. (See छत्रा and पालघ्न.) <BR>II. f. (-त्रा)<BR> ^1 Anise (Anethum pimpinella).<BR> ^2 Barleria longifolia. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and छत्र (in the sense of the accusative), ‘surpassing a parasol’; in the fem. with टाप् aff.

atichChatraka|अतिच्छत्रक
I. m. (-कः) A mushroom. See the preceding. <BR>II. f. (-का) The same as अतिच्छत्रा. E. taddh. aff. कन् added to the last.

atichChanda|अतिच्छन्द
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-न्दः-न्दा-न्दम्) Without desire, free from worldly desire. Also अतिच्छन्दस्. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and छन्द (in the sense of the accusative), ‘having gone beyond desires’.

atichChandas|अतिच्छन्दस्
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-न्दाः-न्दाः-न्दः) The same as the preceding. <BR>II. f. n. (-न्दाः-न्दः) The name of two classes of metres regulated by number and quantity, the first of which comprises the classes अतिजगती, शक्वरी, अतिशक्वरी, अष्टि, अत्यष्टि, धृति, अतिधृति (qq. vv.) and the second the classes कृति, प्रकृति, आकृति, विकृति, सङ्कृति, अतिकृति (or अभिकृति), उत्कृति (qq. vv.). <BR>III. f. (-न्दाः) The name of one of the consecrated bricks or isht́akás. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and छन्दस् I. desire, II. metre (in the sense of the accusative) ‘going or having gone beyond desires’ and ‘going beyond the seven Chhandas or metres गायत्री, उष्णिह्, अनुष्टुभ्, बृहती, पङ्क्ति, त्रिष्टुभ् and जगती’.

atijagatii|अतिजगती
Tatpur. f. (-ती) The name of a class of metres regulated by number and quantity. See अतिच्छन्दस्. It comprises sixteen varieties and consists of a stanza of four lines, with thirteen syllables in each line. (See<BR> ^1 प्रहर्षिणी,<BR> ^2 रुचिरा (or अतिरुचिरा),<BR> ^3 मत्तमयूर (or माया),<BR> ^4 गौरी,<BR> ^5 मञ्जुभाषिणी (or प्रबोधिता, or सुनन्दिनी, or कनकप्रभा),<BR> ^6 चन्द्रिका (or क्षमा, or उत्पलिनी, or कुटिलगति),<BR> ^7 कलहंस (or चित्रवती, or सिंहनाद),<BR> ^8 चञ्चरिकावली,<BR> ^9 चन्द्रलेखा,<BR> ^10 विद्युत्,<BR> ^11 मृगेन्द्रमुख,<BR> ^12 तारक,<BR> ^12 क लाकन्द (or कन्द),<BR> ^14 पङ्कजावली (or पङ्कावली),<BR> ^15 चण्डी,<BR> ^16 प्रभावती.) E. अति (sc. क्रान्ता) and जगती (in the sense of the accusative) ‘going beyond the metre जगती q. v.’.

atijana|अतिजन
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-नः-ना-नम्) Solitary, lonely. E. अति (in the sense of अतिगत or अत्यन्तविगत) and जन; or perhaps as a Tatpur. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and जन (in the sense of the accusative).

atijara|अतिजर
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Exceedingly old. With respect to the declension of this word, see जरा and जरस्. E. अति and जरा.

atijava|अतिजव
Tatpur. I. m. (-वः) Extreme speed. <BR>II. m. f. n. (-वः-वा-वम्) Marching fast or fleet. E. अति and जव.

atijaagara|अतिजागर
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Very wakeful, restless. <BR>II. m. (-रः) The black curlew. E. अति and जागर.

atijaata|अतिजात
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Superior by birth (to the parents). E. अति and जात.

atijiirNa|अतिजीर्ण
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-र्णः-र्णा-र्णम्) Very old. E. अति and जीर्ण.

atiDiina|अतिडीन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Very lofty or very rapid flight of birds. E. अति and डीन.

atitaraam|अतितराम्
ind.<BR> ^1 Far more, far better (with a word following in the ablative or fifth case).<BR> ^2 Very much, excessively, exceedingly.<BR> ^3 Far beyond, far above (with a word following in the accusative or second case). E. अति, taddh. aff. तरप् and आमु. (अतितराम् may better be considered as the comparative degree of अति in the accus. of the femin.)

atitaarin|अतितारिन्
m. f. n. (-री-रिणी-रि) Crossing or getting over. E. तॄ with अति, kŕit aff. णिनि.

atitiixNa|अतितीक्ष्ण
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-क्ष्णः-क्ष्णा-क्ष्णम्) Very pungent, sharp, hot or acrid. E. अति and तीक्ष्ण.

atitiivra|अतितीव्र
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-व्रः-व्रा-व्रम्) Very sharp or pungent. <BR>II. f. (-व्रा) Dúb grass. See गण्डदूर्वा. E. अति and तीव्र.

atitRNNa|अतितृण्ण
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ण्णः-ण्णा-ण्णम्) Very much hurt or injured. E. अति and तृण्ण.

atitRpti|अतितृप्ति
Tatpur. f. (-प्तिः) Oversatisfaction, satisfying one's appetite too much. E. अति and तृप्ति.

atityad|अतित्यद्
Tatpur. Beyond that. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and त्यद् (in the sense of the accusative). This word seems to be only one of grammatical coinage, to show that the declension of त्यद् in compositions like these is like that of other nouns ending in द् and not that of the pronominal theme त्यद्; i. e. अतित्यद्, अतित्यदौ &c. (instead of अतिस्यः, अतित्यौ &c.).

atitvam|अतित्वम्
Tatpur. m. Surpassing thee. E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and त्वम् (in the sense of त्वाम्). This word seems to be, like the last, only a grammatical one and scarcely in real use; its declension is equally purely fictitious and varying, even, according to the different grammatical authorities. See the following and अतित्वाम्, अतियूयम्, also अत्यहम्.

atitvaan|अतित्वान्
Tatpur. The accus. in the plural of the preceding.

atitvaam|अतित्वाम्
Tatpur. The accusative in the singular and dual of अतित्वम्. 

atithi|अतिथि
I. 1. m. f. n. (-थिः-थी-थि) One who arrives and, though entirely unknown, is entitled to the rites of hospitality, a guest. See अतिथिन्. BREAḲ. m. (-थिः)<BR> ^1 A proper name of a king of Ayodhyá, the son of Kuśa and grandson of Ráma.<BR> ^2 The vaidik name of an attendant of Soma. (This latter meaning is more likely to be taken in a figurative sense, Soma being mentioned as the name of a king and Agni, Atithi, Śyena as those of his attendants). E. अत्, uń. aff. इथिन्. (अतिथि in the meaning of ‘guest’ is also explained as a Bahuvr. ‘one who has no kind of तिथि or holy day, who may arrive any day’ or ‘one who does not sojourn a whole tithi, but only one single night’, or ‘one who is not steady (when तिथि is supposed to be a mutilated form of स्थिति)’; all these explanations are artificial.) <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. (-थिः) Wrath, anger. E. अ priv. and तिथि ‘not restricted to a tithi, what may come at any time’.

atithikriyaa|अतिथिक्रिया
Tatpur. f. (-या) Hospitality considered as a religious duty. E. अतिथि and क्रिया.

atithigva|अतिथिग्व
Tatpur. m. (-ग्वः) A proper name or a vaidik epithet of Divodása. (Properly meaning: ‘worthy to be approached by guests, hospitable’. E. अतिथि and ग्व (from गम्, uń. aff. ड्व).

atithitva|अतिथित्व
n. (-त्वम्) Hospitality. E. अतिथि, taddh. aff. त्व.

atithidharma|अतिथिधर्म
Tatpur. m. (-र्मः) The proper quality which constitutes a claim to hospitality. E. अतिथि and धर्म.

atithidharmin|अतिथिधर्मिन्
m. f. n. (-र्मी-र्णिनी-मि) One who has the proper qualities which constitute a claim to hospitality. E. The preceding, taddh. aff. इनि.

atithin|अतिथिन्
I. m. f. n. (-थी-थिनी-थि) Wandering, travelling. (ved.) <BR>II. m. (-थी) The name of a king, called also Suhotra and otherwise Atithi. See अतिथि. E. अत्, uń. aff.(?) इथिन्.

atithidveSha|अतिथिद्वेष
Tatpur. m. (-षः) Inhospitality. E. अतिथि and द्वेष.

atithipuujana|अतिथिपूजन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Hospitality considered as one of the principal sacraments of the Hindus. E. अतिथि and पूजन.

atithipuujaa|अतिथिपूजा
Tatpur. f. (-जा). The same as the preceding. E. अतिथि and पूजा.

atithisatkaara|अतिथिसत्कार
Tatpur. m. (-रः) The rite of hospitality, the hospitable treatment of a guest. E. अतिथि and सत्कार.

atithisevaa|अतिथिसेवा
Tatpur. f. (-वा) Service of a guest, hospitality. E. अतिथि and सेवा.

atidagdha|अतिदग्ध
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-ग्धः-ग्धा-ग्धम्) Very much burnt. <BR>II. n. (-ग्धम्) (In med.) One of the four degrees of burns, described in the following manner: ‘when the flesh hangs down and the part is separated with the destruction of the vessels, joints &c., with fever, thirst, faintness, the tumour growing slowly and, when ripe, being colourless’. E. अति and दग्ध.

atidatta|अतिदत्त
Tatpur. m. (-त्तः) A proper name, the son of Súra or Rájádhideva. E. अति and दत्त.

atidarpa|अतिदर्प
I. Tatpur. m. (-र्पः) Excessive pride or arrogance. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-र्पः-र्पा-र्पम्) Very proud or arrogant. E. अति and दर्प.

atidarshin|अतिदर्शिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-र्शी-र्शिनी-र्शि) Seeing very far. E. अति and दर्शिन्.

atidaatR|अतिदातृ
Tatpur. m. (-ता) A liberal man. E. अति and दातृ. 

atidaana|अतिदान
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Munificence, giving largely. E. अति and दान.

atidaanta|अतिदान्त
Tatpur. m. (-न्तः) The name of a prince. Perhaps the same as, or another reading of अभिदान्त. E. अति and दान्त.

atidaaha|अतिदाह
Tatpur. m. (-हः)<BR> ^1 Great heat.<BR> ^2 Violent inflammation. E. अति and दाह.

atidiShTa|अतिदिष्ट
m. f. n. (-ष्टः-ष्टा-ष्टम्) Being the object of an अतिदेश (q. v.), of an additional or supplementary rule. E. दिश् with अति, kŕit aff. क्त.

atidiipya|अतिदीप्य
Tatpur. m. (-प्यः) The name of a plant (Plumbago rosea). Called also रक्तचित्रक. E. अति and दीप्य.

atidiirgha|अतिदीर्घ
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-र्घः-र्घा-र्घम्) Too or very long (in time and space). E. अति and दीर्घ.

atiduHsaha|अतिदुःसह
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-हः-हा-हम्) Quite intolerable, quite unbearable, not to be borne or endured. E. अति and दुःसह.

atidurgata|अतिदुर्गत
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) In great difficulty or distress. E. अति and दुर्गत.

atidurlambha|अतिदुर्लम्भ
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-म्भः-म्भा-म्भम्) Very difficult to obtain. E. अति and दुर्लम्भ. (The form दुर्लम्भ, however, occurs only as part of a compound, दुर्लभ or दुर्लाभ being the legitimate forms, when used alone.)

atiduShkara|अतिदुष्कर
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-रः-रा or -री-रम्) Very arduous, very difficult. E. अति and दुष्कर.

atiduura|अतिदूर
Tatpur. n. (-रम्) Excessive distance. (अतिदूरम्, अतिदूरात्, अतिदूरेण and अतिदूरे, especially in conjunction with न are used adverbially ‘not very far off’.) E. अति and दूर.

atideva|अतिदेव
Tatpur. m. (-वः) A superior god, one who surpasses the Gods. E. अति and देव (or according to others अति, sc. क्रान्त, and देव, in the sense of the accusative).

atidesha|अतिदेश
m. (-शः) A rule providing for something more than the ordinary or established rules (see प्रदेश, उपदेश) provide for and not comprehended by them; it may be either enjoined specially or derived from inference; if such a rule, in grammar, affects the form, gender &c. of a word, it is called रूपातिदेश, लिङ्गातिदेश &c.; in philosophy atideśas of a general or comprehensive nature are called सामान्यातिदेश and those restricted to a special case विशेषातिदेश. See also शास्त्रातिदेश, कार्यातिदेश, निमित्तातिदेश, व्यपदेशातिदेश. E. दिश् with अति, kŕit aff. घञ्.

atidoSha|अतिदोष
Tatpur. m. (-षः) A great fault. E. अति and दोष.

atidhanvan|अतिधन्वन्
Bahuvr. m. (-न्वा) The proper name of a descendant of Śunaka. E. अति and धन्वन्.

atidhRti|अतिधृति
Tatpur. f. (-तिः)<BR> ^1 The name of a class of metres which are regulated by number and quantity. See अतिच्छन्दस्. It comprises thirteen varieties and consists of a stanza of four lines with nineteen syllables in each line. (See<BR> ^1 शार्दूल or शार्दूलविक्रीडित,<BR> ^2 मेघविस्फुर्जित or विस्मित,<BR> ^3 पञ्चचामर,<BR> ^4 पुष्पदामन्,<BR> ^5 बिम्बा,<BR> ^6 छाया,<BR> ^7 मकरन्दिका,<BR> ^8 समुद्रतटा,<BR> ^9 सुरसा,<BR> ^10 मणिमञ्जरी,<BR> ^11 चन्द्रमाला or चन्द्र,<BR> ^12 धवलाङ्क or धवल,<BR> ^13 सम्भु.)<BR> ^2 (In arithmetic sometimes used to denote) the number nineteen. E. अति (sc. क्रान्ता) and धृति (in the sense of the accusative) ‘going beyond the metre धृति q. v.’. 

atidhenu|अतिधेनु
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-नुः-नुः-नु) Having excellent or a great many cows. E. अति and धेनु.

atinaaman|अतिनामन्
Bahuvr. m. (-मा) A proper name, one of the seven Ŕishis or Sages who preside over the reign of Chákshusha, the sixth Manu. E. अति and नामन्.

atinichRt|अतिनिचृत्
Tatpur. f. (-चृत्) The name of a vaidik metre regulated by the number of syllables; it consists of three Pádas of seven, six, and seven syllables in each; also read अतिनिवृत्. E. अति (sc. क्रान्ता) and निचृत् (or निवृत्), in the sense of the accusative.

atinidra|अतिनिद्र
I. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-द्रः-द्रा-द्रम्) One who sleeps inordinately. <BR>II. Tatpur. f. (-द्रा) Excessive sleep (also considered as a morbid symptom). <BR>III. Avyayíbh. (-द्रम्) After sleeping. E. अति and निद्रा.

atinivRt|अतिनिवृत्
Tatpur. f. (-वृत्). See अतिनिचृत्.

atinau|अतिनौ
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-नौः-नौः-नु) Landed from a boat. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and नौ (in the sense of the accusative) ‘gone beyond a boat’.

atipatana|अतिपतन
n. (-नम्) Transgressing, going beyond bounds. E. पत् with अति, kŕit aff. ल्युट्.

atipatita|अतिपतित
m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Transgressed, missed. See also अतिपन्न. E. पत् with अति, kŕit aff. क्त.

atipatti|अतिपत्ति
f. (-त्तिः) Going beyond, passing away. E. पत् with अति, kŕit aff. क्तिन्.

atipatra|अतिपत्र
Bahuvr. m. (-त्रः)<BR> ^1 A tree, see हस्तिकन्द.<BR> ^2 Another tree, the Teak tree. See शाकवृक्ष. E. अति and पत्र.

atipathin|अतिपथिन्
Tatpur. m. (-पन्था) A good road. E. अति and पथिन्, ‘a very road’.

atipada|अतिपद
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-दः-दा-दम्) Having one foot too much or more (as an exuberant metre; f. i. अतिपदा गायत्री, अतिपदा शक्वरी). E. अति and पद.

atipanna|अतिपन्न
m. f. n. (-न्नः-न्ना-न्नम्). The same as अतिपतित. E. पद् with अति, kŕit aff. क्त.

atipara|अतिपर
Tatpur. m. (-रः) I. A great enemy. E. अति and पर. <BR>II. One who has conquered his enemy. E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and पर (in the sense of the accusative).

atiparoxa|अतिपरोक्ष
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-क्षः-क्षा-क्षम्) Very imperceptible, very remote. E. अति and परोक्ष.

atiparoxavRtti|अतिपरोक्षवृत्ति
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-त्तिः-त्तिः-त्ति) Being of very remote explanation, very difficult to explain (as words the etymology of which is obscure). E. अतिपरोक्ष and वृत्ति.

atipaata|अतिपात
m. (-तः)<BR> ^1 Passing away.<BR> ^2 Transgression, neglect of duty, deviation from laws or customs, sin, offence.<BR> ^3 Contrariety, opposition. E. पत् with अति, kŕit aff. घञ्.

atipaataka|अतिपातक
Tatpur. n. (-कम्) The worst of the great sins, a heinous sin, viz. the sexual intercourse of a man with his mother, daughter or daughter-in-law and that of a woman with her son, father and father-in-law. E. अति and पातक.

atipaatita|अतिपातित
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Quite thrown, quite driven otu. <BR>II. n. (-तम्) (In medicine.) A dislocation, complete separation of a limb from the body (see भग्न and काण्डभग्न). E. अति and पातित. 

atipaatin|अतिपातिन्
m. f. n. (-ती-तिनी-ति) I. Going beyond, exceeding. E. पत् with अति, kŕit aff. घिणुन्. <BR>II. Tatpur. Passing very quick, acute (as a disease). E. अति and पातिन्.

atipaadanichRt|अतिपादनिचृत्
Tatpur. f. (-त्) The name of a vaidik metre regulated by the number of syllables. It is a species of the Gáyatrí metre and consists of three Pádas of six, eight and seven syllables in each. Also read अतिपादनिवृत्. E. अति (sc. क्रान्ता) and पादनिचृत् (or पादनिवृत्), in the sense of the accusative.

atipaadanivRt|अतिपादनिवृत्
Tatpur. f. (-त्). See the preceding.

atipitaamaha|अतिपितामह
Tatpur. m. (-हः) Surpassing the grand-father, better than his grand-father (as a grand-son). E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and पितामह (in the sense of the accusative).

atipitR|अतिपितृ
Tatpur. m. (-ता) Surpassing the father, better than his father (as a son). E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and पितृ (in the sense of the accusative).

atipuruSha|अतिपुरुष
Tatpur. m. (-षः) A great man, a great hero; also written अतिपूरुष. E. अति and पुरुष or पूरुष.

atipeshala|अतिपेशल
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-लः-ला-लम्) Very dexterous or clever. E. अति and पेशल.

atiprage|अतिप्रगे
Tatpur. ind. Very early or too early in the morning. E. अति and प्रगे.

atipramaaNa|अतिप्रमाण
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-णः-णा-णम्) Exceedingly large, very great. E. अति and प्रमाण.

atipravRtti|अतिप्रवृत्ति
Tatpur. f. (-त्तिः) Coming forth very much, running too abundantly &c. E. अति and प्रवृत्ति.

atipravRddha|अतिप्रवृद्ध
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-द्धः-द्धा-द्धम्)<BR> ^1 Too much grown, swollen &c.<BR> ^2 Too haughty, too arrogant. E. अति and प्रवृद्ध.

atiprashna|अतिप्रश्न
m. (-श्नः) A question which goes beyond its proper bounds, a question concerning a transcendental object. E. प्रच्छ् with अति, kŕit aff. नङ्.

atiprashnya|अतिप्रश्न्य
m. f. n. (-श्न्यः-श्न्या-श्न्यम्) Belonging to, referring to, being the object of a question which goes beyond its proper bounds, or concerns a transcendental object. E. अतिप्रश्न, taddh. aff. यत्.

atiprasakti|अतिप्रसक्ति
Tatpur. f. (-क्तिः) Being attached too much, too great attachment. See also the following. E. अति and प्रसक्ति.

atiprasanga|अतिप्रसङ्ग
m. (-ङ्गः) I. Tatpur. Too great attachment, being attached too much. E. अति and प्रसङ्ग. <BR>II. (In grammar, law and philosophy.) The applicability of a rule, definition, notion &c. extended too far: applying a rule &c. to a case, object &c. where properly it aught not to be applied. E. सञ्ज् with प्र and अति, kŕit aff. घञ्.

atiprasiddha|अतिप्रसिद्ध
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-द्धः-द्धा-द्धम्) Very notorious, quite known. E. अति and प्रसिद्ध.

atipreShita|अतिप्रेषित
Tatpur. n. (-तम्) The time after the ceremony with the प्रैष (q. v.) Mantras has been performed. E. अति (sc. क्रान्तम्) and प्रेषित (in the sense of the accusative).

atiprauDhayauvana|अतिप्रौढयौवन
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-नः-ना-नम्) Being in the fullness of youth. E. अति and प्रौढयौवन.

atibala|अतिबल
Bahuvr. I. m. f. n. (-लः-ला-लम्) Very strong, very powerful. <BR>II. m. (-लः)<BR> ^1 An active soldier.<BR> ^2 The name of a king. <BR>III. f. (-ला)<BR> ^1 The name of a medicinal plant ‘employed  against disorders from wind, worms, sickness, burning heat and thirst, excess of saliva, in pregnancy &c. and considered as possessing strengthening properties’ (Sidonia cordifolia and rhombifolia, or according to others Annona squamosa).<BR> ^2 A proper name, a daughter of Daksha and wife of Kaśyapa.<BR> ^3 The name of a mystical verse or charm, used as a mystical weapon. E. अति and बल.

atibaahu|अतिबाहु
Bahuvr. m. (-हुः) One of the seven Ŕishis or Sages who preside over the reign of the fourteenth Manu. E. अति and बाहु, ‘having very great arms’.

atibrahmacharya|अतिब्रह्मचर्य
Tatpur. n. (-र्यम्) Excess of chastity. E. अति and ब्रह्मचर्य.

atibrahman|अतिब्रह्मन्
Tatpur. m. (-ह्मा) The proper name of a king. E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and ब्रह्मन् (in the sense of the accusative).

atibhaara|अतिभार
I. Tatpur. m. (-रः)<BR> ^1 A great or excessive burden.<BR> ^2 (Figuratively.) Inexplicitness, great obscurity (of a sentence &c.). <BR>II. Bahuvr.(?) A proper name, according to a Puráńa, the son of Ŕiteyu and a descendant of Puru. See also अतिमार. E. अति and भार.

atibhaaraga|अतिभारग
Tatpur. m. (-गः) A mule. E. अतिभार and ग.

atibhaava|अतिभाव
m. (-वः) Surpassing, overcoming, overpowering. E. भू with अति, kŕit aff. घञ्.

atibhii|अतिभी
Bahuvr. m. (-भीः) Lightning, the flash accompanying thunder. E. अति and भी.

atibhiiShaNa|अतिभीषण
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-णः-णा-णम्) Very horrible, very formidable. E. अति and भीषण.

atibhuumi|अतिभूमि
Tatpur. f. (-मिः)<BR> ^1 Extensive land.<BR> ^2 Excess, extremeness, impropriety. E. अति and भूमि; (some explain this word by अतिशयस्य स्थानम्.)

atibhojana|अतिभोजन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Eating too much (considered also as a consequence of the disease भस्मक q. v.). E. अति and भोजन.

atibhruu|अतिभ्रू
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-भ्रूः-भ्रूः-भ्रु) Having very large eyebrows. E. अति and भ्रू.

atimangalya|अतिमङ्गल्य
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-ल्यः-ल्या-ल्यम्) Very auspicious &c. (See मङ्गल्य.) <BR>II. m. (-ल्यः) A fruit (Ægle, or Cratœva marmelos). See विल्व. E. अति and मङ्गल्य.

atimati|अतिमति
Tatpur. f. (-तिः) Pride, arrogance. E. अति and मति.

atimadhyandina|अतिमध्यन्दिन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) The height of midday. E. अति and मध्यन्दिन.

atimaryaada|अतिमर्याद
I. Tatpur. m. f. n. (-दः-दा-दम्) Very much, excessive. <BR>II. Avyayíbh. (-दम्) Excessively, beyond bounds. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and मर्यादा (in the sense of the accusative).

atimartya|अतिमर्त्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-र्त्यः-र्त्या-र्त्यम्) Superhuman, divine. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and मर्त्य (in the sense of the accusative).

atimaatra|अतिमात्र
I. Tatpur. m. f. n. (-त्रः-त्रा-त्रम्) Much, excessive. <BR>II. Avyayíbh. (-त्रम्) Excessively. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and मात्रा (in the sense of the accusative).

atimaan|अतिमान्
Tatpur. The accus. in the plural of अत्यहम् q. v.

atimaana|अतिमान
Tatpur. m. (-नः) Great pride or arrogance. E. अति and मान.

atimaanin|अतिमानिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-नी-निनी-नि) Very proud, very haughty or arrogant. E. अति and मानिन्. 

atimaanuSha|अतिमानुष
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-षः-षी-षम्)<BR> ^1 Superhuman, more than mortal.<BR> ^2 Immortal, divine. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and मानुष (in the sense of the accusative).

atimaam|अतिमाम्
Tatpur. The accusative in the singular and in the dual of अत्यहम् q. v.

atimaaya|अतिमाय
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्)<BR> ^1 Free from illusion.<BR> ^2 Entirely liberated or freed. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and माया (in the sense of the accusative).

atimaara|अतिमार
Tatpur. m. (-रः) The name of a prince; also written अतिभार q. v. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and मार (in the sense of the accusative).

atimaaruta|अतिमारुत
I. Tatpur. m. (-तः) A hurricane. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Very windy. E. अति and मारुत.

atimita|अतिमित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्)<BR> ^1 Not wet, not moistened. E. अ neg. and तिमित.<BR> ^2 Over measured. E. अति and मित.

atimukta|अतिमुक्त
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-क्तः-क्ता-क्तम्)<BR> ^1 Entirely liberated or freed.<BR> ^2 Free from passion or worldly desire.<BR> ^3 Seedless, barren. E. अति and मुक्त. <BR>II. m. (-क्तः) A large creeper bearing white fragrant flowers (Gærtnera racemosa), ‘used against colds, bilious heat, feverish delirium, hiccough, sickness &c.’ See also पुण्ड्रक, माधवीलता. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and मुक्ता (in the sense of the accusative) ‘surpassing pearls sc. in whiteness’. <BR>III. m. (-क्तः) A tree (Dalbergia oujeiniensis). E. अति and मुक्त ‘from its spreading very widely’.

atimuktaka|अतिमुक्तक
m. (-कः)<BR> ^1 A tree (Dalbergia oujeiniensis).<BR> ^2 A creeper (Gærtnera racemosa). See अतिमुक्त.<BR> ^3 Mountain ebony. See तिन्दुक.<BR> ^4 Another tree. See हरिमन्थ. E. अतिमुक्त, taddh. aff. कन्.

atimukti|अतिमुक्ति
f. (-क्तिः) Liberation from death. See मुक्ति, अतिमोक्ष and मोक्ष. E. मुच् with अति, kŕit aff. क्तिन्; or a Tatpur. consisting of अति and मुक्ति.

atimRtyu|अतिमृत्यु
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-त्युः-त्युः-त्यु) Overcoming death. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and मृत्यु (in the sense of the accusative).

atimaithuna|अतिमैथुन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Excess of sexual intercourse. E. अति and मैथुन.

atimoxa|अतिमोक्ष
m. (-क्षः) Liberation from death. See मोक्ष, मुक्ति and अतिमुक्ति. E. मोक्ष् with अति, kŕit aff. अच्; or a Tatpur. consisting of अति and मोक्ष.

atimodaa|अतिमोदा
Bahuvr. f. (-दा) A tree (Jasminum arboreum). See नवमल्लिका. E. अति and मोद.

atiyasha|अतियश
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-शः-शा-शम्) Very glorious, very celebrated. E. अति and यश (instead of यशस्). See the following.

atiyashas|अतियशस्
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-शाः-शाः-शः) Very glorious, very celebrated. E. अति and यशस्.

atiyaaja|अतियाज
Tatpur. m. (-जः) The name of a Ŕishi (properly meaning: a great sacrificer, very pious). E. अति and याज.

atiyuvan|अतियुवन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-युवा-यूनी or -युवती-युव) Very young. E. अति and युवन्.

atiyuuyam|अतियूयम्
Tatpur. The nominative in the plural of अतित्वम् q. v.

atiyoga|अतियोग
Tatpur. m. (-गः) Too great conflux, excessive combination, excess. E. अति and योग. 

atirakta|अतिरक्त
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-क्तः-क्ता-क्तम्) Very red. <BR>II. f. (-क्ता) One of the seven tongues of Agni. See अग्निजिह्वा. E. अति and रक्त.

atiratha|अतिरथ
Tatpur. m. (-थः) A mighty warrior or chief, one going to battle in a car. E. अति and रथ.

atirasaa|अतिरसा
Bahuvr. f. (-सा) The name of several plants. See मूर्वा, रास्ना, क्लीतनक. E. अति and रस.

atiraajakumaari|अतिराजकुमारि
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-रिः-रिः-रि) Surpassing a princess. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and राजकुमारी (in the sense of the accusative).

atiraajan|अतिराजन्
Tatpur. m. (-जा)<BR> ^1 An excellent, a mighty king. E. अति and राजन्. See अतिराजी.<BR> ^2 One who surpasses a king. E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and राजन् (in the sense of the accusative). See अतिराज्ञी.

atiraajay|अतिराजय्
denom. par. (-यति) To surpass a king. E. अतिराजन् (one who surpasses a king), denom. aff. णिच्.

atiraajii|अतिराजी
Tatpur. m. (-जी) An excellent queen. E. अति and राजन्, samásánta aff. टच् and fem. aff. ङीप्. (The masculine form of this word which would be अतिराज, does not exist. See अतिराजन्, 1.)

atiraaJNii|अतिराज्ञी
Tatpur. m. (-ज्ञी) A woman who surpasses a king. E. See अतिराजन्, 2, fem. aff. ङीप्.

atiraatra|अतिरात्र
Tatpur. m. (-त्रः)<BR> ^1 The name of the fifth part or Somasansthá of the Jyotisht́oma sacrifice, for the complete performance of which, however, it is not considered nitya, essential or obligatory but kámya, voluntary, viz. if the sacrificer institutes it for the sake of progeny, and therefore anitya, not always taking place, supererogatory. (See अग्निष्टोम.)<BR> ^2 The usual beginning and concluding part of those Ahargańa sacrifices which are called Sattra (q. v.) and the beginning or the concluding part of those which are called Ahína (q. v.). There are, however, exceptions to this rule, see f. i. पञ्चदशरात्र, कुण्डपायिनामयन.<BR> ^3 The name of the Sámaveda verse which closes the ceremonies of the sacrifices mentioned before.<BR> ^4 A proper name, the son of Chákshusha or the sixth Manu by Nadvalá. E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and रात्रि (in the sense of the accusative), samásánta aff. अच्; properly meaning ‘lasting beyond a night’.

atiraatrasavaniiyapashu|अतिरात्रसवनीयपशु
Tatpur. m. (-शुः) The savaníyapaśu (q. v.) or sacrificial animal in the Atirátra (q. v.). It is a ewe consecrated to Saraswatí and subject to the regulations which exist for the अग्नीषोमीयपशु (q. v.) E. अतिरात्र and सवनीयपशु.

atirikta|अतिरिक्त
m. f. n. (-क्तः-क्ता-क्तम्) Excessive, exceeding. E. रिच् with अति, kŕit aff. क्त.

atiriktataa|अतिरिक्तता
f. (-ता) Increase of bulk or quantity, expansion, enlargement, elevation, &c. E. taddh. aff. तल् added to the preceding.

atiriktaanga|अतिरिक्ताङ्ग
I. Tatpur. n. (-ङ्गम्) An additional or extra limb. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-ङ्गः-ङ्गा-ङ्गम्) Having a limb too much (f. i. six fingers). E. अतिरिक्त and अङ्ग.

atiruch|अतिरुच्
Tatpur. m. (-रुक्र्) The knee of a horse. E. अति and रुच् ‘very bright’(?).

atiruchira|अतिरुचिर
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Very beautiful, very pleasing. <BR>II. f. (-रा) The name of two metres; viz.<BR> ^1 A metre re gulated by quantity, consisting of a stanza of four lines with twenty-nine syllables to each couplet, or according to others, a variety of the Gítyáryá, with thirty syllables in the first couplet and thirty-two in the second. Also called चूडिका or चूलिका.<BR> ^2 A metre regulated by number and quantity; a variety of the metre अतिजगती (q. v.) and consisting of a stanza of four lines with the following feet in each line: {??} Also called रुचिरा. E. अति and रुचिर.

atireka|अतिरेक
m. (-कः) Going over, exceeding, excess. Also used as adject. in the three genders, excessive. Also written अतीरेक. E. रिच् with अति, kŕit aff. घञ्.

atirekin|अतिरेकिन्
m. f. n. (-की-किणी-कि) More, superior. E. अतिरेक, taddh. aff. इनि.

atirai|अतिरै
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-रैः-रैः-रि) One who goes beyond his wealth or property, extravagant. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and रै (in the sense of the accusative).

atiroga|अतिरोग
Tatpur. m. (-गः) Consumption (Phthisis pulmonalis). E. अति and रोग.

atiromasha|अतिरोमश
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-शः-शा-शम्) Very hairy, too hairy. See अतिलोमश. <BR>II. m. (-शः) A wild goat, or according to some, a large monkey. E. अति and रोमश.

atilaxmii|अतिलक्ष्मी
I. Tatpur. f. (-क्ष्मीः) Great fortune, great beauty &c. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-क्ष्मीः-क्ष्मीः-क्ष्मि) Very fortunate, very beautiful &c. E. अति and लक्ष्मी.

atilamba|अतिलम्ब
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-म्बः-म्बा-म्बम्) Very spacious, very large or extended. E. अति and लम्ब.

atilihaa|अतिलिहा
Tatpur.(?) f. (-हा) A Prákrit metre regulated by quantity; it consists of a stanza of four lines with sixteen mátrás in each line, does not contain an Amphibrachys and ends in a Pyrrhichius. Also called अठिल्ला. E. अति and लिह(?).

atilubdha|अतिलुब्ध
m. f. n. (-ब्धः-ब्धा-ब्धम्) Very covetous. E. अति and लुब्ध.

atilobha|अतिलोभ
I. Tatpur. m. (-भः) Excessive desire or greediness. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-भः-भा-भम्) Very greedy, very covetous. E. अति and लोभ.

atilobhataa|अतिलोभता
f. (-ता) Great greediness. E. अतिलोभ (II), taddh. aff. तल्.

atiloma|अतिलोम
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-मः-मा-मम्) Having too many or very many hairs on the body, too hairy, very hairy. E. अति and लोम.

atilomasha|अतिलोमश
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-शः-शा-शम्) Too hairy, very hairy. <BR>II. f. (-शा) A potherb (Convolvulus argenteus). E. अति and लोमश.

atilohita|अतिलोहित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Very red. E. अति and लोहित.

atilaulya|अतिलौल्य
Tatpur. n. (-ल्यम्) Excessive desire or greediness. E. अति and लौल्य.

ativaktR|अतिवक्तृ
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-क्ता-क्त्री-क्तृ) Loquacious, talkative. E. अति and वक्तृ.

ativakra|अतिवक्र
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-क्रः-क्रा-क्रम्) Very crooked, very oblique &c. <BR>II. f. (-क्रा) One of the eight gatis or kinds of motion of a planet. (See गति.) E. अति and वक्र. 

ativayam|अतिवयम्
Tatpur. The nominative in the plural of अत्यहम् q. v.

ativartana|अतिवर्तन
n. (-नम्) An accident, a circumstance not capable of being prevented or guarded against, and which, therefore, does not render a person liable to punishment. E. वृत् with अति, kŕit aff. ल्युट् ‘out of the reach of punishment’.

ativartin|अतिवर्तिन्
m. f. n. (-र्ती-र्तिनी-र्ति)<BR> ^1 Going beyond.<BR> ^2 Transgressing, offending. E. वृत् with अति, kŕit aff. इनि.

ativartula|अतिवर्तुल
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-लः-ला-लम्) Very round, circular &c. <BR>II. m. (-लः) A kind of potherb. See कलाय. E. अति and वर्तुल.

ativaada|अतिवाद
m. (-दः) Opprobrious or harsh speech. Another reading of this word is अभिवाद. E. वद् with अति, kŕit aff. घञ् ‘a speech going beyond its proper bounds’.

ativaadin|अतिवादिन्
m. f. n. (-दी-दिनी-दि) Speaking more than is proper. E. वद् with अति, kŕit aff. णिनि (implying in this instance habit or nature).

ativaalaka|अतिवालक
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-कः-का-कम्) Childish. <BR>II. m. (-कः) An infant. E. अति and वालक.

ativaasa|अतिवास
Tatpur. m. (सः) The fast observed on the day preceding that in which the Śráddha or presentation of oblations to deceased ancestors is performed. E. अति and वास.

ativaahana|अतिवाहन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Excessive carrying or toiling, carrying or toiling too much. E. अति and वाहन.

ativaahika|अतिवाहिक
m. (-कः) An infernal spirit, an inhabitant of the hell. E. अतिवाह, taddh. aff. ठक् (having to toil very hard; see यात्य).

ativikaTa|अतिविकट
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-टः-टा-टम्) Very fierce, very formidable. <BR>II. m. (-टः) A vicious elephant. E. अति and विकट.

atividdha|अतिविद्ध
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-द्धः-द्धा-द्धम्) Pierced through, transfixed. E. अति and विद्ध.

ativilambin|अतिविलम्बिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-म्बी-म्बिनी-म्बि) Very dilatory, very slow. E. अति and विलम्बिन्.

ativishrabdhanavoDhaa|अतिविश्रब्धनवोढा
Karmadh. f. (-ढा) One of the female characters in the amatory poetry of the Hindus, described as very much attached to her husband, but being sarcastic when he is in fault and firm, and abusive when he is in fault but weak. E. अति-विश्रब्ध and नवोढा.

ativishva|अतिविश्व
Tatpur. m. (-श्वः) The name of a Muni. E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and विश्व (in the sense of the accusative) ‘beyond all’.

ativiSha|अतिविष
I. m. f. n. (-षः-षा-षम्)<BR> ^1 Bahuvr. Very poisonous.<BR> ^2 Tatpur. Exceeding or subduing poison. <BR>II. Tatpur. (or Bahuvr.) f. (-षा) The name of a most poisonous plant growing in Nepal used in medicine as an antidote and also against disorders produced by bilious fevers, dysentery, sickness, preternatural parturition &c. Its bark is also employed in dying; it is of three kinds, white, red and black. The root is employed by the natives of India and Nepal to poison the barbs of arrows (Aconitum ferox). E. Bahuvr. अति and विष; Tatpur. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and विष (in the sense of the accusative).

ativRtti|अतिवृत्ति
f. (-त्तिः) I. Going beyond, not being appropriate. E. वृत् with अति, kŕit aff. क्तिन्. <BR>II. Tatpur. Excess, abundance. E. अति and वृत्ति. 

ativRShTi|अतिवृष्टि
Tatpur. f. (-ष्टिः) Heavy rain, excess of rain. E. अति and वृष्टि.

ativRShTihata|अतिवृष्टिहत
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Injured by heavy rain. E. अतिवृष्टि and हत.

ativela|अतिवेल
I. Tatpur. m. f. n. (-लः-ला-लम्) Much, excessive. <BR>II. Avyayíbh. (-लम्) Excessively. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and वेला (in the sense of the accusative).

ativoDhR|अतिवोढृ
m. (-ढा) One who carries over or beyond. E. वह् with अति, kŕit aff. तृच्.

ativyathana|अतिव्यथन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Causing excessive pain or agony. E. अति and व्यथन.

ativyathaa|अतिव्यथा
Tatpur. f. (-था) Excessive pain, agony. E. अति and व्यथा.

ativyaya|अतिव्यय
Tatpur. m. (-यः) Extravagance, great expenditure. E. अति and व्यय.

ativyaadhin|अतिव्याधिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-धी-धिनी-धि) Piercing through, transfixing. E. अति and व्याधिन्.

ativyaapta|अतिव्याप्त
m. f. n. (-प्तः-प्ता-प्तम्) (In grammar and philosophy.) Obtained through generalizing by going beyond the mark or too far, inferred without being warranted by the rules, premises &c. given, not authorised. E. आप् with वि and अति, kŕit aff. क्त.

ativyaapti|अतिव्याप्ति
f. (-प्तिः) (In grammar and philosophy.) Generalising by going beyond the mark or too far, drawing an inference unwarranted by the premises, rules &c.; applying a rule, definition, notion &c. to a case, object &c. where it aught not to be applied. E. आप् with वि and अति, kŕit aff. क्तिन्.

atishakkarii|अतिशक्करी
f. (-री). See अतिशक्वरी which is the more correct reading of this word.

atishakta|अतिशक्त
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-क्तः-क्ता-क्तम्) Very powerful. E. अति and शक्त.

atishakti|अतिशक्ति
Tatpur. f. (-क्तिः) Great power. E. अति and शक्ति.

atishaktitaa|अतिशक्तिता
f. (-ता) Heroick valor, prowess. E. अतिशक्ति, taddh. aff. तल्.

atishaktibhaaj|अतिशक्तिभाज्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-क्) Possessing great power. E. अतिशक्ति and भाज्.

atishakvarii|अतिशक्वरी
Tatpur. f. (-री) The name of a class of metres regulated by number and quantity. See अतिच्छन्दस्. It consists in the classic Sanskŕit of a stanza of four lines with fifteen syllables in each line and comprises eighteen varieties. (See<BR> ^1 चन्द्रावर्ता,<BR> ^2 माला or स्रज्,<BR> ^3 मणिगुणनिकर,<BR> ^4 मालिनी or नन्दीमुखी,<BR> ^5 चन्द्रलेखा,<BR> ^6 कामक्रीडा or लीलाखेला or सरङ्गक,<BR> ^7 प्रभद्रक or सुभद्रक or सुकेसर,<BR> ^8 एला,<BR> ^9 उपमालिनी,<BR> ^10 विपिनतिलक,<BR> ^11 चित्रा,<BR> ^12 तुणक or चामर,<BR> ^13 भ्रमरावली,<BR> ^14 मनहंस,<BR> ^15 सरभ or शशिकला,<BR> ^16 निशिपाल,<BR> ^17 उत्सर,<BR> ^18 हंस.) Also written, though not correctly, अतिशक्करी. E. अति (sc. क्रान्ता) and शक्वरी (in the sense of the accusative), another metre.

atishaya|अतिशय
I. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Excellent, superior, excessive. (The femin. is very seldom used.) <BR>II. m. (-यः)<BR> ^1 Excellence, superiority, excessiveness. (अतिशयेन used adverbially.)<BR> ^2 Advantage, visible result of an action (opposed to अपूर्व q. v.).<BR> ^3 A superhuman quality inherent to a Jaina Arhat; there are thirty-four such qualities belonging to them, four of which regard their per sonal accomplishment, eleven their supernatural powers and the remaining twenty-nine their celestial attributes. <BR>III. n. (-यम्) used as adverb. Very much, excessive. E. शी with अति, kŕit aff. अच्.

atishayana|अतिशयन
I. m. f. n. (-नः-नी-नम्) Very much, excessive. <BR>II. f. (-नी) A metre regulated by number and quantity; a variety of the class called अत्यष्टि (q. v.) and consisting of a stanza of four lines with the following feet in each line: {??} Also called चित्रलेखा. <BR>III. n. (-नम्) used as adverb. Excessively. E. शी with अति, kŕit aff. ल्युट्.

atishayita|अतिशयित
m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Very much, excessive, superior. See अतिशेत. E. शी in the caus. with अति, kŕit aff. क्त.

atishayin|अतिशयिन्
m. f. n. (-यी-यिनी-यि) Exceeding, superior. E. शी with अति, kŕit aff. इनि.

atishasta|अतिशस्त
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-स्तः-स्ता-स्तम्) Preeminent, very excellent. E. अति and शस्त.

atishayokti|अतिशयोक्ति
Tatpur. f. (-क्तिः)<BR> ^1 Extreme assertion.<BR> ^2 Verbosity, prolixity.<BR> ^3 (In rhetoric.) Hyperbole. See अत्युक्ति. E. अतिशय and उक्ति.

atishastra|अतिशस्त्र
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-स्त्रः-स्त्रा-स्त्रम्) Surpassing a weapon. more injurious or powerful than a weapon. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and शस्त्र (in the sense of the accusative).

atishaakvara|अतिशाक्वर
m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Belonging to, written in the metre Atiśakvarí. E. अतिशक्वरी, taddh. aff. अण्.

atishaayana|अतिशायन
n. (-नम्) Excellence, superiority, excessiveness. अतिशायनम् used as adverb. E. शी with अति, kŕit aff. ल्युट्.

atishaayin|अतिशायिन्
m. f. n. (-यी-यिनी-यि) Very much, excessive. E. शी with अति, kŕit aff. णिनि.

atishiitam|अतिशीतम्
Avyayíbh. After the cold (weather &c.). E. अति and शीत.

atishukla|अतिशुक्ल
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-क्लः-क्ला-क्लम्) Very white, too white. E. अति and शुक्ल.

atisheta|अतिशेत
