atisarga|अतिसर्ग
m. (-र्गः)<BR> ^1 Giving away, spending.<BR> ^2 Full leave, unrestricted permission. See अन्ववसर्ग. E. सृज् with अति, kŕit aff. घञ्.

atisarjana|अतिसर्जन
n. (-नम्)<BR> ^1 Liberality, giving.<BR> ^2 A gift, a donation.<BR> ^3 Appointing, engaging.<BR> ^4 Slaughter, killing. E. सृज् with अति, kŕit aff. ल्युट्.

atisarva|अतिसर्व
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-र्वः-र्वा-र्वम्) Above all, beyond all. (The masc. used as a proper name or as an epithet of a divinity; see अतिविश्व.) E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and सर्व (in the sense of the accusative).

atisaaMvatsara|अतिसांवत्सर
m. f. n. (-रः-री-रम्) Going or lasting beyond a year. E. अतिसंवत्सर (beyond a year), taddh. aff. अण्.

atisaadhvasa|अतिसाध्वस
Tatpur. n. (-सम्) Extreme fear. E. अति and साध्वस.

atisaantapana|अतिसान्तपन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Severe penance or expiation, especially for the guilt of eating unclean animals; taking as food nothing but cow's urine, cowdung, curds, milk, and ghee, each two days in succession. See सान्तपन and महासान्तपन. E. अति and सान्तपन.

atisaamyaa|अतिसाम्या
Bahuvr. f. (-म्या) The sweet juice of Bengal madder (लतायष्टि). E. अति and साम्य.

atisaayam|अतिसायम्
Tatpur. ind. Very late in the evening. E. अति and सायम्.

atisaara|अतिसार
m. (-रः) Dysentery or diarrhœa, described as produced by vitiated bile or air or phlegm or by these three humours collectively or by grief or by vitiated mucus in the abdomen; according to others also by various other reasons and comprised under acute and chronic dysentery. (See पित्तातिसार, वातातिसार, श्लेष्मातिसार, शोकातिसार, आ मातिसार, पक्वातिसार.) An older division is that in ज्वरातिसार, वातातिसार, पित्तातिसार, श्लेष्मातिसार, रक्तातिसार, सन्निपातातिसार (qq. vv.). Also written अतीसार. E. सृ with अति, kŕit aff. घञ्.

atisaarakin|अतिसारकिन्
m. f. n. (-की-किणी-कि) Dysenteric, afflicted with dysentery. Also written अतीसारकिन्. E. अतिसार, taddh. aff. इनि and ágama कुक्.

atisaarin|अतिसारिन्
m. f. n. (-री-रिणी-रि) Afflicted with dysentery. E. अतिसार, taddh. aff. इनि.

atisujana|अतिसुजन
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-नः-ना-नम्) Very good, very virtuous or respectable. E. अति and सुजन.

atisundara|अतिसुन्दर
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Very handsome, very beautiful. <BR>II. m. (-रः) The name of a metre regulated by number and quantity; a variety of the class called अष्टि, consisting of a stanza of four lines with the following feet in each line:{??} Also called चित्र, चित्रसङ्ग or चञ्चला. E. अति and सुन्दर.

atisuhita|अतिसुहित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Overkind, more than affectionate &c. E. अति and सुहित.

atisRShTi|अतिसृष्टि
