atura|अतुर
Tatpur. m. (-रः) (ved.) Not liberal. E. अ neg. and तुर.

atula|अतुल
Bahuvr. I. m. f. n. (-लः-ला-लम्) Unequalled. <BR>II. m. (-लः) A plant bearing an oily seed (Sesamum orientale). See तिल. E. अ priv. and तुला.

atulya|अतुल्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ल्यः-ल्या-ल्यम्) Unequalled, unparalleled. E. अ neg. and तुल्य.

atuShaarakara|अतुषारकर
Bahuvr. m. (-रः) The sun. E. अ-तुषार (not cold) and कर ‘whose rays are not cold’.

atuShTi|अतुष्टि
Tatpur. f. (-ष्टिः) Dissatisfaction, displeasure. E. अ neg. and तुष्टि.

atuhinadhaaman|अतुहिनधामन्
Bahuvr. m. (-मा) The sun. E. अ-तुहिन and धामन्. See the following.

atuhinarashmi|अतुहिनरश्मि
Bahuvr. m. (-श्मिः) The sun. E. अ-तुहिन and रश्मि ‘whose rays are not cold’, also analogous compounds, as अतुहिनरुचि &c.

atuutuji|अतूतुजि
Tatpur. m. (-जिः) (ved.) Not fast, slow. E. अ neg. and तूतुजि.

atuurta|अतूर्त
Tatpur. (ved.) I. m. f. n. (-र्तः-र्ता-र्तम्)<BR> ^1 Unhurt, uninjured.<BR> ^2 Not hastening, not going speedily. <BR>II. n. (-र्तम्) The illimited space. E. अ neg. and तूर्त.

atuurtadaxa|अतूर्तदक्ष
Bahuvr. m. (-क्षः) (ved.) Of unhurt power, irresistible; an epithet of the Aświns. E. अतूर्त and दक्ष. 

atuurtapathin|अतूर्तपथिन्
Bahuvr. m. (-न्थाः) (ved.) Whose path is unhurt or without obstacles; an epithet of Váyu and of Aryaman, one of the Ádityas. E. अतूर्त and पथिन्.

atRNaada|अतृणाद
Tatpur. m. (-दः) A recently born calf. E. अ neg. and तृणाद ‘not or not yet eating grass’.

atRNyaa|अतृण्या
Tatpur. f. (-ण्या) A small quantity of grass. E. अ neg. and तृण्या (a quantity of grass).

atRdila|अतृदिल
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-लः-ला-लम्) (ved.) Not brittle, solid. E. अ neg. and तृदिल.

atRpa|अतृप
Bahuvr. m. (-पः) (ved.) Not satisfied. E. अ priv. and तृपा(?).

atRShya|अतृष्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ष्यः-ष्या-ष्यम्) (ved.) Not suffering thirst. E. अ neg. and तृष्य.

atejas|अतेजस्
I. Tatpur. n. (-जः)<BR> ^1 Shade, shadow.<BR> ^2 Insignificance, feebleness, imbecility. E. अ neg. and तेजस्. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-जाः-जाः-जः) Dark, dim, dull. E. अ priv. and तेजस्.

atejaska|अतेजस्क
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-स्कः-स्का-स्कम्) Dark, dim, dull. E. अ priv. and तेजस्, samásánta aff. कप्.

atejasvin|अतेजस्विन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-स्वी-स्विनी-स्वि) Void of splendour or energy. E. अ neg. and तेजस्विन्.

atoShaNiiya|अतोषणीय
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Implacable, not to be appeased. E. अ neg. and तोषणीय.

atka|अत्क
I. m. f. n. (-कः-का-कम्) A traveller. <BR>II. m. (-कः)<BR> ^1 A limb, a member of the body.<BR> ^2 (ved.) Moisture, fluid.<BR> ^3 (ved.) Armour, mail.<BR> ^4 (ved.) Thunderbolt. lightning(?).<BR> ^5 (ved.) The name of an Asura, a synonyme of Vŕitra. E. अत्, uń. aff. कन्.

atkiila|अत्कील
m. (-लः) See उत्कील, the more correct reading of this word.

attaa|अत्ता
f. (-त्ता)<BR> ^1 A mother.<BR> ^2 An elder sister.<BR> ^3 A mother's elder sister. (In Prákŕit: a mother in law.) E. unknown. See also अत्ति, अत्तिका.

atti|अत्ति
I. f. (-त्तिः) (In theatrical language.) An elder sister. E. unknown. See the preceding. <BR>II. m. (-त्तिः) (ved.) An eater, one who eats. E. अद्, uń. aff. ति.

attikaa|अत्तिका
f. (-का) (In theatrical language.) An elder sister. E. अत्ता a mother, and कन् affix, ‘who is, as it were, a mother’. Also written अन्तिका and अर्तिका.

attR|अत्तृ
m. f. n. (-त्ता-त्त्री-त्तृ) An eater, one who eats. See अत्त्रिन्. E. अद्, kŕit aff. तृच्.

attra|अत्त्र
I. m. (-त्त्रः) and II. n. (-त्त्रम्). See अत्र III. and IV., the less correct, but more usual reading of this vaidik word.

attri|अत्त्रि
m. (-त्त्रिः). See अत्रि the less correct, but more usual reading of this word. E. अद्, uń. aff. त्रिप्. See the following.

attrin|अत्त्रिन्
m. (-त्त्री). See अत्रिन्, the less correct, but more usual reading of this vaidik word. E. अद्, uń. aff. त्रिनि; or according to others, अत्त्र (food), taddh. aff. इनि. The plur. अत्त्रिणः is also explained, as an irregul. plural of अत्तृ, with ágama इनुङ्.

atna|अत्न
m. (-त्नः) The sun. E. अत्, uń. aff. न. See the following.

atnu|अत्नु
m. (-त्नुः) The sun. E. अत्, uń. aff. क्नु.

atya|अत्य
m. (-त्यः) (ved.) A horse. E. अत्, uń. aff. य.

atyaMhas|अत्यंहस्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-हाः-हाः-हः) (ved.) Beyond sin, free from sin. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and अंहस् (in the sense of the accusative).

atyagni|अत्यग्नि
Tatpur. I. m. (-ग्निः) Too quick digestion, described as  ‘followed by burning heat in throat, palate and lips’. E. अति and अग्नि. <BR>II. m. f. n. (-ग्निः-ग्निः-ग्नि) Surpassing fire (f. i. in brilliancy). E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and अग्नि (in the sense of the accus.).

atyagniShToma|अत्यग्निष्टोम
Tatpur. m. (-मः)<BR> ^1 The name of the second part or Somasansthá of the Jyotisht́oma sacrifice, for the complete performance of which, however, it is not considered nitya, essential or obligatory, as the Agnisht́oma (q. v.), but kámya, voluntary and therefore anitya, supererogatory.<BR> ^2 The name of the Sámaveda verse which closes the ceremonies of this sacrifice. E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and अग्निष्टोम (in the sense of the accus.), ‘going beyond, coming after the Agnisht́oma’.

atyankusha|अत्यङ्कुश
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-शः-शा-शम्) No more controllable by a hook, unmanageable, vicious (as an elephant). E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and अङ्कुश (in the sense of the accusative).

atyangula|अत्यङ्गुल
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-लः-ला-लम्) Surpassing, going beyond a finger or an angula-incasure. (See अङ्गुलि.) E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and अङ्गुलि (in the sense of the accusative), samásánta aff. अच्.

atyadhvan|अत्यध्वन्
Tatpur. m. (-ध्वा)<BR> ^1 A very great way or road.<BR> ^2 Travelling very or too much. E. अति and अध्वन्.

atyanila|अत्यनिल
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-लः-ला-लम्) Surpassing the wind (in quickness &c.). E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and अनिल (in the sense of the accusative).

atyanta|अत्यन्त
I. Tatpur. m. f. n. (-न्तः-न्ता-न्तम्)<BR> ^1 Excessive, very much, very far.<BR> ^2 Complete, thorough.<BR> ^3 Uninterrupted, continual (in space or time). II. Avyayíbh. (-न्तम्)<BR> ^1 Excessively.<BR> ^2 Completely.<BR> ^3 Always, continually. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and अन्त (in the sense of the accusative).

atyantakopana|अत्यन्तकोपन
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-नः-ना-नम्) Very passionate, fierce, violent. E. अत्यन्त and कोपन.

atyantaga|अत्यन्तग
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-गः-गा-गम्) What goes very much or quickly. E. अत्यन्त and ग.

atyantagata|अत्यन्तगत
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Completely established or pertinent, always applicable (as a rule). E. अत्यन्त and गत.

atyantagati|अत्यन्तगति
Tatpur. f. (-तिः) (In grammar.) The sense of ‘completely, thoroughly’ (opposed to the sense of ‘diminutive’). See अनत्यन्तगति. E. अत्यन्त (complete, thorough) and गति (sense, understanding).

atyantagaamin|अत्यन्तगामिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-मी-मिनी-मि) Going very much or quickly, going very far. E. अत्यन्त and गामिन्.

atyantaguNin|अत्यन्तगुणिन्
m. f. n. (-णी-णिनी-णि) Having highly good qualities. E. अत्यन्त-गुण (highly good quality), taddh. aff. इनि.

atyantatiraskRtavaachyadhvani|अत्यन्ततिरस्कृतवाच्यध्वनि
Karmadh. m. (-निः) (In rhetoric.) A metaphorical expression, when the word expressing the figure or comparison drops its literal sense in order to become appropriate for the comparison; f. i. in the sentence ‘the moon does not shine, like a mirror which has become blind by breathing upon it’--the word ‘blind’ loses its literal meaning, to serve as a comparison for ‘the not shining’ of the moon with which it has no common quality. E. अत्यन्त, तिरस्कृत, वाच्य (these three words forming a Bahuvr.) and ध्वनि.

atyantapiiDana|अत्यन्तपीडन
Karmadh. n. (-नम्) Causing excessive pain or agony. E. अत्यन्त and पीडन.

atyantavaasin|अत्यन्तवासिन्
Karmadh. m. (-सी) The Brahman who con tinues to live with his spiritual preceptor and always remains in the condition of a religious student. See नैष्ठिक. E. अत्यन्त and वासिन्.

atyantasaMyoga|अत्यन्तसंयोग
Karmadh. m. (-गः) (In grammar.) The intimate proximity (of two words), the connexion of two words without any other word standing between them. E. अत्यन्त and संयोग.

atyantasamparka|अत्यन्तसम्पर्क
Karmadh. m. (-र्कः) Too frequent sexual intercourse. E. अत्यन्त and सम्पर्क.

atyantasukumaara|अत्यन्तसुकुमार
Tatpur. m. (-रः) A species of grain (Panicum Italicum). E. अत्यन्त and सुकुमार ‘extremely soft’.

atyantaabhaava|अत्यन्ताभाव
Karmadh. m. (-वः) (In the Vaiśeshika philosophy.) Absolute negation or non-existence, one of the four kinds of अभाव q. v. E. अत्यन्त and अभाव.

atyantika|अत्यन्तिक
m. f. n. (-कः-का-कम्) I. Tatpur. Very near, very proximate. E. अति and अन्तिक. <BR>II. Going much or quickly, going very far. E. अत्यन्त, taddh. aff. ठन्.

atyantiina|अत्यन्तीन
m. f. n. (-नः-ना-नम्) Going much or quickly, going very far. E. अत्यन्त, taddh. aff. ख.

atyantiinatva|अत्यन्तीनत्व
n. (-त्वम्) The condition or property of going very far, of being distant or exalted, a high degree. E. अत्यन्तीन, taddh. aff. त्व.

atyamla|अत्यम्ल
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-म्लः-म्ला-म्लम्) Very sour. <BR>II. m. (-म्लः) A tree (Spondias mangifera). See वृक्षाम्ल. <BR>III. f. (-म्ला) Another plant and fruit; a species of citron. See मातुलुङ्गी. E. अति and अम्ल.

atyamlaparNii|अत्यम्लपर्णी
Bahuvr. f. (-र्णी) A creeper and medicinal plant, ‘of pungent and astringent properties, employed as a stomachic and against pains and enlargement of the spleen, rheumatism and diseases coming from disorders of the phlegmatic humour.’ See तीक्ष्णा, कण्डुरा, वयस्था. E. अत्यम्ल and पर्ण, with the fem. aff. ङीष्.

atyaya|अत्यय
m. (-यः)<BR> ^1 Going over or beyond.<BR> ^2 Surpassing.<BR> ^3 Going or passing away.<BR> ^4 Death.<BR> ^5 Loss, destruction, end.<BR> ^6 Transgression, sin, offence, guilt.<BR> ^7 Vice, fault.<BR> ^8 Distress.<BR> ^9 Punishment. E. इ with अति, kŕit aff. अण्.

atyayin|अत्ययिन्
m. f. n. (-यी-यिनी-यि) Exceeding, excessive. E. इ with अति, kŕit aff. इनि (implying here nature, disposition).

atyaraati|अत्यराति
Tatpur. m. (-तिः) A proper name, the son of Janantapa. E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and अराति (in the sense of the accusative) ‘overcoming his enemies’.

atyartha|अत्यर्थ
I. Tatpur. m. f. n. (-र्थः-र्था-र्थम्) Very much, excessive. <BR>II. Avyayíbh. (-र्थम्) Excessively. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and अर्थ (in the sense of the accusative).

atyalpa|अत्यल्प
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ल्पः-ल्पा-ल्पम्) Very small, very little. E. अति and अल्प.

atyavi|अत्यवि
Tatpur. m. (-विः) (ved.) Going beyond the sheep, running beyond the sheep's tail serving as a filtre for sacrificial purposes (an epithet of Soma in the Vedas). E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and अवि (in the sense of the accusative).

atyashana|अत्यशन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Eating too much, excess of eating. E. अति and अशन.

atyaShTi|अत्यष्टि
Tatpur. f. (-ष्टिः)<BR> ^1 The name of a class of metres regulated by number and quantity. See अतिच्छन्दस्. It consists of four lines with seventeen syllables to each line and comprises twelve varieties. (See<BR> ^1 शिखरिणी,<BR> ^2 पृथ्वी,<BR> ^3 वं शपत्रपतित or वंशपत्र,<BR> ^4 हरिणी,<BR> ^5 मन्दाक्रान्ता,<BR> ^6 नर्कुटक or नर्धटक or अवितथ,<BR> ^7 कोकिलक,<BR> ^8 हरि,<BR> ^9 कान्ता or क्रान्ता,<BR> ^10 चित्रलेखा or अतिशयनी,<BR> ^11 मालाधर or वनमालाधर,<BR> ^12 हारिणी.)<BR> ^2 (In arithmetic sometimes used to denote) the numeral 17. E. अति (sc. क्रान्ता) and अष्टि, another metre (in the sense of the accusative).

atyasta|अत्यस्त
m. f. n. (-स्तः-स्ता-स्तम्) Having overcome, having surpassed. (This word may form a compound with a word depending upon it in the accusative; f. i. तुहिनमत्यस्त or तुहिनात्यस्त.) E. अस् (to throw &c.) with अति, kŕit aff. क्त.

atyaham|अत्यहम्
Tatpur. m. Surpassing me. E. अति (sc. क्रान्तः) and अहम् (in the sense of माम्). This word seems to be only one of grammatical coinage and scarcely to occur in the real language. See also अतिमान्, अतिमाम्, अतिवयम्; and अतित्वम्.

atyahna|अत्यह्न
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ह्नः-ह्ना-ह्नम्) Passing beyond one day, lasting more than one day. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and अहन् (in the sense of the accusative), samásánta aff. टच्.

atyaakaara|अत्याकार
m. (-रः) Censure, blame, contempt. E. कृ with आ and अति, kŕit aff. घञ्.

atyaachaara|अत्याचार
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Deviating from prescribed observances, contemning religious and moral laws. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and आचार (in the sense of the accusative). <BR>II. m. (-रः) Observance of uncommanded and unnecessary rites or practices. E. अति and आचार.

atyaadaana|अत्यादान
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Taking away too much. E. अति and आदान.

atyaaditya|अत्यादित्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-त्यः-त्या-त्यम्) Surpassing the sun. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and आदित्य (in the sense of the accus.).

atyaadhaana|अत्याधान
n. (-नम्)<BR> ^1 Putting over, placing over or beyond.<BR> ^2 A groundless demand, an imposition. E. धा with आ and अति, kŕit aff. ल्युट्.

atyaanandaa|अत्यानन्दा
Tatpur. f. (-न्दा) A morbid affection of the female organs of generation, described as ‘when the woman has no pleasure in the embraces of her husband’. See योनिव्यापद्. E. अति (sc. क्रान्ता) and आनन्द (the sense of the accus.), sc. योनि.

atyaaya|अत्याय
m. (-यः) Exceeding, transgressing. E. इ with अति, kŕit aff. ण.

atyaala|अत्याल
Tatpur. m. (-लः) The name of a plant (Plumbago rosea). See रक्तचित्रक. E. अति and आल.

atyaashaa|अत्याशा
Tatpur. f. (-शा) Unreasonable hope or desire. E. अति and आशा.

atyaashramin|अत्याश्रमिन्
m. (-मी) An ascetic of the highest degree, one who is above the four orders or áśramas. E. अत्याश्रम (अति and आश्रम), taddh. aff. इनि.

atyaasam|अत्यासम्
ind. After the lapse of; only used in composition, f. i. द्व्यहात्यासम्, ‘after the lapse of two days’. E. अस् with अति, kŕit aff. णमुल्.

atyaahaara|अत्याहार
Tatpur. m. (-रः) Excessive food. E. अति and आहार.

atyaahaarin|अत्याहारिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-री-रिणी-रि) Eating excessively, a glutton, a gormandizer. E. अति and आहारिन्.

atyaahita|अत्याहित
Tatpur. n. (-तम्)<BR> ^1 Great dread.<BR> ^2 Desperate or daring action. E. अति and आहित.

atyuktaa|अत्युक्ता
Tatpur. f. (-क्ता) The name of a class of metres, regulated by number and quantity; it consists of a stanza of four lines with two syllables in each line and comprises four varieties.  (See<BR> ^1 स्त्री or काम,<BR> ^2 रति or मही,<BR> ^3 सारु,<BR> ^4 मधु.) Also called अत्युक्था. E. अति (sc. क्रान्ता) and उक्ता, another class of metres (in the sense of the accusative).

atyukti|अत्युक्ति
Tatpur. f. (-क्तिः)<BR> ^1 Idle or excessive talk.<BR> ^2 A figure of rhetoric, description of any thing surprising or extraordinary, hyperbole. E. अति and उक्ति.

atyukthaa|अत्युक्था
Tatpur. f. (-क्था). See अत्युक्ता. E. अति (sc. क्रान्ता) and उक्था (in the sense of the accusative).

atyugra|अत्युग्र
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-ग्रः-ग्रा-ग्रम्)<BR> ^1 Very hot, very sharp or pungent.<BR> ^2 Very formidable. <BR>II. n. (-ग्रम्) Asa foetida. E. अति and उग्र.

atyuchchairdhvani|अत्युच्चैर्ध्वनि
Tatpur. m. (-नि) A very loud sound, a very high note. E. अत्युच्चैस् and ध्वनि.

atyuchchais|अत्युच्चैस्
Tatpur. ind. Very loud, very high (as a sound, a note). E. अति and उच्चैस्.

atyutkaTa|अत्युत्कट
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-टः-टा-टम्) Exceedingly great. E. अति and उत्कट.

atyupadha|अत्युपध
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-धः-धा-धम्) Above trial, proved, sincere, upright. E. अति (sc. क्रान्त) and उपधा (in the sense of the accusative).

atyulvaNa|अत्युल्वण
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-णः-णा-णम्) Excessive, very much. E. अति and उल्वण.

atyuShNa|अत्युष्ण
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ष्णः-ष्णा-ष्णम्) Very hot. E. अति and उष्ण.

atyuumashaa|अत्यूमशा
ind. A particle of abuse or reproach(?), used only in composition with अस्, भू, कृ. E. unknown; comp. ऊम.

atyuurmi|अत्यूर्मि
m. f. n. (-र्मिः-र्मिः-र्मि) (ved.) Overflowing. E. ऋ with अति, uń. aff. मि and ऊ substituted for the initial अ.

atyuuha|अत्यूह
Bahuvr. I. m. (-हः) A gallinule. <BR>II. f. (-हा) A plant (Jasminum villosum, Rox. or in Bengal, Nyctanthes tristis). See नीलिका or शेफालिका. E. अति and ऊह.

atra|अत्र
I. ind.<BR> ^1 In this place, here, herein.<BR> ^2 In conjunction with nouns used in the same sense as एतस्मिन्, the locat. of एतद्; f. i. अत्राह्नि = एतस्मिन्नह्नि, ‘on that day’.--In the Vedas also written अत्रा which seems to be the more original form of this word. E. अश् (i. e. अ which, in this instance, is considered as a substitute of एतद् (and not of इदम्), because अत्र points always to what precedes), taddh. aff. त्रल्. <BR>II. Tatpur. m. f. n. (-त्रः-त्रा-त्रम्) Not protecting. E. अ neg. and त्र. <BR>III. m. (-त्रः) (ved.) A demon, a Rákshasa. E. अद्, uń. aff. त्र (literally: ‘one who eats or devours’). See अत्त्र. <BR>IV. n. (-त्रम्) (ved.) Food. E. अद्, uń. aff. ष्ट्रन्. See अत्त्र.

atradaghna|अत्रदघ्न
m. f. n. (-घ्नः-घ्नी-घ्नम्) Having that size, being of that height. E. अत्र, taddh. aff. दघ्नच्, in the fem. with aff. ङीप्; or more correctly, a Bahuvr. consisting of अत्र and an obsolete noun दघ्न q. v.

atrapa|अत्रप
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-पः-पा-पम्) Shameless, immodest. E. अ priv. and त्रपा.

atrabhavat|अत्रभवत्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-वान्-वती-वत्) Respectable, venerable (especially in theatrical language used as a respectful mode of address). E. अत्र and भवत्. See also तत्रभवत्.

atravas|अत्रवस्
ind. The last year but one. E. अत्र, taddh. aff. वस्(?). This word is of doubtful authority. 

atrasnu|अत्रस्नु
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-स्नुः-स्नुः-स्नु) Not timid, fearless. E. अ neg. and त्रस्नु.

atraasa|अत्रास
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-सः-सा-सम्) Fearless. E. अ priv. and त्रास.

atri|अत्रि
m. (-त्रिः)<BR> ^1 Eater, devourer (in the Vedas especially as an epithet of Agni, the divinity of fire).<BR> ^2 The name of a Maharshi or a great Saint, who in the Vedas occurs especially in hymns composed for the praise of Agni, Indra, the Aświns and the Viśwadevas; and who in the epic period is considered as one of the ten Prajápatis or lords of creation engendered by Manu for the purpose of creating the universe; at a later period he appears as a mindborn son of Brahmá and as one of the seven Ŕishis who preside over the reign of Swáyambhuva, the first, or according to others of Swárochisha, the second, or of Vaivaswata, the seventh Manu; he is married to Anasúyá, the daughter of Daksha and their son is Durvásas. Produced by a flash of light from his eye which was received by Space, the via lactea personified, or according to a more recent legend, by his penitence, is Soma or the moon. See अत्रिजात, अत्रिदृग्ज, अत्रिनेत्रज &c. As sons of his are also named the Manes Barhishads and Udamaya; a daughter of his is Apálá. The name of Atri occurs also as that of the author of several vaidik hymns, as that of an inspired legislator, of the author of an astronomical and medical work and, in astronomy, as one of the seven Ŕishis in the constellation of the great bear.--An Atri, son of Sánkhya, but probably a different personage, is the author of a hymn in the Ŕigveda.--Amongst the authors of vaidik hymns we find as sons or descendants of Atri the following: Archanána, Avasyu, Báhuvŕikta, Bhauma, Budha, Dvita, Gavisht́hira, Gaya, Gopavana, Isha, Paura, Pratibhánu, Pratiprabha, the Prayaswats, Purísha, Ratahavya, Sadápŕińa, Saptavadhri, Śaśa, Satyaśravas, Śrutavid, Sutambhara, Śyáváśwa, Vasuśruta, the Vasúyus, Viśwasáman, Yajata; and as daughters of Atri, Apálá, Gátu, Viśwavárá.<BR> ^3 m. pl. (अत्रयः) The descendants (see गोत्र) of Atri collectively. (The masc. plur. अत्रयः is considered as the plur. of the patronymic आत्रेय (q. v.) with luk of the taddh. aff. ढक्; the plural of the fem., however, remaining regular, viz. आत्रेय्यः; but there is no necessity to adopt this artificial etymology which is given to connect the sense of the patronymic with that of the plur. of the original form.) E. See अत्त्रि.

atrichaturaha|अत्रिचतुरह
Tatpur. m. (-हः) The name of a sacrifice, belonging to the class of those called अहीन q. v. E. अत्रि and चतुरह.

atrijaata|अत्रिजात
Tatpur. m. (-तः)<BR> ^1 The moon.<BR> ^2 A man of the three first classes. E.<BR> ^1 अत्रि and जात. See for the meaning under अत्रि.<BR> ^2 अ neg., त्रि and जात ‘not thrice born, i. e. born twice’; see द्विज.

atridRgja|अत्रिदृग्ज
Tatpur. m. (-जः)<BR> ^1 The moon.<BR> ^2 (In arithmetic sometimes used to denote) the numeral one. E. अत्रि-दृश् (eye) and ज. See for the meaning of this word and of its synonymes under अत्रि.

atrin|अत्रिन्
m. (-त्री) (ved.) A Rákshasa, a demon. (Literally: one who eats or devours.) E. See अत्त्रिन्. 

atrinetraja|अत्रिनेत्रज
Tatpur. m. (-जः). See अत्रिदृग्ज. E. अत्रि-नेत्र and ज.

atrinetraprasuuta|अत्रिनेत्रप्रसूत
Tatpur. m. (-तः). See अत्रिदृग्ज. E. अत्रि-नेत्र and प्रसूत.

atrinetrabhava|अत्रिनेत्रभव
Tatpur. m. (-वः). See अत्रिदृग्ज. E. अत्रि-नेत्र and भव.

atrinetrabhuu|अत्रिनेत्रभू
Tatpur. m. (-भूः). See अत्रिदृग्ज. E. अत्रि-नेत्र and भू.

atrinetrasuuta|अत्रिनेत्रसूत
Tatpur. m. (-तः). See अत्रिदृग्ज. E. अत्रि-नेत्र and सूत.

atribhaaradvaajikaa|अत्रिभारद्वाजिका
f. (-का) The marriage union of Atri and Bháradwájí. E. अत्रि and भारद्वाजी (as Dwandwa), taddh. aff. वुञ् implying in this and similar Dwandwa compounds condition or action. The more correct form of this word seems to be आत्रिभारद्वाजिका.

atrivat|अत्रिवत्
ind. Like Atri of like the descendants of Atri. E. अत्रि, taddh. aff. वति.

atrisaMhitaa|अत्रिसंहिता
Tatpur. f. (-ता) The name of a law-book ascribed to Atri. E. अत्रि and संहिता.

atrismRti|अत्रिस्मृति
Tatpur. f. (-तिः) The same as the preceding. E. अत्रि and स्मृति.

atvaraa|अत्वरा
Tatpur. f. (-रा) Want of haste or precipitation. E. अ neg. and त्वरा.

atha|अथ
ind. An inceptive and auspicious particle. It serves to introduce the beginning of a work, a chapter, a sentence and with respect to the latter may imply doubt or interrogation or may serve as a conjunctive or disjunctive particle. It may be accompanied by those particles or words which themselves are used in the same sense, giving them greater emphasis, especially by उ, अतस्, अनन्तरम्, किम्, तु, पुनर्, वा, किमु, अपि. Without or with these particles अथ corresponds therefore with:<BR> ^1 Now (inceptive or premising); in the same sense but with greater emphasis अथो (अथ and उ), अथातस्, अथानन्तरम्.<BR> ^2 Why? what? (interrogatively and doubtingly); (likewise अथवा.)<BR> ^3 How else? certainly; (in the same sense अथकिम्.)<BR> ^4 But, on the contrary; (in the same sense अथ तु, अथ पुनर्.)<BR> ^5 Or, or rather; (likewise अथवा, अथवापि, अथापि वा &c.)<BR> ^6 Moreover, so much the more, therefore, thus; (likewise अथच, अथापि, अथो अपि, अथ किमु.) In the Vedas there occurs also the protracted form अथा which seems to be the more original one; (cf. तथा and यथा). E. According to the native authorities from अर्थ्, kŕit aff. ड with र् being dropped; but it is more probably derived from अ, the pron. theme which is considered as a substitute for इदम् (pointing to what follows), taddh. aff. थ.

athakim|अथकिम्
ind. A particle of assent, how else, what else, assuredly. (Better to be considered as two words. See अथ.) E. अथ and किम्.

athakimu|अथकिमु
ind. So much the more. (Better to be considered as two separate words and also written अथ किमु. See अथ.) E. अथ and किमु.

athacha|अथच
ind. Also, moreover. (Better to be considered as two words. See अथ.) E. अथ and च.

athatu|अथतु
ind. But, on the contrary. (More properly to be considered as two distinct words and also written अथ तु. See अथ.) E. अथ and तु. 

atharii|अथरी
f. (occurs only as a plural in the Vedas; -र्यः) The finger. E. This word is given as an irregular derivation from अत् ‘to go constantly’; but it is more probable that it is derived, with aff. अरि, from an obsolete rad. अथ् which seems to have had the same meaning as अत् (cf. अट् and अठ्), but is found only in अथरी, अथर्वन् and their derivatives, implying quickness or agility. The same etymological connexion between words meaning ‘finger’ and ‘fire’ may be perceived in other derivations from a radical in the sense of ‘to go’ f. i. in अङ्गुलि or अङ्गुरि, अग्रू and अग्नि, अङ्गिरस्, from अङ्ग्. It reappears distinctly in the denom. अथर्य् and its derivatives अथर्य, अथर्यु qq. vv.

athary|अथर्य्
par. (-र्यति) To go, to move. (Only in the Vedas.) Probably a denominative from अथरी or अथर् with aff. यक्.

atharya|अथर्य
m. (-र्यः) Moving constantly; an epithet of Agni in the Vedas. See also the following. E. अथर्य्, kŕit aff. अच्(?). A commentary explains, that अथर्य is an epithet of दक्षिणाग्नि, because the sacred fire ‘goes always’ from the Gárhapatya (q. v.) to his proper place; the epithet may be considered, however, as one of a more general bearing.

atharyu|अथर्यु
m. (-युः) Moving constantly; an epithet of Agni in the Vedas. See the preceding. E. अथर्य्, kŕit aff. उ.

atharva|अथर्व
m. (-र्वः) A proper name of the eldest son of Brahmá, to whom Brahmá revealed the Brahmavidyá (q. v.) or knowledge of God. See अथर्वन्. E. See अथर्वन् of which it is an abbreviated form.

atharvaNa|अथर्वण
m. (-णः) A name of Śiva. E. अथर्वन्, taddh. aff. अ(?).

atharvaNi|अथर्वणि
m. (-णिः)<BR> ^1 A Brahman versed in the Atharvaveda.<BR> ^2 A family priest. E. See आथर्वणि which is the better reading of this word.

atharvan|अथर्वन्
1. m. (-र्वा)<BR> ^1 A Bráhmańa, a priest (probably one connected with offerings to fire or the attendance on the holy fire).<BR> ^2 The proper name of a priest who is considered to have obtained the fire from heaven and who in the course of mythological personification appears as a Prajápati or father of all beings, as the inspired author of the fourth or Atharvaveda, as the eldest son of Brahmá to whom Brahmá revealed the Brahmavidyá (q. v.) or knowledge of God (see also अथर्व) and, at a later period, as the same as Angiras (q. v.). Sons of his are Agni (see also अङ्गिरस्), Dadhyanch, Bhishaj, Bŕihaddiva, Kabandha.<BR> ^3 An epithet of<BR> ^a. Vasisht́ha q. v.,<BR> ^b. Soma q. v.,<BR> ^c. प्राण q. v.,<BR> ^d. Śiva (the god being supposed to carry into effect the charms of the Atharvaveda). BREAḲ. m. n. (-र्वा-र्व) The fourth or Atharvaveda q. v. (see also m. pl. अथर्वाणः). <BR>3. m. pl. (-र्वाणः)<BR> ^1 The descendants of Atharvan; they appear sometimes coupled with the descendants of Bhŕigu and of Angiras (see अथर्वाङ्गिरसः).<BR> ^2 The hymns of the fourth or Atharvaveda collectively (considered as the descendants of Atharvan); the Atharvaveda (see also अथर्वाङ्गिरसः). E. From an obsolete theme अथर्, fire, with taddh. aff. वनिप्. See the E. of अथरी. The oldest etym. which derives अथर्वन् from अ neg. and थर्वन् (from थर्व् ‘to go’), is without any probability. A similar etym. is given of अथर्वी q. v.

atharvabhuuta|अथर्वभूत
Tatpur. m. pl. (-ताः) An epithet of the twelve Maharshis:  धर्म, दक्ष, मरीचि, अत्रि, पुलस्त्य, पुलह, क्रतु, वसिष्ठ, गौतम, भृगु, अङ्गिरस्, मनु and (according to a commentary) of ‘Rudra, the Lord of the Universe’. E. अथर्वन् and भूत (according to a commentary from भू, to obtain, ‘having obtained i. e. versed in the Atharvaveda, the same as अथर्वविद्’).

atharvavat|अथर्ववत्
ind. Like Atharvan or the descendants of Atharvan. E. अथर्वन्, taddh. aff. वति.

atharvavid|अथर्वविद्
Tatpur. m. (-वित्) One versed in the Atharvaveda. See अथर्वभूत. According to the Pariśisht́a of this Veda esp. an epithet of the priest called Brahman q. v. See ब्रह्मवेद. E. अथर्वन् and विद्.

atharvaveda|अथर्ववेद
Tatpur. m. (-दः) The fourth or Atharvaveda (see ऋच्, यजुस्, सामन्), the Veda revealed by Atharvan or Angiras and sometimes considered, therefore, personified as a son of Angiras. See अथर्वन्, अथर्वाङ्गिरस्, प्रत्यङ्गिरस्, ब्रह्मवेद. E. अथर्वन् and वेद.

atharvashikhaa|अथर्वशिखा
Tatpur. f. (-खा) The name of one of the Upanishads of the Atharvaveda. E. अथर्वन् and शिखा ‘the crest’ i. e. (according to the comm.) the essence of the Atharvaveda.

atharvashiras|अथर्वशिरस्
Tatpur. n. (-रः) The name of an Upanishad of the Atharvaveda. E. अथर्वन् and शिरस् ‘the head’ i. e. the principal Upanishad of the A. V.

atharvahRdaya|अथर्वहृदय
Tatpur. n. (-यम्) The name of a Pariśisht́a of the Atharvaveda. E. अथर्वन् and हृदय.

atharvaangiras|अथर्वाङ्गिरस्
I. Tatpur. m. (-राः) The Angiras of the Atharvaveda. This use of the word, as a Tatpur. in the sing., is of later origin than that of the Dwandwa in the plur., and, as it seems, adopted to explain the form अथर्वाङ्गिरस q. v. <BR>II. Dwandwa. m. pl. (-रसः)<BR> ^1 The descendants of Atharvan and of Angiras.<BR> ^2 The Atharvaveda hymns of both collectively; the Atharvaveda (q. v.), one part (or parvan) of which is considered to have been revealed by the descendants of Atharvan and another by the descendants of Angiras. According to another explanation, however, this name of the Atharvaveda would merely refer to Atharvan (q. v.) being the inspired author of one part and Angiras (q. v.) of the other. E. अथर्वन् and अङ्गिरस्.

atharvaangirasa|अथर्वाङ्गिरस
I. m. f. n. (-सः-सी-सम्) Referring or belonging to the अथर्वाङ्गिरसः q. v. <BR>II. n. (-सम्) The religious observances (कर्मन्) connected with the ritual of the Atharvaveda. <BR>III. m. pl. (-साः) The mantras or hymns of the Atharvaveda. E. अथर्वाङ्गिरस्, taddh. aff. टच्.

atharvaaNa|अथर्वाण
n. (-णम्) The religious observances (कर्मन्) connected with the ritual of the Atharvaveda. E. Irregular derivation from अथर्वन्, taddh. aff. अण्(?).

atharvaaNavid|अथर्वाणविद्
Tatpur. m. (-त्) One versed in the rites of the Atharvaveda. E. अथर्वाण and विद्.

atharvii|अथर्वी
Tatpur. f. (-वी). This word occurs only in the Veda and is explained ‘not going, unable to move’, from अ neg. and थर्वी (from थर्व्, to go). It would seem, however, that it is a Tatpur. composed of the obsolete word अथर्, fire, and वी, ‘surrounded by fire’(?). See the E. of अथर्वन् and अथरी. 

athavaa|अथवा
ind.<BR> ^1 Why? what?<BR> ^2 Or, or rather. See अथ. E. अथ and वा.

athavaapi|अथवापि
ind. Or, or rather. More properly to be considered as two separate words, अथवा and अपि. See अथ. E. अथवा and अपि.

athaatas|अथातस्
ind. Now (inceptive or premising). More properly to be considered as two distinct words. See अथ. E. अथ and अतस्.

athaanantaram|अथानन्तरम्
ind. The same as the preceding; better considered as two separate words. See अथ. E. अथ and अनन्तरम्.

athaapi|अथापि
ind. Moreover, so much the more, therefore, thus; better considered as two distinct words. See अथ. E. अथ and अपि.

atho|अथो
ind. Now (inceptive or premising). (According to some it has the same meanings as अथ.) अथो अपि, moreover &c. See अथ. E. अथ and उ.

ad|अद्
I. (अद-अदादि-अनुदात्त-उदात्तेत्) r. 2d cl. par. (अत्ति- imperf. आदत्- imper. अद्धि, ep. अदस्व- perf. आद, 2d pers. आदिथ- fut. 1. अत्स्यति, 2. अत्ता- inf. अत्तुम्- p. p. अदित (अन्न only used as subst.). Pass. अद्यते. Caus. आदयति-ते.--For the tenses which are not formed of अद्, see घस् which is then considered as a substitute of it.) To eat. (Caus. To feed.)--With अव(?)-आ-प्र-सम् to eat, to devour; वि- to gnaw, to nibble. <BR>II. m. f. n. (अत्) Eating. This word occurs only as the latter part of a Tatpur., the former part of which may be any word but अन्न (which forms अन्नाद and not अन्नाद्). See f. i. अहुताद्, आमाद्, क्रव्याद्. E. अद्, kŕit aff. विट्.

ada|अद
m. f. n. (-दः-दी-दम्) Eating; (occurs only as the latter part of Tatpur. compounds). See f. i. अजाद, अतृणाद, अन्नाद. E. अद्, kŕit aff. अण्.

adaxa|अदक्ष
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-क्षः-क्षा-क्षम्) Awkward, unskilful. E. अ neg. and दक्ष.

adaxiNa|अदक्षिण
m. f. n. (-णः-णा-णम्) I. Tatpur.<BR> ^1 Not right, left.<BR> ^2 Not clever, unskilful. E. अ neg. and दक्षिण. <BR>II. Bahuvr. Being or being performed without the presents usually given to Brahmans (see दक्षिणा), as a sacrifice &c. The celebration of a sacrifice without the Dakshińá occurs for instance under the following circumstances: at the Prátah́savana of the Jyotisht́oma, when about to sing the Vahishpavamána stotra, the priests step out from the house where the sacred fire is kept, one going after the other and holding the one who precedes by the hem of his garment: if it so happens, at this procession, that the Udgátŕi inadvertently drops the hem, the sacrifice goes on without the Dakshińá; once accomplished, however, it is to be repeated and then the Udgátŕi has to pay the Dakshińá which should have been given at the first performance; if the Pratihartŕi meets with a similar accident, he has to pay his whole property at the renewal of the ceremony, which then is called सर्वस्वदक्षिण. E. अ priv. and दक्षिणा.

adaxiNatva|अदक्षिणत्व
n. (-त्वम्)<BR> ^1 Leftness, unskilfulness &c.<BR> ^2 The state of a sacrifice performed without the Dakshińá. See the preceding. E. अदक्षिण, taddh. aff. त्व.

adaxiNiiya|अदक्षिणीय
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Not worth the sacrificial gift or दक्षिणा q. v. E. अ neg. and दक्षिणीय. 

adaxiNya|अदक्षिण्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) The same as the preceding. E. अ neg. and दक्षिण्य.

adagdha|अदग्ध
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ग्धः-ग्धा-ग्धम्) Not burnt, unscorched. E. अ neg. and दग्ध.

adaNDa|अदण्ड
I. Tatpur. n. (-ण्डम्) Impunity. E. अ neg. and दण्ड. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-ण्डः-ण्डा-ण्डम्) Unpunished. E. अ priv. and दण्ड.

adaNDya|अदण्ड्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ण्ड्यः-ण्ड्या-ण्ड्यम्)<BR> ^1 Unpunishable, exempt from punishment.<BR> ^2 Not deserving punishment. E. अ neg. and दण्ड्य.

adaNDaniiya|अदण्डनीय
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Unpunishable, unfit to be punished, exempt from punishment. E. अ neg. and दण्डनीय.

adat|अदत्
I. m. f. n. (-दन्-दन्ती-दत्) Eating. E. अद्, kŕit aff. शतृ. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-दन्-दती-दत्) Having no teeth, toothless. E. अ priv. and दत्, considered as a substitute of दन्त.

adatka|अदत्क
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-कः-का-कम्) Toothless. E. अदत् II. q. v., samásánta aff. कप्.

adatta|अदत्त
I. Tatpur. 1. m. f. n. (-त्तः-त्ता-त्तम्) Not given. 2. f. (-त्ता) An unmarried girl. 3. n. (-त्तम्) (In law.) A void and resumable donation (see दत्त, देय, अदेय). E. अ neg. and दत्त. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-त्तः-त्ता-त्तम्) Not having given. E. अ priv. and दत्त.

adadryanc|अदद्र्यञ्च्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-द्र्यङ्-द्रीची-द्र्यक्) Going to that. (This word is probably one of a mere grammatical coinage, to illustrate a rule concerning the pronom. theme अदस्. According to some it would have the same meaning as अदमुयञ्च्, अमुद्र्यञ्च् and अमुमुयञ्च् to which others add अदमुद्र्यञ्च्, अमुमूयञ्च्, अदमूयञ्च् qq. vv., but it might also be that अदद्र्यञ्च् (as well as अदमुयञ्च्, अदमुद्र्यञ्च्, अदमूयञ्च्) is formed to show that its first part represents not the whole theme, but merely the neuter of अदस्, while the first part of अमुद्र्यञ्च्, अमुमुयञ्च् and अमुमूयञ्च् refer to its masc. and femin. For the declension of this word, see अञ्च् II. E. अदस् and अञ्च् (II. 1.), with अद्रि instead of the final अस् of अदस्.

adana|अदन
n. (-नम्)<BR> ^1 Eating.<BR> ^2 Food. E. अद्, kŕit aff. ल्युट्.

adanta|अदन्त
Bahuvr. I. 1. m. f. n. (-न्तः-न्ता-न्तम्) Toothless. See the preceding. BREAḲ. m. (-न्तः) A leech. E. अ priv. and दन्त. <BR>II. m. f. n. (-न्तः-न्ता-न्तम्) (In grammar.) Ending in the short vowel ‘a’. E. अत् (the grammatical designation of short ‘a’ and अन्त.

adantaka|अदन्तक
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-कः-का-कम्) Toothless. E. अदन्त, samásánta aff. कप्.

adantya|अदन्त्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-न्त्यः-न्त्या-न्त्यम्)<BR> ^1 Prejudicial to the teeth.<BR> ^2 Different from or other than what is fit for the teeth. E. अ neg. and दन्त्य; in the first meaning which is the usual one, the word is an oxytonon, in the latter a proparoxytonon.

adabdha|अदब्ध
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ब्धः-ब्धा-ब्धम्) (ved.) Unhurt, uninjured, entire, pure &c. E. अ neg. and दब्ध.

adabdhavrata|अदब्धव्रत
Bahuvr. m. (-तः) (ved.) One whose devotions or religious observances are unbroken. E. अदब्ध and व्रत. 

adabdhavratapramati|अदब्धव्रतप्रमति
m. (-तिः) (ved.) I. Bahuvr. One whose mind is superior in having his devotions or observances unbroken, or II. Dwandwa. One whose devotions or observances are unbroken and whose mind is superior (an epithet of Agni). E. अदब्धव्रत and प्रमति. If a Bahuvr., the former part stands in the sense of the locative.

adabdhaayu|अदब्धायु
m. (-युः) Having uninjured or pure food, an epithet of Agni in the Vedas. (According to a commentary: leaving uninjured the man who institutes the sacrifice. E. अदब्ध and आयु.)

adabhra|अदभ्र
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-भ्रः-भ्रा-भ्रम्) Not little, much. E. अ neg. and दभ्र.

adamudryanc|अदमुद्र्यञ्च्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-द्र्यङ्-द्रीची-द्र्यक्) Going to that. See अदद्र्यञ्च् and the forms mentioned there. For the declension of this word see अञ्च् II. E. Irreg. composition of अदस् and अञ्च् II. 1. See the following.

adamuyanc|अदमुयञ्च्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-यङ्-ईची-यक्) Going to that. See the preceding and अदद्र्यञ्च्; for the declension see अञ्च् II. E. Irreg. compos. of अदस् and अञ्च्. Also read अदमूयञ्च्.

adamuuyanc|अदमूयञ्च्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-यङ्-ईची-यक्). See the preceding.

adambha|अदम्भ
I. Tatpur. m. (-म्भः) Want of hypocrisy or deceti, straightforwardness, sincerity. E. अ neg. and दम्भ. <BR>II. Bahuvr. 1. m. f. n. (-म्भः-म्भा-म्भम्) Without deceit, upright, straightforward, sincere. 2. m. (-म्भः) A name of Śiva. E. अ priv. and दम्भ.

adamya|अदम्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-म्यः-म्या-म्यम्) Uncontrollable, untamable. E. अ neg. and दम्य.

adaya|अदय
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Unfeeling, unmerciful, destitute of pity. अदयम् used adverbially. E. अ priv. and दया.

adara|अदर
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Not little, much. E. अ neg. and दर.

adaraka|अदरक
m. (-कः) A proper name(?). E. unknown.

adarsha|अदर्श
m. (-र्शः)<BR> ^1 Day of the new moon. See दर्श.<BR> ^2 A mirror. See आदर्श. E. This word seems to be an incorrect reading of दर्श or आदर्श; but in the former sense it may be a Tatpur. composed of अ neg. and दर्श.

adarshana|अदर्शन
I. Tatpur. n. (-नम्)<BR> ^1 Not seeing.<BR> ^2 Disappearance, not being visible or present (in grammar f. i. of a letter, an affix &c.). E. अ neg. and दर्शन. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-नः-ना-नम्) Invisible, disappearing. E. अ priv. and दर्शन.

adarshaniiya|अदर्शनीय
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Invisible. E. अ neg. and दर्शनीय.

adala|अदल
Bahuvr. I. m. f. n. (-लः-ला-लम्) Leafless. <BR>II. m. (-लः) A plant (Eugenia acutangula). See हिज्जल. <BR>III. f. (-ला) Socotrine aloe (Aloe perfoliata). See घृतकुमारी. E. अ priv. and दल.

adas|अदस्
I. m. f. n. (असौ-असौ-अदस्). The pronoun (see सर्वनामन्) which generally points to what is absent, remote or uncertain (differently from इदम् q. v.) and which corresponds with<BR> ^1 That.<BR> ^2 A certain (so and so). In correlative phrases it stands therefore usually in the prior sentence, imparting greater emphasis. Its declension is defective in as far as most of its cases are supplied by the themes असु or अस, अमु (अमू) and अमि (अमी). The theme which ap pears in composition is अदस् (except in the forms अदद्र्यञ्च् &c. q. v. See also अद्धा). In some derivations of rare occurrence we meet also with the themes असु, अस and अमु; see असुक, असक, अमुक. <BR>II. ind. (esp. in composition with radicals (see गति), when employed reflectively). So, in such a manner, f. i. अदःकृत्य having done so &c.--In conjunction with a relative pronoun or particle it has the effect of giving emphasis or of generalising, e. g. यददस् whatever, यत्रादस् wherever, यथादस् howsoever. E. unknown; but it is probably derived from the theme अद् which occurs in अदद्र्यञ्च् and अद्धा.

adasy|अदस्य्
denom. par. (-स्यति) To become that. E. अदस्, denom. aff. यक्.

adaatR|अदातृ
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ता-त्री-तृ)<BR> ^1 Not giving.<BR> ^2 Not liberal, miserly.<BR> ^3 Not paying (a debt &c.).<BR> ^4 Not giving in marriage (a daughter, as a father). E. अ neg. and दातृ.

adaadi|अदादि
Bahuvr. m. (-दिः) (In grammar.) The verbs of the second class, the list of which in the native dictionaries begins with अद्, to eat. E. अद् and आदि, sc. धातु.

adaana|अदान
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Not giving, withholding. E. अ neg. and दान.

adaanta|अदान्त
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-न्तः-न्ता-न्तम्) Untamed, unsubdued, undaunted. E. अ neg. and दान्त.

adaabhya|अदाभ्य
Tatpur. I. m. f. n. (-भ्यः-भ्या-भ्यम्) Unhurtable, uninjurable, irreproachable. <BR>II. m. (-भ्यः) The name of a Graha (q. v.) in the Jyotisht́oma sacrifice. E. अ neg. and दाभ्य.

adaayaada|अदायाद
m. f. n. (-दः-दा-दम्) I. Tatpur. Not being an heir, having no claim to be an heir. E. अ neg. and दायाद. <BR>II. Bahuvr. Being without an heir, unclaimed as inheritance. See the following. E. अ priv. and दायाद.

adaayika|अदायिक
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-कः-की-कम्)<BR> ^1 Unclaimed, as inheritance, lapsed.<BR> ^2 Not relating to inheritance. E. अ neg. and दायिक.

adaara|अदार
Bahuvr. m. (-रः) Having no wife, unmarried. E. अ priv. and दार.

adaashu|अदाशु
Tatpur. m. (-शुः) (ved.) Not liberal, not pious. E. अ neg. and दाशु.

adaashuri|अदाशुरि
Tatpur. m. (-रिः) (ved.) Not liberal, not pious. E. अ neg. and दाशुरि.

adaashvas|अदाश्वस्
Tatpur. m. (-श्वान्) (ved.) Not liberal, not pious. E. अ neg. and दाश्वस्.

adaasa|अदास
Tatpur. m. (-सः) Not a slave, a free man. E. अ neg. and दास.

adaahya|अदाह्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ह्यः-ह्या-ह्यम्) Inconsumable by fire, incombustible. E. अ neg. and दाह्य.

adikka|अदिक्क
Bahuvr. m. (-क्कः) Having no quarters, driven from all heavenly regions (an epithet of the Asuras in the Vedas). E. अ priv. and दिश्, samásánta aff. कप्.

aditi|अदिति
I. Tatpur. f. (-तिः)<BR> ^1 Entireness, the being unbroken or unhurt.<BR> ^2 Exemption from defect or misery.<BR> ^3 The full or unbroken creative power of the Prajápati. E. अ neg. and दिति. <BR>II. Bahuvr. I. m. f. (-तिः-तिः)<BR> ^1 Unbroken, unhurt.<BR> ^2 Free from misery, happy.<BR> ^3 Pious, holy. As Bahuvr. 

aditi|अदिति
is in the Vedas often used as an epithet of Indra, the Maruts and Agni, but it becomes personified especially in BREAḲ. f. (-तिः) which in the Vedas means<BR> ^1 the earth,<BR> ^2 a cow,<BR> ^3 speech; but especially<BR> ^4 Aditi, the first goddess of the intermediate space or air, the mother of the Gods, who at a later period was considered as the daughter of Daksha and wife of Kaśyapa, as the sister of Agastya and as the mother of the twelve Ádityas, of the eight Vasus, eleven Rudras and two Aświns, besides of the thirty-six Tushitas.<BR> --Aditi is in a still later time also an appellative of Durgá. <BR>3. f. du. (-ती) (In the Vedas.) Heaven and earth. E. अ priv. and दिति. <BR>III. m. (-तिः) A name of Mŕityu, the god of Death; literally: the eater or devourer. (This meaning of the word occurs only in a commentary of an Upanishad and is rather doubtful.) E. अद् (uń. aff. ति?).

aditija|अदितिज
Tatpur. m. (-जः) A son of Aditi, a deity, a god. See अदितिनन्दन. E. अदिति and ज.

adititva|अदितित्व
n. (-त्वम्)<BR> ^1 Unbrokenness, entireness, fullness of power.<BR> ^2 The being Aditi (in the sense of Mŕityu; see अदिति III). E. अदिति, taddh. aff. त्व.

aditinandana|अदितिनन्दन
Tatpur. m. (-नः) The same as अदितिज. E. अदिति and नन्दन.

aditsat|अदित्सत्
