anuyaa|अनुया
Tatpur. f. (-याः) (ved.) Food; acc. to the comm.: ‘because it pervades the body’. Comp. अनुपद्. E. या with अनु, kŕit aff. विच्.

anuyaaga|अनुयाग
Tatpur. m. (-गः) A subsequent sacrificial act; distinct from अनुयाज q. v. E. अनु and याग.

anuyaaja|अनुयाज
Tatpur. m. (-जः) A secondary sacrificial act; the name of several offerings of clarified butter mixed with curdled milk, which occur in various sacrifices, as the Darśapúrnamása &c. There are, for instance, nine Anuyájas in the Cháturmásya; eleven in the Jyotisht́oma where they form part of the proceedings with the सवनीयपशु (q. v.). Eleven Anuyájas are also personified as divinities of one of the two classes comprising thirty three gods; comp. besides उपयाज and प्रयाज. Also written अनूयाज. Compare प्रयाज. E. अनु and याज.

anuyaajavat|अनुयाजवत्
m. f. n. (-वान्-वती-वत्) Having the secondary sacrificial acts called अनुयाज. E. अनुयाज, taddh. aff. मतुप्.

