anuuchiinagarbha|अनूचीनगर्भ
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-र्भः-र्भा-र्भम्) (ved.) Born successively, born one after the other. E. अनुचीन and गर्भ.

anuuchiinaaha|अनूचीनाह
Tatpur. m. (-हः) (ved.) The following day or days. Only used in the accus. अनूचीनाहम् adv.<BR> ^1 On the following day, e. g. द्व्यहमनूचीनाहं यजते.<BR> ^2 On two successive days, on the preceding and following day, e. g. ताभ्यामनूचीनाहं वेष्टिभ्यां यजते.<BR> ^3 Day by day, every day, e. g. सवा एकैक एवानूचीनाहं पुरोडाशो भवति. E. अनूचीन and अहन्, samásánta aff. टच्.

anuuchya|अनूच्य
n. (-च्यम्) (ved.) The board on the south-and on the north-side of a couch. E. अन्वच्, taddh. aff. यत्.

anuuDha|अनूढ
Tatpur. 1. m. f. n. (-ढः-ढा-ढम्) Not carried, not maintained. BREAḲ. f. (-ढा) An unmarried woman. E. अ neg. and ऊढ.

anuuDhamaana|अनूढमान
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-नः-ना-नम्) Bashful. E. अ neg. and ऊढ-मान.

anuuDhaabhraatR|अनूढाभ्रातृ
Tatpur. m. (-ता) The brother of an unmarried woman; used in a rhetorical work in the sense of ‘the brother of a concubine’, scil. of a king; he is called शकार or the mock-brother-in-law of the king. E. अनूढा and भ्रातृ.

anuuti|अनूति
Tatpur. f. (-तिः) (ved.) Not arriving, not coming. E. अ neg. and ऊति.

anuutta|अनूत्त
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-त्तः-त्ता-त्तम्) Given back, returned. The same as अनुदत्त. E. An abbrev. of अनुदत्त. 

anuudaka|अनूदक
Tatpur. n. (-कम्) Want of water, drought. E. अ neg. and ऊदक instead of उदक.

anuudita|अनूदित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Spoken or said in conformity with or in reference to a previous statement, in the way of a detailed illustration; being an अनुवाद q. v. E. वद् with अनु, kŕit aff. क्त.

anuuddesha|अनूद्देश
Tatpur. m. (-शः) Telling in conformity with a previous statement, telling or pointing out in successive reference to what precedes; e. g. यथासंख्यमनूद्देश उद्दिष्टानां क्रमेण यत् (v. s. v. यथासंख्य). E. अनु and उद्देश.

anuudya|अनूद्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-द्यः-द्या-द्यम्) The same as अनुवाद्य q. v. [In the present edition of Páńini III. 1. 101. अनूद्य is a misreading for अनुद्य q. v.]<BR>E. वद् with अनु, kŕitya aff. यत्.

anuudyamaana|अनूद्यमान
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-नः-ना-नम्) What is said in reference to what is previously stated, ruled &c.; e. g. विधीयमानानूद्यमानयोरनुदात्तत्वार्थं सर्वग्रहणम्. E. वद् with अनु, kŕit aff. शानच् and ágama मुक्.

anuudhas|अनूधस्
Bahuvr. f. (-धाः) Without an udder. E. अ priv. and ऊधस्.

anuuna|अनून
Tatpur. 1. m. f. n. (-नः-ना-नम्)<BR> ^1 Undiminished.<BR> ^2 Complete, full.<BR> ^3 Not less, not inferior (seq. ablat.). Comp. अन्यून. BREAḲ. f. (-ना) The name of an Apsaras. E. अ neg. and ऊन.

anuunaka|अनूनक
m. f. n. (-कः-का-क्रम्) The same as the preceding. E. अनून, taddh. aff. कन्.

anuunaguru|अनूनगुरु
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-रुः-रुः-रु) Very heavy, very massive. E. अनून and गुरु.

anuunavarchas|अनूनवर्चस्
Bahuvr. m. (-र्चाः) Of undiminished or full splendor, a vaidik epithet of Agni. E. अनून and वर्चस्.

anuupa|अनूप
I. 1. Bahuvr. 1. m. f. n. (-पः-पा-पम्) Watery, rich in water. 2. m. (-पः) (Used in a comm. of the Rámáyańa also as a neuter: -पम्.)<BR> ^1 A moist country. According to the division of the medical Átreya-Sanhitá one of the three climates of India--see besides जाङ्गल and साधारण; it is defined in Wise's Hindu system of Medicine as having much water on its surface, being intersected by rivers and irregular in its surface, with high mountains and tall trees; the air being there cool and the wind temperate; abounding in grass, water flowers, geese, ducks, cranes, fish, serpents &c., unhealthy and its inhabitants being fat, indolent and weak.<BR> ^2 (ved.) A jar (कलश).<BR> ^3 The name of a country (mentioned f. i. amongst those conquered by Rudradáman, one of the Sinha-kings). BREAḲ. Tatpur. m. (-पः)<BR> ^1 A buffalo. [^2 Any animal living in the water or on shore.<BR> ^3 The francoline partridge (तित्तिरक).<BR> ^4 An elephant.<BR> ^5 A frog (प्लव).<BR> ^6 Any shelled animal which lives in the water.<BR> ^7 An amphibious animal.<BR> ^8 A fish. (The last seven meanings are given on the authority of several medical authors.)]<BR>^9 A proper name, an abbreviation of अनूपसिंह q. v. See अनूपविलास. E. अनु and अप्, changed, according to Páńini, to ऊप्, samásánta aff. अ (the affix being the same in the Tatpur. and the Bahuvr., according to the Káśiká), but as regards the change of the vowel, it is more probable that अ of अप् has got lost and the preceding vowel lengthened by way of compensation, analogously to समीप, प्रतीप, द्वीप, वीप &c. In दर्भानूप q. v. the न् is not changed to ण्. <BR>II. Tatpur. m. (-पः) (ved.) Throwing or effusing in re gular succession or according to (scil. one's functions); an epithet of the three divinities Parjanya, Váyu and Áditya ‘who effuse on the earth (i. e. produce there) rain, cold and heat successively or according to their functions’ (accord. to Yáska and Sáyańa). E. वप् with अनु, kŕit aff. अच्(?), but it is better perhaps to assume that this अनूप means originally ‘favourable, propitious’ and comes from अनु and अप्, kŕit aff. अच्. For the latter etym. see the Preface.

anuupaja|अनूपज
Tatpur. n. (-जम्) Ginger in its undried state. E. अनूप and ज. See also अनुपज.

anuupapraaya|अनूपप्राय
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्) Abounding in watery ground, marshy. E. अनूप and प्राय.

anuupavilaasa|अनूपविलास
Tatpur. m. (-सः) Name of a treatise on ritual subjects, written by order of the king Anúpasinha. E. अनूप, abbrev. of अनूपसिंह, and विलास.

anuupasadam|अनूपसदम्
Avyayíbh. At each religious ceremony called उपसद् q. v. E. अनु and उपसद्, samásánta aff. टच्.

anuupasiMha|अनूपसिंह
Tatpur. m. (-हः) The proper name of a king. Comp. अनूपविलास. E. अनूप and सिंह.

anuupya|अनूप्य
m. f. n. (-प्यः-प्या-प्यम्) Being or met with in moist countries, as water; (opposed to the waters धन्वन्य ‘met with in deserts’). E. अनूप, taddh. aff. यत्.

anuubandhya|अनूबन्ध्य
Tatpur. The same as अनुबन्ध्य q. v.

anuuyaaja|अनूयाज
Tatpur. The same as अनुयाज q. v.

anuuraadha|अनूराध
Tatpur. I. m. (-धः) (ved.) Propitious, favourable; an epithet of Indra. Compare अनुराध. E. राध् with अनू instead of अनु, kŕit aff. अच्. <BR>II. f. (-धा) The same as अनुराधा q. v.

anuuru|अनूरु
Bahuvr. 1. m. f. n. (-रुः-रुः-रु) Thighless. BREAḲ. m. (-रुः) Aruńa, the charioteer of the sun, the dawn. E. अ priv. and ऊरु; Aruńa being represented without legs.

anuurudh|अनूरुध्
Tatpur. The same as अनुरुध् q. v.

anuurusaarathi|अनूरुसारथि
Bahuvr. m. (-थिः) The sun (whose charioteer is Aruńa). E. अनूरु and सारथि.

anuurjita|अनूर्जित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्)<BR> ^1 Weak, powerless.<BR> ^2 Free from pride. E. अ neg. and ऊर्जित.

anuurdhva|अनूर्ध्व
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-र्ध्वः-र्ध्वा-र्ध्वम्) Nether, inferior, low. E. अ neg. and ऊर्ध्व.

anuurdhvabhaas|अनूर्ध्वभास्
Bahuvr. m. (-भाः) (ved.) 1. One whose lustre or power is not great, of inferior strength. E. अनूर्ध्व and भास्. or 2. One who has not lighted a sacrificial fire, impious. E. अ priv. and ऊर्ध्वभास्.

anuurmi|अनूर्मि
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-र्मिः-र्मिः-मि) (ved.) Uninjurable, invulnerable. E. अ neg. and ऊर्मि.

anuulaa|अनूला
f. (-ला) The name of a river in Kashmir. E. unknown.

anuuShara|अनूषर
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) 1. Of a saline nature (a spot). The same as ऊषर. 2. Not of a saline nature (a spot); e. g. श्वभ्रशर्कराश्मविषमवल्मीकश्मशानाद्यतनदेवतायतनसिकताभिरनुपहतामनूषरामभङ्गुरामदूरादेकां स्निग्धां… …भूमिमौषधार्थं परीक्षेत. E. अ 1. compar. or expl., 2. neg. and ऊषर.

anuuShita|अनूषित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Lived together with; used actively, passively, personally and impersonally; e. g. अनूषितो गुरुं भवान् or अनूषितो गुरुर्भवता or अनूषितं भवता. Compare for the construction अधिशयित, अनुजात, आसित, उपस्थित &c. E. वस् with अनु, kŕit aff. क्त. 

anuuShmapara|अनूष्मपर
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Not followed by a consonant called ऊष्मन् q. v. E. अ neg. and ऊष्मपर.

anRkka|अनृक्क
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-क्कः-क्का-क्कम्) Not having or containing a verse from the Ŕigveda. (The form अनृच्क which occurs in the present edition of Páńini, is wrong.) E. अ priv. and ऋच्, samásánta aff. कप्.

anRxara|अनृक्षर
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Thornless (as a path; ved.). E. अ priv. and ऋक्षर.

anRch|अनृच्
Bahuvr. 1. m. f. n. (-क्-क्-क्) Not having or containing a verse from the Ŕigveda. Comp. अनृक्क. BREAḲ. m. (-क्) One not possessing i. e. not conversant with, the Ŕigveda. Comp. अनृच. E. अ priv. and ऋच्.

anRcha|अनृच
Bahuvr. m. (-चः) One not conversant with the Ŕigveda. E. अ priv. and ऋच्, samásánta aff. अ.

anRchka|अनृच्क
See the remark s. v. अनृक्क.

anRju|अनृजु
Tatpur. 1. m. f. n. (-जुः-जुः-जु)<BR> ^1 Not straight.<BR> ^2 Wicked. BREAḲ. m. (-जुः) A shrub, explained by तगर q. v. E. अ neg. and ऋजु.

anRNa|अनृण
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-णः-णा-णम्) Free from debt, unindebted. E. अ neg. and ऋण.

anRNataa|अनृणता
f. (-ता) or ºत्व n. (-त्वम्) Freedom from debt. E. अनृण, taddh. aff. तल् or त्व.

anRNin|अनृणिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-णी-णिनी-णि) Free from debt or obligation, unindebted. Also अऋणिन् (without ágama नुट्). E. अ neg. and ऋणिन्.

anRta|अनृत
Tatpur. I. 1. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Untrue. BREAḲ. n. (-तम्) Untruth, falsehood. (In the mythology of the Puráńas Anŕita is the son of Adharma (vice) and Hinsá (violence), and the brother of Nikŕiti (immorality); they intermarry and have two sons, Bhaya (fear) and Naraka (hell) and twins to them, two daughters, Máyá (deceit) and Vedaná (torture) who became their wives.--In the Rámáyańa Anŕita is the name of one of the mystical weapons delivered to Ráma by Viśwámitra.) E. अ neg. and ऋत. <BR>II. n. (-तम्) Agriculture. E. According to the native comm. the etym. would be the same as before; their account for the meaning ‘agriculture’ however is not very plausible, some explain it: ‘because agriculture is like falsehood’ or ‘because agriculture cannot be carried on without falsehood’, another refers ऋत in this sense to the radical ऋ ‘to hurt’ and explains it as a Bahuvr. ‘that from which injury does not arise’. The etym. of this meaning and its probable connection with प्रमृत used in the same sense by Manu will be discussed in the Preface.

anRtadeva|अनृतदेव
Bahuvr. m. (-वः) (ved.) One to whom the gods are untrue. E. अनृत and देव.

anRtadviSh|अनृतद्विष्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ट्-ट्-ट्) Hating untruth; a vaidik epithet of the Ádityas. E. अनृत and द्विष्.

anRtabhaaShaNa|अनृतभाषण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) Speaking an untruth, lying. E. अनृत and भाषण.

anRtamaya|अनृतमय
m. f. n. (-यः-यी-यम्) Untrue. E. अनृत, taddh. aff. मयट्.

anRtavadana|अनृतवदन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Speaking an untruth, lying. E. अनृत and वदन.

anRtavaach|अनृतवाच्
I. Tatpur. f. (-क्) An untruth, a lie. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-क्-क्-क्) Speaking an untruth, lying. E. अनृत and वाच्. 

anRtavaadin|अनृतवादिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-दी-दिनी-दि) Speaking habitually the untruth, a liar. E. अनृत and वादिन्.

anRtaakhyaana|अनृताख्यान
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) Speaking an untruth, lying, a lie. E. अनृत and आख्यान.

anRtin|अनृतिन्
m. f. n. (-ती-तिनी-ति) A liar. E. अनृत, taddh. aff. इनि.

anRtu|अनृतु
I. Tatpur. m. (-तुः) A wrong season, improper or forbidden time. <BR>II. Bahuvr. f. (-तुः) See the following. E. अ neg. and ऋतु.

anRtukanyaa|अनृतुकन्या
Karmadh. f. (-न्या) A girl before menstruation or about ten years old. E. अनृतु II. and कन्या.

anRtodya|अनृतोद्य
Karmadh. n. (-द्यम्) Untrue speech, falsehood. E. अनृत and उद्य (वद्, kŕitya aff. क्यप्).

anRpa|अनृप
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-पः-पा-पम्) Without a king, kingless (as a country). E. अ priv. and नृप.

anRbhuxin|अनृभुक्षिन्
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-क्षी-क्षी-क्षि) (?) Without Indra. (The Siddhántakaumudí gives अनृभुक्षी as the fem. of अनृभुक्षिन् instead of अनृभुक्षिणी in the instance अनृभुक्षी सेना, but this form is not supported by the old gramm. authorities.) E. अ priv. and ऋभुक्षिन्.

anRshaMsa|अनृशंस
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-सः-सा-सम्) Not mischievous, not cruel, mild. E. अ neg. and नृशंस.

anRshaMsataa|अनृशंसता
f. (-ता) or ºत्व n. (-त्वम्) Mildness. Compare आनृशंस and आनृशंस्य. E. अनृशंस, taddh. aff. तल् or त्व.

aneka|अनेक
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-कः-का-कम्)<BR> ^1 Not one, much, many, multitudinous. (In the Sánkhya-phil.: one of the characteristics of the discrete principle or व्यक्त, since it comprises बुद्धि, अहङ्कार, the five तन्मात्र and the eleven इन्द्रिय qq. vv., the reverse of एक, the characteristic of प्रधान or अव्यक्त qq. vv., the Undiscrete, and of पुरुष q. v., the Soul.)<BR> ^2 Not united, separated; e. g. यथा संधीयमानानामनेकीभवतां स्वरः । उपदिष्टस्तथा विद्यादक्षराणामवग्रहे ॥. E. अ neg. and एक.

anekakaala|अनेककाल
Karmadh. m. (-लः) Much time, a long time; the accus. used adv. E. अनेक and काल.

anekakRt|अनेककृत्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-त्-त्-त्) Doing much (an epithet of Śiva). E. अनेक and कृत्.

anekakriyaa|अनेकक्रिया
Karmadh. f. (-या) A plurality of acts, of cognitions; e. g. न(एकं मनः)युगपदनेकक्रियोपलब्धेः ‘(the mind is) not (one), because it perceives more than one cognition’. E. अनेक and क्रिया.

anekaxetravyavachChedaka|अनेकक्षेत्रव्यवच्छेदक
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-दकः-दिका-दकम्) What separates several fields from one another (as a boundary or a piece of land common to both). E. अनेक-क्षेत्र and व्यवच्छेदक.

anekagotra|अनेकगोत्र
Bahuvr. m. (-त्रः) (In Law.) A boy who belongs to different i. e. to two families, viz. to that of his own and to that of his adopted father; comp. असमानगोत्र; e. g. सर्वत्रानेकगोत्राणामेकोद्दिष्टं क्षयेऽहनि. See also द्व्यामुष्यायण. E. अनेक and गोत्र.

anekaja|अनेकज
Tatpur. 1. m. f. n. (-जः-जा-जम्) Born more than once. BREAḲ. m. (-जः) A bird (viz. born in the shell and upon being hatched). E. अनेक and ज.

anekataa|अनेकता
f. (-ता) Muchness, multitudinousness. E. अनेक, taddh. aff. तल्.

anekatra|अनेकत्र
Tatpur. ind. In various places, in many respects; e. g. यद्यप्यनेकत्र सुराशब्दप्रयोगो दृश्यते &c. E. अ neg. and एकत्र.

anekatva|अनेकत्व
n. (-त्वम्) The same as अनेकता; e. g. प्रयत्नकार्यानेकत्वात्कार्यसमः. E. अनेक, taddh. aff. त्व. 

anekadharma|अनेकधर्म
Tatpur. m. (-र्मः) A property different from (those of something else); oppos. to समानधर्म; e. g. समानानेकधर्माध्यवसायादन्यतरधर्माध्यवसायाद्वा न संशयः. E. अनेक and धर्म.

anekadharmakathaa|अनेकधर्मकथा
Tatpur. f. (-था) A varied narrative or explanation of the doctrine (a definition of the Buddhistic works called Gáthá). E. अनेक and धर्म-कथा.

anekadhaa|अनेकधा
Tatpur. ind.<BR> ^1 In many ways; e. g. (रूपं) चक्षुषः सहकारि स्याच्छुक्लादिकमनेकधा.<BR> ^2 More than once, often; e. g. अनेकधा कृताः पुत्रा ऋषिभिर्ये पुरातनैः । न शक्यास्ते ऽधुना कंर्तुं शक्तिहीनतया नरैः. E. अ neg. and एकधा.

anekadhaaprayoga|अनेकधाप्रयोग
Tatpur. m. (-यः) Employing more than once, making use of or applying several times; e. g. संभ्रमेण प्रवृत्तौ यथेष्टमनेकधाप्रयोगो न्यायसिद्धः. E. अनेकधा and प्रयोग.

anekapa|अनेकप
Tatpur. m. (-पः) An elephant (lit. drinking in two ways, ‘with his trunk and with his mouth’). Compare द्विप.<BR> --In a Gańa list this word is mentioned as being a masc. or a neuter. E. अनेक and प.

anekapitRka|अनेकपितृक
Bahuvr. m. pl. (-काः) Grandsons of various fathers. E. अनेक and पितृ, samásánta aff. कप्.

anekapratipatti|अनेकप्रतिपत्ति
Tatpur. f. (-त्ति) The assumption of several (sc. bodies), the multiform incarnation (of the divinity). E. अनेक (sc. देह) and प्रतिपत्ति.

anekabhaarya|अनेकभार्य
Bahuvr. m. (-र्यः) A husband who has more than one or several wives. E. अनेक and भार्या.

anekamukha|अनेकमुख
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-खः-खा-खम्)<BR> ^1 Many-faced.<BR> ^2 Dispersed, going in various directions; e. g. जिते नृपारौ… वृद्धस्य राज्ञोऽनुमते बलानि जगाहिरेऽनेकमुखानि मार्गान् ‘when Paraśuráma was vanquished, with the leave of the old king Daśaratha the armies dispersed everywhere’. E. अनेक and मुख.

anekaruupa|अनेकरूप
I. Tatpur. n. (-पम्) Multiformity. <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-पः-पा-पम्)<BR> ^1 Multiform.<BR> ^2 Of various kinds or sorts.<BR> ^3 Fickle, of variable nature; e. g. वाराङ्गनेव नृपनीतिरनेकरूपा. E. अनेक and रूप.

anekaruupadhaaraNasaamarthya|अनेकरूपधारणसामर्थ्य
Tatpur. n. (र्थ्यम्) The power of assuming many forms, of multiform metamorphosis, Máyá. E. अनेकरूप-धारण and सामर्थ्य.

anekalochana|अनेकलोचन
Bahuvr. m. (-नः) A name of Śiva (lit. ‘having several i. e. three eyes’); comp. त्रिलोचन. E. अनेक and लोचन.

anekavarNaguNana|अनेकवर्णगुणन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) (In Arithmetic.) Multiplication of several unknown quantities. E. अनेक-वर्ण and गुणन.

anekavarNabhajana|अनेकवर्णभजन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) (In Arithmetic.) Division of several unknown quantities. E. अनेक-वर्ण and भजन.

anekavarNamadhyamaaharaNa|अनेकवर्णमध्यमाहरण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) (In Arithmetic.) Multiliteral quadratic equation, one whose solution involves the elimination of the middle term. E. अनेक-वर्ण and मध्यम (middle term) -आहरण (elimination).

anekavarNavyavakalana|अनेकवर्णव्यवकलन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) (In Arithmetic.) Subtraction of several unknown quantities. E. अनेक-वर्ण and व्यवकलन.

anekavarNaShaDvidha|अनेकवर्णषड्विध
Tatpur. n. (-धम्) (In Arithmetic.) The six arithmetical operations with several unknown quantities, viz. addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, involution and extraction of the square root. E. अनेक-वर्ण and षड्विध. 

anekavarNasankalana|अनेकवर्णसङ्कलन
Tatpur. n. (-नम्) (In Arithmetic.) Addition of several unknown quantities. E. अनेक-वर्ण and सङ्कलन.

anekavarNasamiikaraNa|अनेकवर्णसमीकरण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) (In Arithmetic.) Multiliteral equation, equation involving several unknown quantities, ‘where more than one unknown quantity represented severally by colours (equivalent to our x, y, z &c.) being premised, two sides are equated’. E. अनेक-वर्ण and समीकरण.

anekavaaram|अनेकवारम्
Tatpur. ind. Several times, frequently. E. अनेक and वार.

anekavidha|अनेकविध
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-धः-धा-धम्) Various, of many kinds, in different ways. E. अनेक and विध.

anekavidhatva|अनेकविधत्व
n. (-त्वम्) Manifoldedness, variety. E. अनेकविध, taddh. aff. त्व.

anekashapha|अनेकशफ
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-फः-फा-फम्) Cloven-hoofed. (Tame cloven-hoofed animals, if spoken of in general and provided the young be not meant, have usually the feminine gender; e. g. गाव इमाः, अजा इमाः.) E. अनेक and शफ.

anekashas|अनेकशस्
Tatpur. ind.<BR> ^1 In various manners; e. g. अनेकशो निर्जितराजकस्त्वम्.<BR> ^2 Several times, frequently; e. g. पुरुषान्तरसंक्रमणेन प्रयोगान्तरकरणे तस्मिन्नेव वा पुरुषेऽनेकशः प्रयोगान्तरकरणे सुवर्णादिकं द्वैगुण्याद्यतिक्रमस्य पूर्ववद्वर्धते.<BR> ^3 By large numbers or quantities; e. g. अनेकगोब्राह्मणमनुष्यबधान्मे पुत्रा अनेकशो मृता दाराश्च. E. अ neg. and एकशस्.

anekaakaara|अनेकाकार
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Multiform. E. अनेक and आकार.

anekaakin|अनेकाकिन्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-की-किनी-कि) Not alone, not solitary. E. अ neg. and एकाकिन्.

anekaaxara|अनेकाक्षर
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-रः-रा-रम्) Consisting of more than one syllable (as a word). E. अनेक and अक्षर.

anekaaxaraantya|अनेकाक्षरान्त्य
Tatpur. m. (-न्त्यः) The final letter of a word consisting of more than one syllable. E. अनेकाक्षर and अन्त्य, sc. वर्ण.

anekaach|अनेकाच्
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-च्-च्-च्) (In the terminology of Páńini.) Having more than one vowel (syllable), as a radical, a base &c. E. अनेक and अच् ‘vowel’.

anekaanta|अनेकान्त
Tatpur. m. (-न्तः)<BR> ^1 Unsettled condition, want of permanency, non-absoluteness--‘सर्वत्र यदवधारेणोच्यते स एकान्तः । यथा त्रिवृद्धि रेचपयति मदनफलं वामयतीति । क्वचित्तथा क्वचिदन्यथेति यः सोऽनेकान्तः’--.^2 Instability, indeterminateness, possibility; e. g. स्यादित्यनेकान्ते । स्याद्वादिनो जैनाः । स्यादपि न स्यादिति पक्षान्तरसंभावनादावपि.<BR> ^3 Uncertainty, uncertain occurrence (as of a rule); e. g. येषां चाप्यारभ्यते तेषामप्यनेकान्तः.<BR> ^4 An unessential part, f. i. of a word, as an Anubandha q. v.; e. g. अनेकान्ता अनुबन्धाः which is thus explained by Kaiyyat́a: एकान्त इति । एकदेश अवयव इत्यर्थः । अनेकान्तस्तूपलक्षणमेव केवलं यथा गृहस्य काकः ।. E. अ neg. and एकान्त.

anekaantatva|अनेकान्तत्व
n. (-त्वम्) Unsettledness, indeterminateness, uncertainty &c. See the preceding. E. अनेकान्त, taddh. aff. त्व.

anekaantavaada|अनेकान्तवाद
Tatpur. m. (-दः) Scepticism, maintaining that nothing is certain. E. अनेकान्त and वाद.

anekaantavaadin|अनेकान्तवादिन्
Tatpur. m. (-दी)<BR> ^1 An Arhat of the Jainas.<BR> ^2 A Jaina. E. अनेकान्त and वादिन् ‘lit. one who maintains the uncertainty as principle, a sceptic.

anekaartha|अनेकार्थ
I. Tatpur. m. (-र्थः) Multiplicity of objects, topics.  <BR>II. Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-र्थः-र्था-र्थम्)<BR> ^1 Having more than one object; e. g. अनेकार्थाभियोग.<BR> ^2 Having more than one meaning (as a word).<BR> ^3 Having the sense of the word अनेक; e. g. नाना विनोभयानेकार्थेषु ‘नाना has the sense of विना, उभय and अनेक. [The reading अनेकार्थ in the present edition of Suśruta 2. 559. line 2 is clearly a misprint for अनेकान्त; comp. ibid. 2. 556. line 7.]<BR>E. अनेक and अर्थ.

anekaarthadhvanimanjarii|अनेकार्थध्वनिमञ्जरी
Tatpur. n. (-री) The title of a little vocabulary in three chapters, containing words with their various meanings appended. More commonly designated as नानार्थध्वनिमञ्जरी. E. अनेकार्थ-ध्वनि and मञ्जरी.

anekaarthasangraha|अनेकार्थसङ्ग्रह
Tatpur. m. (-हः) The title of the second part of Hemachandra's vocabulary, containing words with their various meanings. E. अनेकार्थ and संग्रह.

anekaarthaabhiyukta|अनेकार्थाभियुक्त
Tatpur. m. (-क्तः) (In Law.) One charged on several counts. E. अनेकार्थ and अभियुक्त.

anekaarthaabhiyoga|अनेकार्थाभियोग
Karmadh. m. (-गः) (In Law.) A plaint, a charge implying different counts. E. अनेकार्थ and अभियोग.

anekaal|अनेकाल्
Bahuvr. m. (-ल्) (In the terminology of Páńini.) Consisting of more than one letter (as an आदेश q. v.). E. अनेक and अल् ‘a letter’.

anekaashraya|अनेकाश्रय
Tatpur. m. (-यः) Dependance upon more than one, abiding in more than one; according to the Vaiśeshika phil., the characteristic of the numerals from two upwards (and of the notions mentioned in the following article q. v.). E. अनेक and आश्रय.

anekaashrita|अनेकाश्रित
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Depending upon more than one, abiding in more than one; according to the Vaiśeshika phil. such dependance is the characteristic of the notion of conjunction (संयोग), of disjunction (विभाग), of separatedness prevailing between two or more things (द्विपृथक्त्वादि) and of the numerals from two upwards. See the preceding. E. अनेक and आश्रित.

anekiikaraNa|अनेकीकरण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) Making manifold, dividing into several portions; e. g. एकस्यानेकीकरणमनेकस्य वैकीकरणम्. E. अनेक, taddh. aff. च्वि and करण.

anekiibhavat|अनेकीभवत्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-न्-न्ती-त्) Becoming separated or disunited; e. g. words by hiatus or consonants; the reverse of संधीयमान, ‘combining or coalescing by means of Sandhi’. (See s. v. अनेक.) E. अनेक, taddh. aff. च्वि and भवत्.

anekiiya|अनेकीय
m. f. n. (-यः-या-यम्)<BR> ^1 Having more than one.<BR> ^2 Made by more than one.<BR> ^3 Inhabited by more than one.<BR> ^4 Not far from more than one. (It may be that this word is used only in one or another, instead of in all these meanings.) E. अनेक, taddh. aff. छ.

anekaikatvabuddhi|अनेकैकत्वबुद्धि
Tatpur. f. (-द्धिः) Comprehension of manifold unities (i. e. according to some, of unities from two upwards, according to others, from three upwards); in the Vaiśeshika phil. the characteristic of अपेक्षाबुद्धि q. v. E. अनेक-एकत्व and बुद्धि.

aneDa|अनेड
Tatpur. m. (-डः) A fool. E. अ compar. and एड.

aneDamuuka|अनेडमूक
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-कः-का-कम्)<BR> ^1 Deaf and dumb.<BR> ^2 Wicked, perverse.<BR> ^3 Blind(?). See एडमूक. E. अ compar. or explet. and एडमूक.

anetad|अनेतद्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-षः-षा-तद्) Not he, she, it; other than he, she, it. (The nomin. अनेषः does not loose its  Visarga when the uncompounded word would drop it; e. g. अनेषो ददाति, but एष ददाति. Before the taddh. aff. अकच् which is always placed before the inflection endings and cannot be made visible in the base itself, the feminine which in its uncompounded state would be either एषका or एषिका, is always अनेषका, whether the etym. be अ neg. and एषक i. e. एतद, taddh. aff. अकच् (Tatpur.) or अनेतद्, taddh, aff. अकच्.) E. अ neg. and एतद्.

anedya|अनेद्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-द्यः-द्या-द्यम्) (ved.) Blameless, praiseworthy, excellent; an epithet of the Maruts. Comp. अनिन्द्य. E. अ neg. and नेद्य (= निन्द्य).

anedyas|अनेद्यस्
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-द्याः-द्याः-द्यः) (ved.) Reaching far; अनेद्यः श्रवः ‘far spread fame’; according to Sáyańa also in the meaning of अनेद्य i. e. ‘excellent fame’. (The latter interpretation seems very doubtful.) E. अ neg. and नेद्यस् (probably a contracted form of नेदीयस्) lit. ‘not very near’.

anena|अनेन
Bahuvr. m. (-नः) A supreme lord, one who has no other king over himself (according to a quibbling interpretation of a passage of the Nalodaya). E. अन or अना and इन.

anenas|अनेनस्
Bahuvr. 1. m. f. n. (-नाः-नाः-नः) Sinless, faultless. अनेनस् neutr. acc. also used as adv. (The abstract noun is आनेनस्य q. v.) BREAḲ. m. (-नाः) A proper name of<BR> ^1 a son of Kakutstha and father of Pŕithu;<BR> ^2 a son of Sanjaya and father of Kshemári or Kshemadhi;<BR> ^3 a son of Áyus. E. अ priv. and एनस्.

aneman|अनेमन्
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-मा-मा-म) (ved.) Excellent, superior. E. अ priv. and नेमन्.

aneShakaa|अनेषका
see s. v. अनेतद्.

anehas|अनेहस्
Bahuvr. 1. m. f. n. (-हा-हा-हस्) (ved.) Free from sin or evil, free from obstruction. BREAḲ. m. (-हा) Time. (The nomin. of this word is अनेहा instead of अनेहाः.) E. अ neg. and एहस् q. v.

anaikaanta|अनैकान्त
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-न्तः-न्ता-न्तम्) The same as अनैकान्तिक q. v. E. अ neg. and ऐकान्त.

anaikaantika|अनैकान्तिक
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-कः-का-कम्) (In Philosophy.) Indeterminate, going astray, non-absolute.--In the Nyáya and Vaiśeshika philosophies a quality which constitutes one of the five हेत्वाभास (q. v.) or semblances of reason; in the Nyáya it is also called सव्यभिचार. A ‘semblance of reason’ ‘goes astray’ or is ‘indeterminate’, if the argument is either too general (साधारण) i. e. if it may be applied to the subject of conclusion and to an opposite one; e. g. ‘sound is eternal, because it is not the object of touch’ or ‘the hearth smokes, because it is fiery’; or not general enough (असाधारण) i. e. if it is excluded from either; e. g. ‘sound is eternal because it has the properties of sound’; or non-exclusive (अनुपसंहारिन्) i. e. if the major may be predicated of any other notion; e. g. ‘every thing is eternal because it can be measured’ or ‘every thing can be named because it can be inferred’. E. अ neg. and ऐकान्तिक.

anaikaantikatva|अनैकान्तिकत्व
n. (-त्वम्) Indeterminateness, uncertainty, nonabsoluteness. See the preceding; e. g. अर्थापत्तिरप्रमाणमनैकान्तिकत्वात् or ‘अनुक्तस्यार्थापत्तेः पक्षहानेरुपपत्तिरनुक्तत्वादनैकान्तिकत्वाच्चार्थापत्तेः’ or दुःखस्य निवृत्तेरदर्शनादनैकान्तिकत्वम्. E. अनैकान्तिक, taddh. aff. त्व. 

anaikya|अनैक्य
Tatpur. n. (-क्यम्)<BR> ^1 Plurality, the existence of many.<BR> ^2 Want of union, anarchy. E. अ neg. and ऐक्य.

anaipuNa|अनैपुण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) Clumsiness, uncleverness. See the following and आनैपुण. E. अ neg. and नैपुण.

anaipuNya|अनैपुण्य
Tatpur. n. (-ण्यम्) The same as the preceding. See also आनैपुण्य. E. अ neg. and नैपुण्य.

anaishvarya|अनैश्वर्य
Tatpur. n. (-र्यम्) Absence of power or supremacy; e. g. यस्मिन्ननैश्वर्यकृतव्यलीकः पराभवं प्राप्त इवान्तिकोऽपि. See also आनैश्वर्य. (For the meaning of this word in the Sánkhya-and Yoga-philosophies see s. v. ऐश्वर्य of which it is the reserve.) E. अ neg. and ऐश्वर्य.

ano|अनो
ind. No, not; also नो. E. Probably अन or अना and उ.

anokashaayin|अनोकशायिन्
Tatpur. m. (-यी) One who is in the habit of sleeping elsewhere than in a house (such as is occupied by a householder), a beggar who sleeps in empty dwellings, temples, potter's shops and such like places; e. g. अनोकशायी लघुरल्पप्रचारश्चरन्देशानेकचरः स भिक्षुः (a comm.: अनोकशायी शून्यागारदेवालयकुलालशालादौ गृहस्थागारभिन्ने स्थाने शायी). E. अ neg. -ओक (instead of ओकस्) and शायिन्.

anokaha|अनोकह
Tatpur. m. (-हः) A tree. The native E. is very improbable: अनस्-अक (going) and ह ‘because a tree impedes the progress of carts’; probably from अ neg. and ओक (instead of ओकस्; compare the preceding) and ह (from हा) ‘because it does not quit its house’.

anogha|अनोघ
Tatpur. m. (-घः) A technical term in the Sánkhya philosophy; the reverse of ओघ q. v. E. अ neg. and ओघ.

anonkRta|अनोङ्कृत
Bahuvr. m. f. n. (-तः-ता-तम्) Not accompanied with the Om-kára, with the mystical syllable Om (as the reading of the Veda). E. अ priv. and ओम्-कृत.

anovaahya|अनोवाह्य
Tatpur. m. f. n. (-ह्यः-ह्या-ह्यम्) Fit or worthy to be carried on a cart. E. अनस् and वाह्य.

anohaka|अनोहक
A various, but probably wrong reading for अनोकह q. v.

anauchitya|अनौचित्य
Tatpur. n. (-त्यम्) Unfitness, impropriety; e. g. अनौचित्यप्रवृत्तत्व आभासो रसभावयोः &c. E. अ neg. and औचित्य.

anaujasya|अनौजस्य
Tatpur. n. (-स्यम्) Want of strength, want of energy; e. g. दौर्गत्याद्यैरनौजस्यं दैन्यं मलिनतादिकृत्. E. अ neg. and औजस्य.

anauddhatya|अनौद्धत्य
Tatpur. n. (-त्यम्) Modesty, humility. E. अ neg. and औद्धत्य.

anaurasa|अनौरस
Tatpur. m. (-सः) Adopted (as a son). E. अ neg. and औरस.

ant|अन्त्
r. 1st cl. par. (अन्ततिआनत्-आनन्त-अन्तिता.--Caus. अन्तयति-आन्तितत्.-Desid. अन्तितिषति.) To bind. (According to Dhanapála this radical is a provincialism of the Dravid́as instead of the classical अन्द् q. v. which occurs also in the variety of ईन्त्; Maitreya, Káśyapa and others admit of both, अन्त् and अन्द्, as classical forms.)

anta|अन्त
I. m. (-न्तः)<BR> ^1 End.<BR> ^2 Term, termination; e. g. कूपान्तः ‘the bottom of a well’.<BR> ^3 Limit, boundary, border.<BR> ^4 A place in general (comp. अन्तर); e. g. वनान्तः (explained as वनभूमि) ‘a place in the forest, or the forest-ground’.<BR> ^5 Part, portion; e. g. एकान्ता अनुबन्धाः (‘एकान्त इत्येकदेशो ऽवयव इत्यर्थः’) ‘anubandhas are essential portions of a word’  (comp. अनेकान्त); or अथवायमन्तशब्दोऽस्त्येवावयववाची । तद्यथा । वस्त्रान्तो वसनान्त इति, as Patanjali comments on Páńini VIII. 4. 20.<BR> ^6 End, completion; e. g. पशुबन्धान्तमधीते ‘he reads (the work) as far as and inclusive of the chapter on the tying of the victim’; or स्वप्नान्त Tatpur. ‘profound sleep’, Bahuvr. ‘in profound sleep’.<BR> ^7 End of life, death.<BR> ^8 End, separation (comp. अन्तर); e. g. मैत्रेयीति होवाच याज्ञवल्क्य उद्यास्यन्वा अरेऽहमस्मात्स्थानादस्मि । हन्त ते ऽनया कात्यायन्यान्तं करवाणीति ‘o Maitreyí, quoth Yájnavalkya, I am about to leave this place; hence with thy consent I shall make a separation between (thee and my other wife) the daughter of Kátyáyana’.<BR> ^9 (In Grammar.) The final letter of a word.<BR> ^10 (In Grammar.) The last part of a compound.<BR> ^11 (In Grammar.) A pause.<BR> ^12 Proximity, vicinity; e. g. उदकान्तं गतः; or आचार्यस्य वसेदन्ते.<BR> ^13 Presence; e. g. जायाया अन्ते नाश्नीयात् (= न भार्यादर्शनेऽश्नीयात्).<BR> ^14 Positive conclusion, ascertainment. <BR>II. n. (-न्तम्) Nature, disposition, essence. <BR>III. m. n. (-न्तः-न्तम्)<BR> ^1 The last portion, the remainder; compare अन्तर.<BR> ^2 Last; e. g. अन्ते वयसि ‘in the last stage of life’. [According to a comm. on the Amarak. अन्त ‘last’ remains masc. or neuter even when it is the attribute of a feminine (‘स्त्रीविशेषणत्वेऽपि स्त्रीलिङ्गतानिषेधः । तत्र पुंनपुंसकलिङ्गतैव’).]<BR>IV. m. f. n. (-न्तः-न्ता-न्तम्)<BR> ^1 Lowest, worst.<BR> ^2 Last born, youngest.<BR> ^3 Near (compare अन्तम and अन्तिक).<BR> ^4 Handsome, beautiful. (For this last meaning, given on the authority of Viśwa, the only instance--quoted also by the Śabdamuktámahárńava--which has occurred to me, is that of Mágha's Śiśupálabadha 4. 40. where the last part of the compound विमलोपलमेखलान्ताः is explained by the comm. on the authority of the Śabdárńava अन्ताः = रम्याः; yet as this meaning admits of no connexion with any of the other meanings of अन्त, it seems preferable to analyze the compound in ºमेखला-आन्ताः, when आन्त could be taken as the participle (comp. Páńini VII. 2. 28.) of अम् ‘संभक्तौ’ in the sense of भक्त ‘attached, served’; and this interpretation is the more probable, as the verse in question exhibits a permanent punning on words which either may be applied to women or to objects of nature, and as आन्त would then correspond with भजन्ति in the next line. E. अम्, uń. aff. तन् or according to others, from अन्त्, kŕit aff. अच् or घञ्. Both etym. are not satisfactory; perhaps the origin of अन्त is in the elements of which the accus. plural is composed; see the Preface.

antaHkaraNa|अन्तःकरण
Tatpur. n. (-णम्) (In Philosophy.)<BR> ^1 The interior sense (also called आभ्यन्तरकरण) opposed to the वाह्यकरण (q. v.) or exterior sense; this notion which in general may be termed ‘the faculty of thinking’ is thus modified in the Vedánta and in the Sánkhya:<BR> ^a (In the Vedánta it implies) the notion of what is the general substratum of आत्मन् or Soul (Śankara: तच्चात्मन उपाधिभूतमन्तःकरणम्); its activity becomes manifest in two of the seventeen सूक्ष्मशरीर (q. v.) or subtle bodies of creation, viz. in the बुद्धि (q. v.) or that mental activity which forms positive conclusions, and in the मनस्, or that mental activity which ‘discerns and doubts’;  and as चित्त or ‘logical combination’ is involved by the activity of बुद्धि, and अहङ्कार or ‘self-consciousness’ is involved by मनस्, the activity of the अन्तःकरण is fourfold, viz. as that of बुद्धि, मनस्, चित्त and अहङ्कार. Śankara in his commentary on the Vedánta Sútras varies slightly in this respect by substituting विज्ञान for अहङ्कार; the difference however is merely apparent, विज्ञान, worldly knowledge, being also one of the attributes of मनस् (Śankara: ‘अन्तःकरणं मनो बुद्धिर्विज्ञानं चित्तमिति चानेकधा तत्र तत्राभिलप्यते’).<BR> ^b. (In the Sánkhya it is not the substratum of पुरुष or Soul but) the generic name and characteristic of three successive productions of प्रकृति or Matter, viz. of बुद्धि ‘ascertainment or positive conclusion’, of its product अहङ्कार self-consciousness’ and of the product of Ahankára, viz. मनस् which in this philosophy means ‘an organ both of sensation and of action’ (see बुद्धीन्द्रिय and कर्मेन्द्रिय), ‘the organ of volition’ (see सङ्कल्प). ‘The ten external organs (viz the five organs of sensation and the five of action) supply the objects for the ‘interior sense’, their time is the present time, while the interior sense embraces the past, present and future time’.<BR> ^2 (In the non-philosophical literature where philosophical terms are usually employed in a vague manner, this word means) Mind, heart, feeling, a synonyme of मनस् in its vague, unphilosophical sense; e. g. (in a verse of the Málatímádhava where an apparent show is made of philosophical accuracy) प्रेमार्द्राः प्रणयस्पृशः…चेष्टा भवेयुर्मयि । यास्वन्तःकरणस्य वाह्यकरणव्यापाररोधीक्षणादाशंसापरिकल्पितास्वपि भवत्यानन्दसान्द्रोदयः (var. lect. ºसान्द्रो लयः)--E. अन्तर् and करण.

antaHkaraNavRtti|अन्तःकरणवृत्ति
Tatpur. f. (-त्तिः) The activity of the अन्तःकरण q. v. E. अन्तःकरण and वृत्ति.

antaHkalpa|अन्तःकल्प
Tatpur. m. (-ल्पः) A cycle of the Buddhistic era. ‘From the time that man's age increases from ten years to an Asankhya and again decreases from an Asankhya to ten years, is an Antah́kalpa. Were the surface of the earth to increase in elevation at the rate of one inch in a 1000 years and the process to continue in the same proportion, the elevation would extend to 28 miles before the Antah́kalpa would be concluded. Twenty Antah́kalpas make an Asankhyakalpa. Four Asankhyakalpas make a Mahákalpa.’ (Hardy, Manual of Buddhism.) E. अन्तर् and कल्प.

antaHkuTila|अन्तःकुटिल
Tatpur. 1. m. f. n. (-लः-ला-लम्) Crookedminded, fraudulent, dishonest. BREAḲ. m. (-लः) A conch shell. (See शङ्ख.) E. अन्तर् and कुटिल.

antaHkRmi|अन्तःकृमि
Tatpur. m. (-मिः) (In Medicine.) Worms in the body (a disease). E. अन्तर् and कृमि.

antaHkoTharapuShpii|अन्तःकोठरपुष्पी
